1
00:00:00,019 --> 00:00:06,720
At the gleams of new daylight which they
let in my thoughts went to the clump of

2
00:00:06,720 --> 00:00:17,682
cottonwoods, and I lay still with hands
and feet growing steadily cold.

3
00:00:17,682 --> 00:00:29,003
Now it was going to happen.

4
00:00:32,429 --> 00:00:39,782
I wondered how they would do it;
one instance had been described to me by

5
00:00:39,782 --> 00:00:49,113
a witness, but that was done from a
bridge, and there had been

6
00:00:49,113 --> 00:00:52,515
but a single victim.

7
00:00:52,515 --> 00:01:01,708
This morning, would one have to wait and
see the other go through with it first?

8
00:01:01,708 --> 00:01:10,551
The smell of smoke reached me,
and next the rattle of tin dishes.

9
00:01:10,551 --> 00:01:23,320
Breakfast was something I had forgotten,
and one of them was cooking it now in

10
00:01:23,320 --> 00:01:28,132
the dry shelter of the stable.

11
00:01:28,132 --> 00:01:38,690
He was alone, because the talking and the
steps were outside the stable,

12
00:01:38,690 --> 00:01:46,144
and I could hear the sounds of horses
being driven into the corral and

13
00:01:46,144 --> 00:01:48,384
saddled.

14
00:01:48,384 --> 00:01:54,145
Then I perceived that the coffee was
ready, and almost immediately

15
00:01:54,145 --> 00:01:57,465
the cook called them.

16
00:01:57,465 --> 00:02:07,425
One came in, shutting the door behind him
as he reentered, which the rest as they

17
00:02:07,425 --> 00:02:14,259
followed imitated; for at each opening
of the door I saw the light of day leap

18
00:02:14,259 --> 00:02:22,289
into the stable and heard the louder
sounds of the rain.

19
00:02:22,289 --> 00:02:31,752
Then the sound and the light would again
be shut out, until someone at length

20
00:02:31,752 --> 00:02:46,242
spoke out bluntly, bidding the door be
left open on account of the smoke.

21
00:02:46,242 --> 00:02:50,644
What were they hiding from?

22
00:02:50,644 --> 00:02:52,434
he asked.

23
00:02:52,434 --> 00:02:55,473
The runaways that had escaped?

24
00:02:55,473 --> 00:03:02,536
A laugh followed this sally,
and the door was left open.

25
00:03:02,536 --> 00:03:11,136
Thus I learned that there had been more
thieves than the two that were captured.

26
00:03:11,136 --> 00:03:21,808
It gave a little more ground for their
suspicion about me and my anxiety to

27
00:03:21,808 --> 00:03:26,054
pass the night elsewhere.

28
00:03:26,054 --> 00:03:30,837
It cost nothing to detain me,
and they were taking

29
00:03:30,837 --> 00:03:35,287
no chances, however remote.

30
00:03:35,287 --> 00:03:40,467
The fresh air and the light now filled
the stable, and I lay listening while

31
00:03:40,467 --> 00:03:45,662
their breakfast brought
more talk from them.

32
00:03:45,662 --> 00:03:52,626
They were more at ease now than was I,
who had nothing to do but carry out my

33
00:03:52,626 --> 00:03:59,206
role of slumber in the stall;
they spoke in a friendly,

34
00:03:59,206 --> 00:04:05,595
ordinary way, as if this were like every
other morning of the week to them.

35
00:04:05,595 --> 00:04:13,498
They addressed the prisoners with a sort
of fraternal kindness,

36
00:04:13,498 --> 00:04:22,196
not bringing them pointedly into the
conversation, nor yet

37
00:04:22,196 --> 00:04:25,836
pointedly leaving them out.

38
00:04:25,836 --> 00:04:33,518
I made out that they must all be sitting
round the breakfast together,

39
00:04:33,518 --> 00:04:41,279
those who had to die and those who
had to kill them.

40
00:04:41,279 --> 00:04:46,151
The Virginian I never heard speak.

41
00:04:46,151 --> 00:04:55,630
But I heard the voice of Steve;
he discussed with his captors the sundry

42
00:04:55,630 --> 00:04:58,411
points of his capture.

43
00:04:58,411 --> 00:05:01,868
“Do you remember a haystack?”

44
00:05:01,868 --> 00:05:03,490
he asked.

45
00:05:03,490 --> 00:05:10,678
“Away up the south fork of Gros Ventre?”

46
00:05:10,678 --> 00:05:16,595
“That was Thursday afternoon,”
said one of the captors.

47
00:05:16,595 --> 00:05:19,032
“There was a shower.”

48
00:05:19,032 --> 00:05:20,016
“Yes.

49
00:05:20,016 --> 00:05:21,456
It rained.

50
00:05:21,456 --> 00:05:27,736
We had you fooled that time.

51
00:05:27,736 --> 00:05:39,537
I was laying on the ledge above
to report your movements.”

52
00:05:39,537 --> 00:05:43,298
Several of them laughed.

53
00:05:43,298 --> 00:05:49,596
“We thought you were over
on Spread Creek then.”

54
00:05:49,596 --> 00:05:58,367
“I figured you thought so by the trail
you left after the stack.

55
00:05:58,367 --> 00:06:10,978
Saturday we watched you turn your back on
us up Spread Creek.

56
00:06:10,978 --> 00:06:17,610
We were snug among the trees the other
side of Snake River.

57
00:06:17,610 --> 00:06:22,431
That was another time we had you fooled.”

58
00:06:22,431 --> 00:06:28,296
They laughed again at their own expense.

59
00:06:28,296 --> 00:06:40,489
I have heard men pick to pieces a hand of
whist with more antagonism.

60
00:06:40,489 --> 00:06:47,952
Steve continued: “Would we head for Idaho?

61
00:06:47,952 --> 00:06:58,991
Would we swing back over the Divide?

62
00:06:58,991 --> 00:07:02,515
You didn’t know which!

63
00:07:02,515 --> 00:07:09,798
And when we generalled you on to that
band of horses you thought was the band

64
00:07:09,798 --> 00:07:17,815
you were hunting⁠—ah,
we were a strong combination!”

65
00:07:17,815 --> 00:07:25,019
He broke off with the first touch of
bitterness I had felt in his words.

66
00:07:25,019 --> 00:07:29,681
“Nothing is any stronger
than its weakest point.”

67
00:07:29,681 --> 00:07:36,091
It was the Virginian who said this,
and it was the first word he had spoken.

68
00:07:36,091 --> 00:07:39,022
“Naturally,” said Steve.

69
00:07:39,022 --> 00:07:45,557
His tone in addressing the Virginian was
so different, so curt,

70
00:07:45,557 --> 00:07:56,823
that I supposed he took the weakest
point to mean himself.

71
00:07:56,823 --> 00:08:04,380
But the others now showed me that I was
wrong in this explanation.

72
00:08:04,380 --> 00:08:08,031
“That’s so,” one said.

73
00:08:08,031 --> 00:08:14,642
“Its weakest point is where a rope or a
gang of men is going to break

74
00:08:14,642 --> 00:08:18,413
when the strain comes.

75
00:08:18,413 --> 00:08:23,243
And you was linked with
a poor partner, Steve.”

76
00:08:23,243 --> 00:08:27,643
“You’re right I was,”
said the prisoner, back in

77
00:08:27,643 --> 00:08:32,275
his easy, casual voice.

78
00:08:32,275 --> 00:08:40,748
“You ought to have got yourself
separated from him, Steve.”

79
00:08:40,748 --> 00:08:45,686
There was a pause.

80
00:08:45,686 --> 00:08:50,285
“Yes,” said the prisoner, moodily.

81
00:08:50,285 --> 00:08:54,965
“I’m sitting here because
one of us blundered.”

82
00:08:54,965 --> 00:08:59,115
He cursed the blunderer.

83
00:08:59,115 --> 00:09:05,720
“Lighting his fool fire queered the
whole deal,” he added.

84
00:09:05,720 --> 00:09:15,200
As he again heavily cursed the blunderer,
the others murmured to each other

85
00:09:15,200 --> 00:09:19,012
various I told you so’s.

86
00:09:19,012 --> 00:09:29,019
“You’d never have built that
fire, Steve,” said one.

87
00:09:34,297 --> 00:09:44,149
“I said that when we spied
the smoke,” said another.

88
00:09:44,149 --> 00:09:50,309
“I said, ‘That’s none of Steve’s work,
lighting fires and revealing

89
00:09:50,309 --> -1:59:59,000
to us their whereabouts.’

90
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

91
00:09:56,359 --> 00:10:01,950
It struck me that they were
plying Steve with compliments.

92
00:10:01,950 --> 00:10:13,603
“Pretty hard to have the fool get away
and you get caught,” a third suggested.

93
00:10:14,065 --> 00:10:17,386
At this they seemed to wait.

94
00:10:17,386 --> 00:10:23,585
I felt something curious in
all this last talk.

95
00:10:23,585 --> 00:10:28,257
“Oh, did he get away?”

96
00:10:28,257 --> 00:10:32,310
said the prisoner, then.

97
00:10:32,310 --> 00:10:43,041
Again they waited; and a
new voice spoke huskily:⁠—

98
00:10:43,041 --> 00:10:49,091
“I built that fire, boys.”

99
00:10:49,211 --> 00:10:53,091
It was the prisoner in
the gray flannel shirt.

100
00:10:53,091 --> 00:10:58,191
“Too late, Ed,” they told him kindly.

101
00:10:58,191 --> 00:11:02,614
“You ain’t a good liar.”

102
00:11:02,614 --> 00:11:07,612
“What makes you laugh, Steve?”

103
00:11:07,612 --> 00:11:11,898
said someone.

104
00:11:11,898 --> 00:11:18,483
“Oh, the things I notice.”

105
00:11:18,483 --> 00:11:24,044
“Meaning Ed was pretty slow in
backing up your play?

106
00:11:24,044 --> 00:11:27,683
The joke is really on you, Steve.

107
00:11:27,683 --> 00:11:34,403
You’d ought never to have cursed the
fire-builder if you wanted us to

108
00:11:34,403 --> 00:11:37,766
believe he was present.

109
00:11:37,766 --> 00:11:48,685
But we’d not have done much to Shorty,
even if we had caught him.

110
00:11:48,685 --> 00:11:58,501
All he wants is to be scared good and
hard, and he’ll go back into

111
00:11:58,501 --> 00:12:07,222
virtuousness, which is his nature when
not travelling with Trampas.”

112
00:12:07,222 --> 00:12:12,133
Steve’s voice sounded hard now.

113
00:12:12,133 --> 00:12:17,403
“You have caught Ed and me.

114
00:12:17,403 --> 00:12:23,163
That should satisfy you for one gather.”

115
00:12:23,163 --> 00:12:29,143
“Well, we think different, Steve.

116
00:12:29,143 --> 00:12:37,618
Trampas escaping leaves
this thing unfinished.”

117
00:12:37,618 --> 00:12:42,861
“So Trampas escaped too, did he?”

118
00:12:42,861 --> 00:12:45,021
said the prisoner.

119
00:12:45,021 --> 00:12:54,676
“Yes, Steve, Trampas escaped⁠—this time;
and Shorty with him⁠—this time.

120
00:12:54,676 --> 00:13:01,513
We know it most as well as if
we’d seen them go.

121
00:13:01,513 --> 00:13:08,927
And we’re glad Shorty is loose,
for he’ll build another fire or

122
00:13:08,927 --> 00:13:11,607
do some other foolishness

123
00:13:11,607 --> -1:59:59,000
next time

124
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
,

125
00:13:13,268 --> 00:13:13,447
and

126
00:13:13,447 --> 00:13:18,612
that’s the time we’ll get Trampas.”

127
00:13:18,612 --> 00:13:27,353
Their talk drifted to other points,
and I lay thinking of the skirmish that

128
00:13:27,353 --> 00:13:34,314
had played beneath the
surface of their banter.

129
00:13:34,314 --> 00:13:41,577
Yes, the joke, as they put
it, was on Steve.

130
00:13:41,577 --> 00:13:48,410
He had lost one point in the game to them.

131
00:13:48,410 --> 00:13:55,250
They were playing for names.

132
00:13:55,250 --> 00:14:06,566
He, being a chivalrous thief,
was playing to hide names.

133
00:14:06,566 --> 00:14:19,085
They could only, among several likely
confederates, guess Trampas and Shorty.

134
00:14:19,085 --> 00:14:25,826
So it had been a slip for him to curse
the man who built the fire.

135
00:14:25,826 --> 00:14:29,349
At least, they so held it.

136
00:14:29,349 --> 00:14:37,452
For, they with subtlety reasoned,
one curses the absent.

137
00:14:37,452 --> 00:14:43,825
And I agreed with them that Ed did not
know how to lie well;

138
00:14:43,825 --> 00:14:52,886
he should have at once claimed the
disgrace of having spoiled

139
00:14:52,886 --> 00:14:56,427
the expedition.

140
00:14:56,427 --> 00:15:05,230
If Shorty was the blunderer,
then certainly Trampas was the other

141
00:15:05,230 --> 00:15:17,925
man; for the two were as inseparable
as don and master.

142
00:15:17,925 --> 00:15:26,258
Trampas had enticed Shorty away from
good, and trained him in evil.

143
00:15:26,258 --> 00:15:34,460
It now struck me that after his single
remark the Virginian had been silent

144
00:15:34,460 --> 00:15:38,980
throughout their shrewd discussion.

145
00:15:38,980 --> 00:15:46,613
It was the other prisoner that I
heard them next address.

146
00:15:46,613 --> 00:15:52,400
“You don’t eat any breakfast, Ed.”

147
00:15:52,400 --> 00:15:55,576
“Brace up, Ed.

148
00:15:55,576 --> 00:16:00,399
Look at Steve, how hardy he eats!”

149
00:16:00,399 --> 00:16:08,552
But Ed, it seemed, wanted no breakfast.

150
00:16:08,552 --> 00:16:14,367
And the tin dishes rattled as they were
gathered and taken to be packed.

151
00:16:14,367 --> 00:16:19,660
“Drink this coffee, anyway,”
another urged; “you’ll feel warmer.”

152
00:16:19,660 --> 00:16:22,860
These words almost made it seem
like my own execution.

153
00:16:22,860 --> 00:16:28,683
My whole body turned cold in company with
the prisoner’s, and as if with a clank

154
00:16:28,683 --> 00:16:32,263
the situation tightened
throughout my senses.

155
00:16:32,263 --> 00:16:35,100
“I reckon if everyone’s
ready we’ll start.”

156
00:16:35,100 --> 00:16:38,885
It was the Virginian’s voice once more,
and different from the rest.

157
00:16:38,885 --> 00:16:42,645
I heard them rise at his bidding,
and I put the blanket over my head.

158
00:16:42,645 --> 00:16:46,470
I felt their tread as they walked
out, passing my stall.

159
00:16:46,470 --> 00:16:51,950
The straw that was half under me and half
out in the stable was stirred as by

160
00:16:51,950 --> 00:16:55,238
something heavy dragged or half
lifted along over it.

161
00:16:55,238 --> 00:16:59,330
“Look out, you’re hurting Ed’s arm,”
one said to another,

162
00:16:59,330 --> 00:17:02,810
as the steps with tangled
sounds passed slowly out.

163
00:17:02,810 --> 00:17:06,730
I heard another among those who followed
say, “Poor Ed couldn’t

164
00:17:06,730 --> 00:17:08,031
swallow his coffee.”

165
00:17:08,031 --> 00:17:11,410
Outside they began getting on their
horses; and next their hoofs grew

166
00:17:11,410 --> 00:17:16,594
distant, until all was silence round the
stable except the dull,

167
00:17:16,594 --> 00:17:20,474
even falling of the rain.

168
00:17:20,474 --> 00:17:22,274
CHAPTER XXXI

169
00:17:22,274 --> 00:17:23,564
The Cottonwoods

170
00:17:23,564 --> 00:17:25,889
I do not know how long
I stayed there alone.

171
00:17:25,889 --> 00:17:29,614
It was the Virginian who came back,
and as he stood at the foot of my

172
00:17:29,614 --> 00:17:35,633
blankets his eye, after meeting mine
full for a moment, turned aside.

173
00:17:35,633 --> 00:17:40,391
I had never seen him look as he did now,
not even in Pitchstone Canyon when we

174
00:17:40,391 --> 00:17:42,732
came upon the bodies of
Hank and his wife.

175
00:17:42,732 --> 00:17:47,198
Until this moment we had found no chance
of speaking together,

176
00:17:47,198 --> 00:17:51,555
except in the presence of others.

177
00:17:51,555 --> 00:17:54,933
“Seems to be raining still,”
I began after a little.

178
00:17:54,933 --> 00:17:55,648
“Yes.

179
00:17:55,648 --> 00:17:56,942
It’s a wet spell.”

180
00:17:56,942 --> 00:18:00,201
He stared out of the door,
smoothing his mustache.

181
00:18:00,201 --> 00:18:02,229
It was again I that spoke.

182
00:18:02,229 --> 00:18:03,920
“What time is it?”

183
00:18:03,920 --> 00:18:05,891
He brooded over his watch.

184
00:18:05,891 --> -1:59:59,000
“Twelve minutes to seven.

185
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

186
00:18:10,324 --> 00:18:14,016
I rose and stood drawing on my clothes.

187
00:18:14,016 --> 00:18:17,487
“The fire’s out,” said he;
and he assembled some new

188
00:18:17,487 --> 00:18:19,138
sticks over the ashes.

189
00:18:19,138 --> 00:18:21,261
Presently he looked round with a cup.

190
00:18:21,261 --> 00:18:24,157
“Never mind that for me,” I said.

191
00:18:24,157 --> 00:18:27,007
“We’ve a long ride,” he suggested.

192
00:18:27,007 --> 00:18:28,757
“I know.

193
00:18:28,757 --> 00:18:30,811
I’ve crackers in my pocket.”

194
00:18:30,811 --> 00:18:33,677
My boots being pulled on,
I walked to the door

195
00:18:33,677 --> 00:18:35,080
and watched the clouds.

196
00:18:35,080 --> 00:18:37,506
“They seem as if they might lift,” I said.

197
00:18:37,506 --> 00:18:39,348
And I took out my watch.

198
00:18:39,348 --> 00:18:41,090
“What time is it?”

199
00:18:41,090 --> 00:18:41,720
he asked.

200
00:18:41,720 --> 00:18:43,412
“A quarter of⁠—it’s run down.”

201
00:18:43,412 --> 00:18:46,295
While I wound it he seemed to
be consulting his own.

202
00:18:46,295 --> 00:18:47,092
“Well?”

203
00:18:47,092 --> 00:18:48,087
I inquired.

204
00:18:48,087 --> 00:18:49,740
“Ten minutes past seven.”

205
00:18:49,740 --> 00:18:52,540
As I was setting my watch he slowly said:

206
00:18:52,540 --> 00:18:54,501
“Steve wound his all regular.

207
00:18:54,501 --> 00:18:56,407
I had to night-guard him till two.”

208
00:18:56,407 --> 00:18:59,321
His speech was like that of one in a
trance: so, at least,

209
00:18:59,321 --> 00:19:01,441
it sounds in my memory today.

210
00:19:01,441 --> 00:19:05,849
Again I looked at the weather and the
rainy immensity of the plain.

211
00:19:05,849 --> 00:19:09,628
The foothills eastward where we were
going were a soft yellow.

212
00:19:09,628 --> 00:19:15,094
Over the gray-green sagebrush moved
shapeless places of light⁠—not yet the

213
00:19:15,094 --> 00:19:19,751
uncovered sunlight, but spots where the
storm was wearing thin;

214
00:19:19,751 --> 00:19:23,686
and wandering streams of warmth passed
by slowly in the surrounding air.

215
00:19:23,686 --> 00:19:29,210
As I watched the clouds and the earth,
my eyes chanced to fall on the

216
00:19:29,210 --> 00:19:31,458
distant clump of cottonwoods.

217
00:19:31,458 --> 00:19:35,841
Vapors from the enfeebled storm floated
round them, and they were indeed far

218
00:19:35,841 --> 00:19:39,794
away; but I came inside and began
rolling up my blankets.

219
00:19:39,794 --> 00:19:41,914
“You will not change your mind?”

220
00:19:41,914 --> 00:19:43,992
said the Virginian by the fire.

221
00:19:43,992 --> 00:19:46,270
“It is thirty-five miles.”

222
00:19:46,270 --> 00:19:51,928
I shook my head, feeling a certain shame
that he should see how unnerved I was.

223
00:19:51,928 --> 00:19:56,107
He swallowed a hot cupful,
and after it sat thinking;

224
00:19:56,107 --> 00:20:01,439
and presently he passed his hand across
his brow, shutting his eyes.

225
00:20:01,439 --> 00:20:06,352
Again he poured out a cup,
and emptying this, rose abruptly to his

226
00:20:06,352 --> 00:20:09,078
feet as if shaking himself
free from something.

227
00:20:09,078 --> 00:20:12,035
“Let’s pack and quit here,” he said.

228
00:20:12,035 --> 00:20:16,453
Our horses were in the corral and our
belongings in the shelter of what had

229
00:20:16,453 --> 00:20:20,416
been once the cabin at
this forlorn place.

230
00:20:20,416 --> 00:20:23,710
He collected them in silence while I
saddled my own animal,

231
00:20:23,710 --> 00:20:28,635
and in silence we packed the two
packhorses, and threw the diamond hitch,

232
00:20:28,635 --> 00:20:31,455
and hauled tight the slack, damp ropes.

233
00:20:31,455 --> 00:20:35,415
Soon we had mounted, and as we turned
into the trail I gave a look back at

234
00:20:35,415 --> 00:20:36,935
my last night’s lodging.

235
00:20:36,935 --> 00:20:39,295
The Virginian noticed me.

236
00:20:39,295 --> 00:20:41,095
“Goodbye forever!”

237
00:20:41,095 --> 00:20:42,655
he interpreted.

238
00:20:42,655 --> 00:20:44,175
“By God, I hope so!”

239
00:20:44,175 --> 00:20:46,525
“Same here,” he confessed.

240
00:20:46,525 --> 00:20:50,828
And these were our first
natural words this morning.

241
00:20:50,828 --> 00:20:54,110
“This will go well,” said I,
holding my flask out to him;

242
00:20:54,110 --> 00:20:58,017
and both of us took some,
and felt easier for it

243
00:20:58,017 --> 00:20:59,721
and the natural words.

244
00:20:59,721 --> 00:21:04,453
For an hour we had been shirking real
talk, holding fast to the weather,

245
00:21:04,453 --> 00:21:08,712
or anything, and all the while that
silent thing we were keeping off spoke

246
00:21:08,712 --> 00:21:12,991
plainly in the air around us and in
every syllable that we uttered.

247
00:21:12,991 --> 00:21:16,539
But now we were going to get away from
it; leave it behind in the stable,

248
00:21:16,539 --> 00:21:19,341
and set ourselves free from it
by talking it out.

249
00:21:19,341 --> 00:21:23,397
Already relief had begun to
stir in my spirits.

250
00:21:23,397 --> 00:21:26,175
“You never did this before,” I said.

251
00:21:26,175 --> 00:21:26,774
“No.

252
00:21:26,774 --> 00:21:29,842
I never had it to do.”

253
00:21:29,842 --> 00:21:33,374
He was riding beside me,
looking down at his saddle-horn.

254
00:21:33,374 --> 00:21:36,214
“I do not think I should ever
be able,” I pursued.

255
00:21:36,214 --> 00:21:38,414
Defiance sounded in his answer.

256
00:21:38,414 --> 00:21:40,103
“I would do it again this morning.”

257
00:21:40,103 --> 00:21:41,944
“Oh, I don’t mean that.

258
00:21:41,944 --> 00:21:43,229
It’s all right here.

259
00:21:43,229 --> -1:59:59,000
There’s no other way.

260
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

261
00:21:44,521 --> 00:21:46,784
“I would do it all over again
the same this morning.

262
00:21:46,784 --> -1:59:59,000
Just the same.

263
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

264
00:21:48,975 --> 00:21:52,392
“Why, so should I⁠—if I could
do it at all.”

265
00:21:52,392 --> 00:21:56,239
I still thought he was justifying
their justice to me.

266
00:21:56,239 --> 00:22:00,263
He made no answer as he rode along,
looking all the while at his saddle.

267
00:22:00,263 --> 00:22:05,217
But again he passed his hand over his
forehead with that frown and

268
00:22:05,217 --> 00:22:07,137
shutting of the eyes.

269
00:22:07,137 --> 00:22:11,537
“I should like to be sure I should behave
myself if I were condemned,” I said

270
00:22:11,537 --> 00:22:12,082
next.

271
00:22:12,082 --> 00:22:15,480
For it now came to me⁠—
which should I resemble?

272
00:22:15,480 --> 00:22:19,132
Could I read the newspaper,
and be interested in county elections,

273
00:22:19,132 --> 00:22:22,531
and discuss coming death as if I had
lost a game of cards?

274
00:22:22,531 --> 00:22:25,132
Or would they have to drag me out?

275
00:22:25,132 --> 00:22:28,488
That poor wretch in the gray flannel
shirt⁠—“It was bad in the

276
00:22:28,488 --> 00:22:31,730
stable,” I said aloud.

277
00:22:31,730 --> 00:22:33,904
For an after-shiver of it went through me.

278
00:22:33,904 --> 00:22:38,681
A third time his hand brushed his
forehead, and I ventured some sympathy.

279
00:22:38,681 --> 00:22:41,003
“I’m afraid your head aches.”

280
00:22:41,003 --> 00:22:44,123
“I don’t want to keep
seeing Steve,” he muttered.

281
00:22:44,123 --> 00:22:44,883
“Steve!”

282
00:22:44,883 --> 00:22:46,386
I was astounded.

283
00:22:46,386 --> 00:22:49,855
“Why he⁠—why all I saw
of him was splendid.

284
00:22:49,855 --> 00:22:51,241
Since it had to be.

285
00:22:51,241 --> 00:22:52,254
It was⁠—”

286
00:22:52,254 --> 00:22:54,249
“Oh, yes; Ed.

287
00:22:54,249 --> 00:22:56,026
You’re thinking about him.

288
00:22:56,026 --> 00:22:57,223
I’d forgot him.

289
00:22:57,223 --> 00:22:58,840
So you didn’t enjoy Ed?”

290
00:22:58,840 --> 00:23:00,625
At this I looked at him blankly.

291
00:23:00,625 --> 00:23:02,265
“It isn’t possible that⁠—”

292
00:23:02,265 --> 00:23:05,454
Again he cut me short with
a laugh almost savage.

293
00:23:05,454 --> 00:23:07,526
“You needn’t to worry about Steve.

294
00:23:07,526 --> -1:59:59,000
He stayed game.

295
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

296
00:23:08,667 --> 00:23:14,236
What then had been the matter that he
should keep seeing Steve⁠—that his

297
00:23:14,236 --> 00:23:18,598
vision should so obliterate from him
what I still shivered at,

298
00:23:18,598 --> 00:23:20,168
and so shake him now?

299
00:23:20,168 --> 00:23:24,178
For he seemed to be growing more stirred
as I grew less.

300
00:23:24,178 --> 00:23:28,220
I asked him no further questions,
however, and we went on for several

301
00:23:28,220 --> 00:23:32,891
minutes, he brooding always in the same
fashion, until he resumed with the hard

302
00:23:32,891 --> 00:23:35,884
indifference that had
before surprised me:⁠—

303
00:23:35,884 --> 00:23:37,911
“So Ed gave you feelings!

304
00:23:37,911 --> 00:23:39,307
Dumb ague and so forth.”

305
00:23:39,307 --> 00:23:42,162
“No doubt we’re not made the
same way,” I retorted.

306
00:23:42,162 --> 00:23:43,910
He took no notice of this.

307
00:23:43,910 --> 00:23:47,435
“And you’d have been more comfortable if
he’d acted same as Steve did.

308
00:23:47,435 --> 00:23:50,760
It cert’nly was bad seeing Ed take it
that way, I reckon.

309
00:23:50,760 --> 00:23:53,695
And you didn’t see him when the
time came for business.

310
00:23:53,695 --> 00:23:59,406
Well, here’s what it is:
a man may be such a confirmed miscreant

311
00:23:59,406 --> 00:24:05,094
that killing’s the only cure for him;
but still he’s your own species,

312
00:24:05,094 --> 00:24:10,224
and you don’t want to have him fall
around and grab your laigs and show

313
00:24:10,224 --> 00:24:12,344
you his fear naked.

314
00:24:12,344 --> 00:24:14,695
It makes you feel ashamed.

315
00:24:14,695 --> 00:24:18,115
So Ed gave you feelings,
and Steve made everything

316
00:24:18,115 --> 00:24:19,172
right easy for you!”

317
00:24:19,172 --> 00:24:24,269
There was irony in his voice as he
surveyed me, but it fell away

318
00:24:24,269 --> 00:24:26,714
at once into sadness.

319
00:24:26,714 --> 00:24:29,200
“Both was miscreants.

320
00:24:29,200 --> 00:24:32,345
But if Steve had played the coward,
too, it would have been a whole

321
00:24:32,345 --> 00:24:33,725
heap easier for me.”

322
00:24:33,725 --> -1:59:59,000
He paused before adding,
“And Steve was not a miscreant once.

323
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

324
00:24:37,969 --> 00:24:41,750
His voice had trembled,
and I felt the deep emotion that seemed

325
00:24:41,750 --> 00:24:46,291
to gain upon him now that action was
over and he had nothing to do but think.

326
00:24:46,291 --> 00:24:50,011
And his view was simple enough:
you must die brave.

327
00:24:50,011 --> 00:24:54,609
Failure is a sort of treason to the
brotherhood, and forfeits pity.

328
00:24:54,609 --> 00:24:59,202
It was Steve’s perfect bearing that had
caught his heart so that he forgot even

329
00:24:59,202 --> 00:25:00,793
his scorn of the other man.

330
00:25:00,793 --> 00:25:03,992
But this was by no means all
that was to come.

331
00:25:03,992 --> 00:25:07,083
He harked back to that notion of a
prisoner helping to make it

332
00:25:07,083 --> 00:25:08,928
easy for his executioner.

333
00:25:08,928 --> 00:25:12,784
“Easy plumb to the end,”
he pursued, his mind reviewing the

334
00:25:12,784 --> 00:25:13,825
acts of the morning.

335
00:25:13,825 --> 00:25:16,784
“Why, he tried to give me your newspaper.

336
00:25:16,784 --> 00:25:17,634
I didn’t⁠—”

337
00:25:17,634 --> 00:25:20,697
“Oh, no,” I said hastily.

338
00:25:20,697 --> 00:25:22,128
“I had finished with it.”

339
00:25:22,128 --> 00:25:27,087
“Well, he took dying as naturally
as he took living.

340
00:25:27,087 --> 00:25:29,089
Like a man should.

341
00:25:29,089 --> 00:25:30,293
Like I hope to.”

342
00:25:30,293 --> 00:25:32,964
Again he looked at the
pictures in his mind.

343
00:25:32,964 --> 00:25:35,789
“No playacting nor last words.

344
00:25:35,789 --> 00:25:41,112
He just told goodbye to the boys as we
led his horse under the limb⁠—you

345
00:25:41,112 --> 00:25:43,926
needn’t to look so dainty,” he broke
off.

346
00:25:43,926 --> 00:25:47,133
“You ain’t going to get
any more shocking particulars.”

347
00:25:47,133 --> 00:25:50,990
“I know I’m white-livered,”
I said with a species of laugh.

348
00:25:50,990 --> 00:25:55,089
“I never crowd and stare when somebody is
hurt in the street.

349
00:25:55,089 --> 00:25:56,011
I get away.”

350
00:25:56,011 --> 00:25:57,214
He thought this over.

351
00:25:57,214 --> 00:25:59,277
“You don’t mean all of that.

352
00:25:59,277 --> 00:26:04,296
You’d not have spoke just that way about
crowding and staring if you thought well

353
00:26:04,296 --> 00:26:05,737
of them that stare.

354
00:26:05,737 --> 00:26:08,919
Staring ain’t courage;
it’s trashy curiosity.

355
00:26:08,919 --> 00:26:10,706
Now you did not have this thing⁠—”

356
00:26:10,706 --> 00:26:16,763
He had stretched out his hand to point,
but it fell, and his utterance stopped,

357
00:26:16,763 --> 00:26:18,691
and he jerked his horse to a stand.

358
00:26:18,691 --> 00:26:25,094
My nerves sprang like a wire at his
suddenness, and I looked

359
00:26:25,094 --> 00:26:26,184
where he was looking.

360
00:26:26,184 --> 00:26:28,971
There were the cottonwoods,
close in front of us.

361
00:26:28,971 --> 00:26:33,818
As we had travelled and talked
we had forgotten them.

362
00:26:33,818 --> 00:26:37,158
Now they were looming within a hundred
yards; and our trail

363
00:26:37,158 --> 00:26:38,597
lay straight through them.

364
00:26:38,597 --> 00:26:41,085
“Let’s go around them,”
said the Virginian.

365
00:26:41,085 --> 00:26:46,482
When we had come back from our circuit
into the trail he continued:

366
00:26:46,482 --> 00:26:49,122
“You did not have that thing to do.

367
00:26:49,122 --> 00:26:52,793
But a man goes through with his
responsibilities⁠—and

368
00:26:52,793 --> 00:26:54,155
I reckon you could.”

369
00:26:54,155 --> 00:26:56,492
“I hope so,” I answered.

370
00:26:56,492 --> 00:26:57,530
“How about Ed?”

371
00:26:57,530 --> 00:27:00,566
“He was not a man, though we thought
he was till this.

372
00:27:00,566 --> 00:27:03,726
Steve and I started punching cattle
together at the Bordeaux

373
00:27:03,726 --> 00:27:05,415
outfit, north of Cheyenne.

374
00:27:05,415 --> 00:27:12,670
We did everything together in those
days⁠—work and play.

375
00:27:12,670 --> 00:27:16,092
Six years ago.

376
00:27:16,092 --> -1:59:59,000
Steve had many good points onced.

377
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

378
00:27:18,350 --> 00:27:22,883
We must have gone two miles
before he spoke again.

379
00:27:22,883 --> 00:27:24,745
“You prob’ly didn’t notice Steve?

380
00:27:24,745 --> 00:27:26,560
I mean the way he acted to me?”

381
00:27:26,560 --> 00:27:29,403
It was a question, but he did not
wait for my answer.

382
00:27:29,403 --> 00:27:32,669
“Steve never said a word
to me all through.

383
00:27:32,669 --> 00:27:33,535
He shunned it.

384
00:27:33,535 --> 00:27:37,618
And you saw how neighborly he talked
to the other boys.”

385
00:27:37,618 --> 00:27:38,978
“Where have they all gone?”

386
00:27:38,978 --> 00:27:39,723
I asked.

387
00:27:39,723 --> 00:27:41,270
He smiled at me.

388
00:27:41,270 --> 00:27:44,428
“It cert’nly is lonesome now, for a fact.”

389
00:27:44,428 --> 00:27:47,113
“I didn’t know you felt it,” said I.

390
00:27:47,113 --> 00:27:49,647
“Feel it!⁠—they’ve went to the railroad.

391
00:27:49,647 --> 00:27:54,924
Three of them are witnesses in a case at
Evanston, and the Judge wants our

392
00:27:54,924 --> 00:27:56,891
outfit at Medicine Bow.

393
00:27:56,891 --> 00:27:58,094
Steve shunned me.

394
00:27:58,094 --> 00:28:00,216
Did he think I was going back on him?”

395
00:28:00,216 --> 00:28:01,254
“What if he did?

396
00:28:01,254 --> 00:28:02,245
You were not.

397
00:28:02,245 --> 00:28:05,806
And so nobody’s going to
Wind River but you?”

398
00:28:05,806 --> 00:28:07,162
“No.

399
00:28:07,162 --> 00:28:10,713
Did you notice Steve would not give us
any information about Shorty?

400
00:28:10,713 --> 00:28:11,526
That was right.

401
00:28:11,526 --> 00:28:13,450
I would have acted that way, too.”

402
00:28:13,450 --> 00:28:16,977
Thus, each time, he brought me
back to the subject.

403
00:28:16,977 --> 00:28:21,665
The sun was now shining warm during two
or three minutes together,

404
00:28:21,665 --> 00:28:26,538
and gulfs of blue opened in
the great white clouds.

405
00:28:26,538 --> 00:28:32,965
These moved and met among each other,
and parted, like hands spread out,

406
00:28:32,965 --> 00:28:38,885
slowly weaving a spell of sleep over the
day after the wakeful night storm.

407
00:28:38,885 --> 00:28:43,725
The huge contours of the earth lay
basking and drying, and not one living

408
00:28:43,725 --> 00:28:47,287
creature, bird or beast, was in sight.

409
00:28:47,287 --> 00:28:51,338
Quiet was returning to my revived
spirits, but there was

410
00:28:51,338 --> 00:28:53,041
none for the Virginian.

411
00:28:53,041 --> 00:28:58,529
And as he reasoned matters out aloud,
his mood grew more overcast.

412
00:28:58,529 --> 00:29:01,118
“You have a friend, and his
ways are your ways.

413
00:29:01,118 --> 00:29:05,530
You travel together, you spree together
confidentially, and you suit each other

414
00:29:05,530 --> 00:29:06,707
down to the ground.

415
00:29:06,707 --> 00:29:11,899
Then one day you find him putting his
iron on another man’s calf.

416
00:29:11,899 --> 00:29:16,965
You tell him fair and square those ways
have never been your ways and ain’t

417
00:29:16,965 --> 00:29:18,448
going to be your ways.

418
00:29:18,448 --> 00:29:22,906
Well, that does not change him any,
for it seems he’s disturbed over getting

419
00:29:22,906 --> 00:29:25,811
rich quick and being a big
man in the Territory.

420
00:29:25,811 --> 00:29:30,913
And the years go on, until you are
foreman of Judge Henry’s ranch and he⁠—

421
00:29:30,913 --> 00:29:33,065
is dangling back in the cottonwoods.

422
00:29:33,065 --> 00:29:34,658
What can he claim?

423
00:29:34,658 --> 00:29:36,209
Who made the choice?

424
00:29:36,209 --> 00:29:41,716
He cannot say, ‘Here is my old friend
that I would have stood by.’

425
00:29:41,716 --> 00:29:42,967
Can he say that?”

426
00:29:42,967 --> 00:29:46,082
“But he didn’t say it,” I protested.

427
00:29:46,082 --> 00:29:46,813
“No.

428
00:29:46,813 --> 00:29:47,955
He shunned me.”

429
00:29:47,955 --> 00:29:49,376
“Listen,” I said.

430
00:29:49,376 --> 00:29:52,561
“Suppose while you were on guard he had
whispered, ‘Get me off’⁠—would

431
00:29:52,561 --> 00:29:53,418
you have done it?”

432
00:29:53,418 --> 00:29:54,857
“No, sir!”

433
00:29:54,857 --> 00:29:56,893
said the Virginian, hotly.

434
00:29:56,893 --> 00:29:58,176
“Then what do you want?”

435
00:29:58,176 --> 00:29:58,985
I asked.

436
00:29:58,985 --> 00:30:00,062
“What did you want?”

437
00:30:00,062 --> 00:30:03,655
He could not answer me⁠—but I had not
answered him, I saw;

438
00:30:03,655 --> 00:30:05,104
so I pushed it farther.

439
00:30:05,104 --> 00:30:08,521
“Did you want endorsement from the
man you were hanging?

440
00:30:08,521 --> 00:30:10,430
That’s asking a little too much.”

441
00:30:10,430 --> 00:30:12,115
But he had now another confusion.

442
00:30:12,115 --> 00:30:16,229
“Steve stood by Shorty,” he said musingly.

443
00:30:16,229 --> 00:30:20,167
“It was Shorty’s mistake cost him his
life, but all the same he didn’t

444
00:30:20,167 --> 00:30:22,022
want us to catch⁠—”

445
00:30:22,022 --> 00:30:25,120
“You are mixing things,” I interrupted.

446
00:30:25,120 --> 00:30:29,320
“I never heard you mix things before.

447
00:30:29,320 --> 00:30:32,783
And it was not Shorty’s mistake.”

448
00:30:32,783 --> 00:30:35,231
He showed momentary interest.

449
00:30:35,231 --> 00:30:36,219
“Whose then?”

450
00:30:36,219 --> 00:30:40,167
“The mistake of whoever took a
fool into their enterprise.”

451
00:30:40,167 --> 00:30:41,017
“That’s correct.

452
00:30:41,017 --> -1:59:59,000
Well, Trampas took Shorty in,
and Steve would not tell on him either.

453
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

454
00:30:45,222 --> 00:30:48,758
I still tried it, saying,
“They were all in the same boat.”

455
00:30:48,758 --> 00:30:52,157
But logic was useless;
he had lost his bearings in

456
00:30:52,157 --> 00:30:53,696
a fog of sentiment.

457
00:30:53,696 --> 00:30:57,750
He knew, knew passionately,
that he had done right;

458
00:30:57,750 --> 00:31:03,890
but the silence of his old friend to him
through those last hours left a sting

459
00:31:03,890 --> 00:31:06,431
that no reasoning could assuage.

460
00:31:06,431 --> 00:31:10,103
“He told goodbye to the rest of the boys;
but not to me.”

461
00:31:10,103 --> 00:31:14,015
And nothing that I could point out in
common sense turned him from the thread

462
00:31:14,015 --> 00:31:15,296
of his own argument.

463
00:31:15,296 --> 00:31:20,415
He worked round the circle
again to self-justification.

464
00:31:20,415 --> 00:31:23,104
“Was it him I was deserting?

465
00:31:23,104 --> 00:31:28,731
Was not the deserting done by him the day
I spoke my mind about stealing calves?

466
00:31:28,731 --> 00:31:31,663
I have kept my ways the same.

467
00:31:31,663 --> 00:31:34,030
He is the one that took to new ones.

468
00:31:34,030 --> 00:31:37,499
The man I used to travel with is not
the man back there.

469
00:31:37,499 --> 00:31:42,194
Same name, to be sure.

470
00:31:42,194 --> 00:31:43,946
And same body.

471
00:31:43,946 --> 00:31:47,331
But different in⁠—and yet
he had the memory!

472
00:31:47,331 --> 00:31:49,926
You can’t never change your memory!”

473
00:31:49,926 --> 00:31:51,091
He gave a sob.

474
00:31:51,091 --> 00:31:54,931
It was the first I had ever heard from
him, and before I knew what I was doing

475
00:31:54,931 --> 00:31:59,840
I had reined my horse up to his and put
my arm around his shoulders.

476
00:31:59,840 --> 00:32:04,089
I had no sooner touched him than
he was utterly overcome.

477
00:32:04,089 --> 00:32:07,068
“I knew Steve awful well,” he said.

478
00:32:07,068 --> 00:32:11,667
Thus we had actually come to change
places; for early in the morning he had

479
00:32:11,667 --> 00:32:15,827
been firm while I was unnerved,
while now it was I who attempted to

480
00:32:15,827 --> 00:32:17,119
steady and comfort him.

481
00:32:17,119 --> 00:32:21,531
I had the sense to keep silent,
and presently he shook my hand,

482
00:32:21,531 --> 00:32:23,238
not looking at me as he did so.

483
00:32:23,238 --> 00:32:26,287
He was always very shy of demonstration.

484
00:32:26,287 --> 00:32:29,673
And he took to patting the
neck of his pony.

485
00:32:29,673 --> 00:32:34,231
“You Monte hawss,” said he,
“you think you are wise,

486
00:32:34,231 --> 00:32:37,248
but there’s a lot of
things you don’t savvy.”

487
00:32:37,248 --> 00:32:40,521
Then he made a new beginning
of talk between us.

488
00:32:40,521 --> 00:32:43,302
“It is kind of pitiful about Shorty.”

489
00:32:43,302 --> 00:32:45,272
“Very pitiful,” I said.

490
00:32:45,272 --> 00:32:46,672
“Do you know about him?”

491
00:32:46,672 --> 00:32:48,342
the Virginian asked.

492
00:32:48,342 --> 00:32:53,418
“I know there’s no real harm in him,
and some real good, and that he has not

493
00:32:53,418 --> 00:32:56,525
got the brains necessary to
be a horse thief.”

494
00:32:56,525 --> 00:32:57,170
“That’s so.

495
00:32:57,170 --> 00:32:58,392
That’s very true.

496
00:32:58,392 --> 00:33:02,263
Trampas has led him in deeper than
his stature can stand.

497
00:33:02,263 --> 00:33:06,095
Now back East you can be
middling and get along.

498
00:33:06,095 --> 00:33:09,616
But if you go to try a thing on in this
Western country, you’ve got

499
00:33:09,616 --> 00:33:10,535
to do it well.

500
00:33:10,535 --> 00:33:13,854
You’ve got to deal cyards well;
you’ve got to steal well;

501
00:33:13,854 --> 00:33:17,366
and if you claim to be quick with your
gun, you must be quick,

502
00:33:17,366 --> 00:33:21,056
for you’re a public temptation,
and some man will not resist trying to

503
00:33:21,056 --> 00:33:23,199
prove he is the quicker.

504
00:33:23,199 --> 00:33:27,441
You must break all the Commandments well
in this Western country,

505
00:33:27,441 --> 00:33:30,760
and Shorty should have stayed in
Brooklyn, for he will be a

506
00:33:30,760 --> 00:33:33,415
novice his livelong days.

507
00:33:33,415 --> 00:33:34,874
You don’t know about him?

508
00:33:34,874 --> 00:33:37,085
He has told me his circumstances.

509
00:33:37,085 --> 00:33:39,600
He don’t remember his father,
and it was like he could have

510
00:33:39,600 --> 00:33:40,799
claimed three or four.

511
00:33:40,799 --> 00:33:45,063
And I expect his mother was not much
interested in him before or

512
00:33:45,063 --> 00:33:46,420
after he was born.

513
00:33:46,420 --> 00:33:51,395
He ran around, and when he was eighteen
he got to be help to a grocery man.

514
00:33:51,395 --> 00:33:57,768
But a girl he ran with kept taking all
his pay and teasing him for more,

515
00:33:57,768 --> 00:34:05,192
and so one day the grocery man caught
Shorty robbing his till, and fired him.

516
00:34:05,192 --> 00:34:09,009
There wasn’t no one to tell goodbye to,
for the girl had to go to the country to

517
00:34:09,009 --> 00:34:10,436
see her aunt, she said.

518
00:34:10,436 --> 00:34:15,031
So Shorty hung around the store and
kissed the grocery cat goodbye.

519
00:34:15,031 --> 00:34:18,184
He’d been used to feeding the cat,
and she’d sit in his lap and

520
00:34:18,184 --> 00:34:19,747
purr, he told me.

521
00:34:19,747 --> 00:34:21,997
He sends money back to that girl now.

522
00:34:21,997 --> 00:34:26,801
This hyeh country is no country for
Shorty, for he will be a conspicuous

523
00:34:26,801 --> -1:59:59,000
novice all his days.

524
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

525
00:34:29,461 --> 00:34:33,492
“Perhaps he’ll prefer honesty after his
narrow shave,” I said.

526
00:34:33,492 --> 00:34:36,469
But the Virginian shook his head.

527
00:34:36,469 --> 00:34:38,138
“Trampas has got hold of him.”

528
00:34:38,138 --> 00:34:43,134
The day was now all blue above,
and all warm and dry beneath.

529
00:34:43,134 --> 00:34:48,273
We had begun to wind in and rise among
the first slopes of the foothills,

530
00:34:48,273 --> 00:34:51,025
and we had talked ourselves into
silence.

531
00:34:51,025 --> 00:34:55,512
At the first running water we made a long
nooning, and I slept on the bare ground.

532
00:34:55,512 --> 00:35:02,583
My body was lodged so fast and deep in
slumber that when the Virginian shook me

533
00:35:02,583 --> 00:35:08,298
awake I could not come back to life at
once; it was the clump of cottonwoods,

534
00:35:08,298 --> 00:35:12,823
small and far out in the plain below
us, that recalled me.

535
00:35:12,823 --> 00:35:17,401
“It’ll not be watching us much
longer,” said the Virginian.

536
00:35:17,401 --> 00:35:22,028
He made it a sort of joke;
but I knew that both of us were glad

537
00:35:22,028 --> 00:35:26,696
when presently we rode into a steeper
country, and among its folds and

538
00:35:26,696 --> 00:35:31,696
carvings lost all sight of the plain.

539
00:35:31,696 --> 00:35:33,576
He had not slept, I found.

540
00:35:33,576 --> 00:35:37,776
His explanation was that the packs needed
better balancing, and after that he had

541
00:35:37,776 --> 00:35:40,454
gone up and down the stream on
the chance of trout.

542
00:35:40,454 --> 00:35:45,295
But his haunted eyes gave me the real
reason⁠—they spoke of Steve,

543
00:35:45,295 --> 00:35:48,546
no matter what he spoke of;
it was to be no short thing with him.

544
00:35:48,546 --> 00:35:49,820
CHAPTER XXXII

545
00:35:49,820 --> 00:35:51,229
Superstition Trail

546
00:35:51,229 --> 00:35:55,912
We did not make thirty-five miles that
day, nor yet twenty-five,

547
00:35:55,912 --> 00:35:57,156
for he had let me sleep.

548
00:35:57,156 --> 00:36:00,878
We made an early camp and tried some
unsuccessful fishing,

549
00:36:00,878 --> 00:36:04,564
over which he was cheerful,
promising trout tomorrow when we should

550
00:36:04,564 --> 00:36:06,302
be higher among the mountains.

551
00:36:06,302 --> 00:36:09,876
He never again touched or came near the
subject that was on his mind,

552
00:36:09,876 --> 00:36:14,652
but while I sat writing my diary,
he went off to his horse Monte,

553
00:36:14,652 --> 00:36:17,153
and I could hear that he occasionally
talked to that friend.

554
00:36:17,153 --> 00:36:22,559
Next day we swung southward from what is
known to many as the Conant trail,

555
00:36:22,559 --> 00:36:28,724
and headed for that shortcut through the
Tetons which is known to but a few.

556
00:36:28,724 --> 00:36:33,502
Bitch Creek was the name of the stream we
now followed, and here there was such

557
00:36:33,502 --> 00:36:36,376
good fishing that we idled;
and the horses and I

558
00:36:36,376 --> 00:36:38,715
at least enjoyed ourselves.

559
00:36:38,715 --> 00:36:43,302
For they found fresh pastures and shade
in the now plentiful woods;

560
00:36:43,302 --> 00:36:46,942
and the mountain odors and the mountain
heights were enough for me when the

561
00:36:46,942 --> 00:36:49,302
fish refused to rise.

562
00:36:49,302 --> 00:36:55,254
This road of ours now became the road
which the pursuit had

563
00:36:55,254 --> 00:36:56,816
taken before the capture.

564
00:36:56,816 --> 00:37:02,533
Going along, I noticed the footprints of
many hoofs, rain-blurred but recent,

565
00:37:02,533 --> 00:37:05,893
and these were the tracks of the people
I had met in the stable.

566
00:37:05,893 --> 00:37:09,185
“You can notice Monte’s,”
said the Virginian.

567
00:37:09,185 --> 00:37:12,506
“He is the only one that has
his hind feet shod.

568
00:37:12,506 --> 00:37:16,791
There’s several trails from this point
down to where we have come from.”

569
00:37:16,791 --> 00:37:23,803
We mounted now over a long slant of rock,
smooth and of wide extent.

570
00:37:23,803 --> 00:37:27,153
Above us it went up easily into a little
side canyon, but ahead,

571
00:37:27,153 --> 00:37:32,398
where our way was, it grew so steep that
we got off and led our horses.

572
00:37:32,398 --> 00:37:36,718
This brought us to the next higher level
of the mountain, a space of sagebrush

573
00:37:36,718 --> 00:37:41,715
more open, where the rain-washed tracks
appeared again in the softer ground.

574
00:37:41,715 --> 00:37:45,823
“Someone has been here since the rain,”
I called to the Virginian,

575
00:37:45,823 --> 00:37:49,377
who was still on the rock,
walking up behind the packhorses.

576
00:37:49,377 --> 00:37:50,066
“Since the rain!”

577
00:37:50,066 --> 00:37:50,930
he exclaimed.

578
00:37:50,930 --> 00:37:52,286
“That’s not two days yet.”

579
00:37:52,286 --> 00:37:54,451
He came and examined the footprints.

580
00:37:54,451 --> 00:37:59,384
“A man and a hawss,” he said, frowning.

581
00:37:59,384 --> 00:38:00,960
“Going the same way we are.

582
00:38:00,960 --> 00:38:05,074
How did he come to pass us,
and us not see him?”

583
00:38:05,074 --> 00:38:07,923
“One of the other trails,” I reminded him.

584
00:38:07,923 --> 00:38:11,256
“Yes, but there’s not
many that knows them.

585
00:38:11,256 --> -1:59:59,000
They are pretty rough trails.

586
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

587
00:38:13,031 --> 00:38:14,989
“Worse than this one we’re taking?”

588
00:38:14,989 --> 00:38:18,279
“Not much; only how does he come to
know any of them?

589
00:38:18,279 --> 00:38:22,140
And why don’t he take the Conant trail
that’s open and easy and not much

590
00:38:22,140 --> 00:38:22,713
longer?

591
00:38:22,713 --> 00:38:24,115
One man and a hawss.

592
00:38:24,115 --> 00:38:27,745
I don’t see who he is or
what he wants here.”

593
00:38:27,745 --> 00:38:30,206
“Probably a prospector,” I suggested.

594
00:38:30,206 --> 00:38:34,766
“Only one outfit of prospectors has ever
been here, and they claimed there was no

595
00:38:34,766 --> -1:59:59,000
mineral-bearing rock in these parts.

596
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

597
00:38:37,369 --> 00:38:41,389
We got back into our saddles
with the mystery unsolved.

598
00:38:41,389 --> 00:38:46,307
To the Virginian it was a greater one,
apparently, than to me;

599
00:38:46,307 --> 00:38:50,263
why should one have to account for every
stray traveller in the mountains?

600
00:38:50,263 --> 00:38:52,980
“That’s queer, too,” said the Virginian.

601
00:38:52,980 --> 00:38:57,380
He was now riding in front of me,
and he stopped, looking

602
00:38:57,380 --> 00:38:58,452
down at the trail.

603
00:38:58,452 --> 00:38:59,661
“Don’t you notice?”

604
00:38:59,661 --> 00:39:01,222
It did not strike me.

605
00:39:01,222 --> 00:39:05,209
“Why, he keeps walking beside his hawss;
he don’t get on him.”

606
00:39:05,209 --> 00:39:11,016
Now we, of course, had mounted at the
beginning of the better trail after the

607
00:39:11,016 --> 00:39:14,963
steep rock, and that was quite
half a mile back.

608
00:39:14,963 --> 00:39:17,559
Still, I had a natural explanation.

609
00:39:17,559 --> 00:39:19,479
“He’s leading a packhorse.

610
00:39:19,479 --> 00:39:21,418
He’s a poor trapper, and walks.”

611
00:39:21,418 --> 00:39:26,128
“Packhorses ain’t usually shod before and
behind,” said the Virginian;

612
00:39:26,128 --> 00:39:28,894
and sliding to the ground
he touched the footprints.

613
00:39:28,894 --> 00:39:31,731
“They are not four hours old,” said he.

614
00:39:31,731 --> -1:59:59,000
“This bank’s in shadow by one o’clock,
and the sun has not cooked them dusty.

615
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

616
00:39:37,489 --> 00:39:41,057
We continued on our way;
and although it seemed no very

617
00:39:41,057 --> 00:39:48,294
particular thing to me that a man should
choose to walk and lead his horse for a

618
00:39:48,294 --> 00:39:53,617
while⁠—I often did so to limber my
muscles⁠—nevertheless I began to catch

619
00:39:53,617 --> 00:39:57,617
the Virginian’s uncertain feeling about
this traveller whose steps had appeared

620
00:39:57,617 --> 00:40:01,879
on our path in mid-journey,
as if he had alighted from the midair,

621
00:40:01,879 --> 00:40:07,439
and to remind myself that he had come
over the great face of rock from another

622
00:40:07,439 --> 00:40:12,997
trail and thus joined us,
and that indigent trappers are to be

623
00:40:12,997 --> 00:40:18,348
found owning but a single horse and
leading him with their belongings

624
00:40:18,348 --> 00:40:25,258
through the deepest solitudes of the
mountains⁠—none of this quite brought

625
00:40:25,258 --> 00:40:30,320
back to me the comfort which had been
mine since we left the cottonwoods out

626
00:40:30,320 --> 00:40:32,055
of sight down in the plain.

627
00:40:32,055 --> 00:40:35,958
Hence I called out sharply,
“What’s the matter now?”

628
00:40:35,958 --> 00:40:39,166
when the Virginian suddenly
stopped his horse again.

629
00:40:39,166 --> 00:40:42,955
He looked down at the trail,
and then he very slowly turned round in

630
00:40:42,955 --> 00:40:45,950
his saddle and stared
back steadily at me.

631
00:40:45,950 --> 00:40:48,556
“There’s two of them,” he said.

632
00:40:48,556 --> 00:40:49,418
“Two what?”

633
00:40:49,418 --> 00:40:50,911
“I don’t know.”

634
00:40:50,911 --> 00:40:56,515
“You must know whether it’s two horses or
two men,” I said, almost angrily.

635
00:40:56,515 --> 00:41:00,512
But to this he made no answer,
sitting quite still on his horse

636
00:41:00,512 --> 00:41:02,134
and contemplating the ground.

637
00:41:02,134 --> 00:41:06,511
The silence was fastening on me like a
spell, and I spurred my horse

638
00:41:06,511 --> 00:41:09,740
impatiently forward to see for myself.

639
00:41:09,740 --> 00:41:13,664
The footprints of two men were
there in the trail.

640
00:41:13,664 --> 00:41:15,264
“What do you say to that?”

641
00:41:15,264 --> 00:41:16,337
said the Virginian.

642
00:41:16,337 --> 00:41:17,984
“Kind of ridiculous, ain’t it?”

643
00:41:17,984 --> 00:41:23,302
“Very quaint,” I answered,
groping for the explanation.

644
00:41:23,302 --> 00:41:28,392
There was no rock here to walk over and
step from into the softer trail.

645
00:41:28,392 --> 00:41:32,552
These second steps came more out of the
air than the first.

646
00:41:32,552 --> 00:41:36,912
And my brain played me the evil trick of
showing me a dead man in

647
00:41:36,912 --> 00:41:38,512
a gray flannel shirt.

648
00:41:38,512 --> 00:41:43,625
“It’s two, you see, travelling with one
hawss, and they take turns riding him.”

649
00:41:43,625 --> 00:41:44,746
“Why, of course!”

650
00:41:44,746 --> 00:41:47,966
I exclaimed; and we went along
for a few paces.

651
00:41:47,966 --> 00:41:53,070
“There you are,” said the Virginian,
as the trail proved him right.

652
00:41:53,070 --> 00:41:55,050
“Number one has got on.

653
00:41:55,050 --> 00:41:57,617
My God, what’s that?”

654
00:41:57,617 --> 00:42:02,616
At a crashing in the woods very close to
us we both flung round and caught sight

655
00:42:02,616 --> 00:42:03,767
of a vanishing elk.

656
00:42:03,767 --> 00:42:07,307
It left us confronted,
smiling a little, and sounding each

657
00:42:07,307 --> 00:42:08,759
other with our eyes.

658
00:42:08,759 --> 00:42:12,022
“Well, we didn’t need him for
meat,” said the Virginian.

659
00:42:12,022 --> 00:42:13,882
“A spike-horn, wasn’t it?”

660
00:42:13,882 --> 00:42:14,702
said I.

661
00:42:14,702 --> 00:42:16,988
“Yes, just a spike-horn.”

662
00:42:16,988 --> 00:42:21,584
For a while now as we rode we kept up a
cheerful conversation about elk.

663
00:42:21,584 --> 00:42:25,435
We wondered if we should meet many more
close to the trail like this;

664
00:42:25,435 --> 00:42:28,625
but it was not long before
our words died away.

665
00:42:28,625 --> 00:42:33,687
We had come into a veritable gulf of
mountain peaks, sharp at their bare

666
00:42:33,687 --> 00:42:39,487
summits like teeth, holding fields of
snow lower down, and glittering still in

667
00:42:39,487 --> 00:42:44,767
full day up there, while down among our
pines and parks the afternoon

668
00:42:44,767 --> 00:42:46,136
was growing sombre.

669
00:42:46,136 --> 00:42:50,488
All the while the fresh hoofprints of the
horse and the fresh footprints of

670
00:42:50,488 --> 00:42:52,208
the man preceded us.

671
00:42:52,208 --> 00:42:56,441
In the trees, and in the opens,
across the levels, and up the

672
00:42:56,441 --> 00:42:58,383
steeps, they were there.

673
00:42:58,383 --> 00:43:00,781
And so they were not four hours old!

674
00:43:00,781 --> 00:43:01,975
Were they so much?

675
00:43:01,975 --> 00:43:05,776
Might we not, round some turn,
come upon the makers of them?

676
00:43:05,776 --> 00:43:07,862
I began to watch for this.

677
00:43:07,862 --> 00:43:11,742
And again my brain played me an evil
trick, against which I found myself

678
00:43:11,742 --> 00:43:15,836
actually reasoning thus:
if they took turns riding,

679
00:43:15,836 --> 00:43:19,225
then walking must tire them as it did
me or any man.

680
00:43:19,225 --> 00:43:22,188
And besides, there was a horse.

681
00:43:22,188 --> 00:43:27,128
With such thoughts I combated the fancy
that those footprints were being made

682
00:43:27,128 --> 00:43:34,121
immediately in front of us all the
while, and that they were the only sign

683
00:43:34,121 --> 00:43:38,765
of any presence which our eyes could
see.

684
00:43:38,765 --> 00:43:41,655
But my fancy overcame my thoughts.

685
00:43:41,655 --> 00:43:45,359
It was shame only which held me from
asking this question of the Virginian:

686
00:43:45,359 --> 00:43:50,209
Had one horse served in both cases of
Justice down at the cottonwoods?

687
00:43:50,209 --> 00:43:51,773
I wondered about this.

688
00:43:51,773 --> 00:43:58,358
One horse⁠—or had the strangling nooses
dragged two saddles empty

689
00:43:58,358 --> 00:43:59,589
at the same signal?

690
00:43:59,589 --> 00:44:04,151
Most likely; and therefore these people
up here⁠—Was I going back to the

691
00:44:04,151 --> 00:44:04,896
nursery?

692
00:44:04,896 --> 00:44:06,596
I brought myself up short.

693
00:44:06,596 --> 00:44:11,124
And I told myself to be steady;
there lurked in this brain-process which

694
00:44:11,124 --> 00:44:14,643
was going on beneath my reason a threat
worse than the childish

695
00:44:14,643 --> 00:44:16,262
apprehensions it created.

696
00:44:16,262 --> 00:44:21,002
I reminded myself that I was a man grown,
twenty-five years old,

697
00:44:21,002 --> 00:44:24,593
and that I must not merely seem like
one, but feel like one.

698
00:44:24,593 --> 00:44:27,685
“You’re not afraid of
the dark, I suppose?”

699
00:44:27,685 --> 00:44:30,557
This I uttered aloud, unwittingly.

700
00:44:30,557 --> 00:44:31,327
“What’s that?”

701
00:44:31,327 --> 00:44:34,006
I started; but it was only
the Virginian behind me.

702
00:44:34,006 --> 00:44:35,270
“Oh, nothing.

703
00:44:35,270 --> -1:59:59,000
The air is getting colder up here.

704
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

705
00:44:36,906 --> 00:44:38,978
I had presently a great relief.

706
00:44:38,978 --> 00:44:44,592
We came to a place where again this trail
mounted so abruptly that we once more

707
00:44:44,592 --> 00:44:46,846
got off to lead our horses.

708
00:44:46,846 --> 00:44:51,259
So likewise had our predecessors done;
and as I watched the two different sets

709
00:44:51,259 --> 00:44:56,007
of footprints, I observed something and
hastened to speak of it.

710
00:44:56,007 --> 00:44:58,517
“One man is much heavier than the other.”

711
00:44:58,517 --> 00:45:01,885
“I was hoping I’d not have to tell you
that,” said the Virginian.

712
00:45:01,885 --> 00:45:03,713
“You’re always ahead of me!

713
00:45:03,713 --> 00:45:06,099
Well, still my education is progressing.”

714
00:45:06,099 --> 00:45:07,692
“Why, yes.

715
00:45:07,692 --> 00:45:10,460
You’ll equal an Injun if you keep on.”

716
00:45:10,460 --> 00:45:14,407
It was good to be facetious;
and I smiled to myself

717
00:45:14,407 --> 00:45:15,359
as I trudged upward.

718
00:45:15,359 --> 00:45:18,885
We came off the steep place,
leaving the canyon beneath us,

719
00:45:18,885 --> 00:45:20,125
and took to horseback.

720
00:45:20,125 --> 00:45:25,125
And as we proceeded over the final gentle
slant up to the rim of the great basin

721
00:45:25,125 --> 00:45:30,018
that was set among the peaks,
the Virginian was jocular once more.

722
00:45:30,018 --> -1:59:59,000
“Pounds has got on,” said he,
“and Ounces is walking.

723
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

724
00:45:34,630 --> 00:45:38,830
I glanced over my shoulder at him,
and he nodded as he fixed the weather-

725
00:45:38,830 --> 00:45:41,217
beaten crimson handkerchief
round his neck.

726
00:45:41,217 --> 00:45:44,670
Then he threw a stone at a pack animal
that was delaying on the trail.

727
00:45:44,670 --> 00:45:47,830
“Damn your buckskin hide,” he drawled.

728
00:45:47,830 --> 00:45:50,328
“You can view the scenery from the top.”

729
00:45:50,328 --> 00:45:56,157
He was so natural, sitting loose in the
saddle, and cursing in his gentle voice,

730
00:45:56,157 --> 00:45:59,683
that I laughed to think what visions
I had been harboring.

731
00:45:59,683 --> 00:46:03,537
The two dead men riding one horse through
the mountains vanished,

732
00:46:03,537 --> 00:46:05,178
and I came back to every day.

733
00:46:05,178 --> 00:46:07,819
“Do you think we’ll catch
up with those people?”

734
00:46:07,819 --> 00:46:09,114
I asked.

735
00:46:09,114 --> 00:46:09,970
“Not likely.

736
00:46:09,970 --> -1:59:59,000
They’re travelling about the
same gait we are.

737
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

738
00:46:12,592 --> 00:46:16,819
“Ounces ought to be the best walker.”

739
00:46:16,819 --> 00:46:19,270
“Up hill, yes.

740
00:46:19,270 --> 00:46:22,356
But Pounds will go down a-foggin’.”

741
00:46:22,356 --> 00:46:25,475
We gained the rim of the basin.

742
00:46:25,475 --> 00:46:32,744
It lay below us, a great cup of country⁠—
rocks, woods, opens, and streams.

743
00:46:32,744 --> 00:46:38,710
The tall peaks rose like spires around
it, magnificent and bare in the last of

744
00:46:38,710 --> 00:46:44,113
the sun; and we surveyed this upper
world, letting our animals get breath.

745
00:46:44,113 --> 00:46:48,182
Our bleak, crumbled rim ran like a
rampart between the towering tops,

746
00:46:48,182 --> 00:46:52,685
a half circle of five miles or six,
very wide in some parts,

747
00:46:52,685 --> 00:46:56,618
and in some shrinking to a
scanty foothold, as here.

748
00:46:56,618 --> 00:47:02,588
Here our trail crossed over it between
two eroded and fantastic shapes of

749
00:47:02,588 --> 00:47:06,584
stone, like mushrooms,
or misshapen heads on pikes.

750
00:47:06,584 --> 00:47:11,200
Banks of snow spread up here against the
black rocks, but half an hour would see

751
00:47:11,200 --> 00:47:14,181
us descended to the green and the woods.

752
00:47:14,181 --> 00:47:18,894
I looked down, both of us looked down,
but our forerunners were not there.

753
00:47:18,894 --> 00:47:22,437
“They’ll be camping somewhere in this
basin, though,” said the Virginian,

754
00:47:22,437 --> 00:47:24,194
staring at the dark pines.

755
00:47:24,194 --> 00:47:26,820
“They have not come this
trail by accident.”

756
00:47:26,820 --> 00:47:32,604
A cold little wind blew down between our
stone shapes, and upward again, eddying.

757
00:47:32,604 --> 00:47:37,800
And round a corner upward with it came
fluttering a leaf of newspaper,

758
00:47:37,800 --> 00:47:39,783
and caught against an edge close to me.

759
00:47:39,783 --> 00:47:41,111
“What’s the latest?”

760
00:47:41,111 --> 00:47:43,435
inquired the Virginian from his horse.

761
00:47:43,435 --> 00:47:47,053
For I had dismounted,
and had picked up the leaf.

762
00:47:47,053 --> 00:47:50,511
“Seems to be interesting,”
I next heard him say.

763
00:47:50,511 --> 00:47:54,153
“Can’t you tell a man what’s making your
eyes bug out so?”

764
00:47:54,153 --> 00:47:59,416
“Yes,” my voice replied to him,
and it sounded like some stranger

765
00:47:59,416 --> 00:48:03,006
speaking lightly near by; “oh, yes!

766
00:48:03,006 --> 00:48:04,846
Decidedly interesting.”

767
00:48:04,846 --> 00:48:07,935
My voice mimicked his pronunciation.

768
00:48:07,935 --> 00:48:10,348
“It’s quite the latest, I imagine.

769
00:48:10,348 --> 00:48:12,095
You had better read it yourself.”

770
00:48:12,095 --> 00:48:15,852
And I handed it to him with a smile,
watching his countenance,

771
00:48:15,852 --> 00:48:19,388
while my brain felt as if clouds
were rushing through it.

772
00:48:19,388 --> 00:48:22,429
I saw his eyes quietly
run the headings over.

773
00:48:22,429 --> 00:48:23,356
“Well?”

774
00:48:23,356 --> 00:48:26,589
he inquired, after scanning
it on both sides.

775
00:48:26,589 --> 00:48:28,809
“I don’t seem to catch the excitement.

776
00:48:28,809 --> 00:48:32,513
Fremont County is going to hold elections.

777
00:48:32,513 --> 00:48:34,097
I see they claim Jake⁠—”

778
00:48:34,097 --> 00:48:38,541
“It’s mine,” I cut him off.

779
00:48:38,541 --> 00:48:39,922
“My own paper.

780
00:48:39,922 --> 00:48:41,547
Those are my pencil marks.”

781
00:48:41,547 --> 00:48:45,658
I do not think that a microscope could
have discerned a change in his face.

782
00:48:45,658 --> 00:48:50,868
“Oh,” he commented, holding the paper,
and fixing it with a critical eye.

783
00:48:50,868 --> 00:48:54,193
“You mean this is the one you lent Steve,
and he wanted to give me to

784
00:48:54,193 --> 00:48:55,096
give back to you.

785
00:48:55,096 --> 00:48:57,102
And so them are your own marks.”

786
00:48:57,102 --> 00:49:01,942
For a moment more he held it judicially,
as I have seen men hold a contract upon

787
00:49:01,942 --> 00:49:03,862
whose terms they were finally passing.

788
00:49:03,862 --> 00:49:06,622
“Well, you have got it back now, anyway.”

789
00:49:06,622 --> 00:49:07,702
And he handed it to me.

790
00:49:07,702 --> 00:49:09,698
“Only a piece of it!”

791
00:49:09,698 --> 00:49:12,224
I exclaimed, always lightly.

792
00:49:12,224 --> 00:49:18,235
And as I took it from him his hand
chanced to touch mine.

793
00:49:18,235 --> 00:49:20,607
It was cold as ice.

794
00:49:20,607 --> 00:49:25,427
“They ain’t through readin’ the
rest,” he explained easily.

795
00:49:25,427 --> 00:49:27,273
“Don’t you throw it away!

796
00:49:27,273 --> 00:49:29,534
After they’ve taken such trouble.”

797
00:49:29,534 --> 00:49:31,584
“That’s true,” I answered.

798
00:49:31,584 --> 00:49:35,002
“I wonder if it’s Pounds or
Ounces I’m indebted to.”

799
00:49:35,002 --> 00:49:39,254
Thus we made further merriment as we rode
down into the great basin.

800
00:49:39,254 --> 00:49:44,341
Before us, the horse and boot tracks
showed plain in the soft slough where

801
00:49:44,341 --> 00:49:46,461
melted snow ran half the day.

802
00:49:46,461 --> 00:49:50,266
“If it’s a paper chase,”
said the Virginian, “they’ll drop

803
00:49:50,266 --> 00:49:51,708
no more along here.”

804
00:49:51,708 --> 00:49:54,114
“Unless it gets dark,” said I.

805
00:49:54,114 --> 00:49:55,728
“We’ll camp before that.

806
00:49:55,728 --> 00:49:57,768
Maybe we’ll see their fire.”

807
00:49:57,768 --> 00:49:59,619
We did not see their fire.

808
00:49:59,619 --> 00:50:04,781
We descended in the chill silence,
while the mushroom rocks grew far and

809
00:50:04,781 --> 00:50:08,474
the sombre woods approached.

810
00:50:08,474 --> 00:50:13,526
By a stream we got off where two banks
sheltered us; for a bleak wind cut down

811
00:50:13,526 --> 00:50:18,999
over the crags now and then,
making the pines send out a great note

812
00:50:18,999 --> 00:50:22,182
through the basin, like breakers
in a heavy sea.

813
00:50:22,182 --> 00:50:24,756
But we made cozy in the tent.

814
00:50:24,756 --> 00:50:27,668
We pitched the tent this night,
and I was glad to have it shut

815
00:50:27,668 --> 00:50:29,202
out the mountain peaks.

816
00:50:29,202 --> 00:50:33,660
They showed above the banks where we
camped; and in the starlight their black

817
00:50:33,660 --> 00:50:36,482
shapes rose stark against the sky.

818
00:50:36,482 --> 00:50:41,993
They, with the pines and the wind,
were a bedroom too unearthly this night.

819
00:50:41,993 --> 00:50:46,513
And as soon as our supper dishes were
washed we went inside to our lantern and

820
00:50:46,513 --> 00:50:47,983
our game of cribbage.

821
00:50:47,983 --> 00:50:51,221
“This is snug,” said the
Virginian, as we played.

822
00:50:51,221 --> 00:50:53,129
“That wind don’t get down here.”

823
00:50:53,129 --> 00:50:55,831
“Smoking is snug, too,” said I.

824
00:50:55,831 --> 00:51:01,081
And we marked our points for an hour,
with no words save about the cards.

825
00:51:01,081 --> 00:51:04,932
“I’ll be pretty near glad when we get out
of these mountains,” said the Virginian.

826
00:51:04,932 --> 00:51:06,247
“They’re most too big.”

827
00:51:06,247 --> 00:51:11,272
The pines had altogether ceased;
but their silence was as tremendous as

828
00:51:11,272 --> 00:51:12,632
their roar had been.

829
00:51:12,632 --> 00:51:15,393
“I don’t know, though,” he resumed.

830
00:51:15,393 --> 00:51:20,214
“There’s times when the plains can
be awful big, too.”

831
00:51:20,214 --> 00:51:26,017
Presently we finished a hand,
and he said, “Let me see that paper.”

832
00:51:26,017 --> 00:51:31,010
He sat reading it apparently through,
while I arranged my blankets to

833
00:51:31,010 --> 00:51:34,971
make a warm bed.

834
00:51:34,971 --> 00:51:40,554
Then, since the paper continued to absorb
him, I got myself ready,

835
00:51:40,554 --> 00:51:43,256
and slid between my blankets
for the night.

836
00:51:43,256 --> 00:51:46,896
“You’ll need another candle soon in
that lantern,” said I.

837
00:51:46,896 --> 00:51:48,942
He put the paper down.

838
00:51:48,942 --> 00:51:51,629
“I would do it all over again,” he began.

839
00:51:51,629 --> 00:51:53,902
“The whole thing just the same.

840
00:51:53,902 --> 00:51:57,416
He knowed the customs of the country,
and he played the game.

841
00:51:57,416 --> 00:52:00,976
No call to blame me for the
customs of the country.

842
00:52:00,976 --> 00:52:07,219
You leave other folks’ cattle alone,
or you take the consequences,

843
00:52:07,219 --> 00:52:10,543
and it was all known to
Steve from the start.

844
00:52:10,543 --> 00:52:14,422
Would he have me take the Judge’s wages
and give him the wink?

845
00:52:14,422 --> 00:52:18,707
He must have changed a heap from the
Steve I knew if he expected that.

846
00:52:18,707 --> 00:52:20,355
I don’t believe he expected that.

847
00:52:20,355 --> 00:52:23,570
He knew well enough the only thing that
would have let him off would have

848
00:52:23,570 --> 00:52:25,639
been a regular jury.

849
00:52:25,639 --> 00:52:29,210
For the thieves have got hold of the
juries in Johnson County.

850
00:52:29,210 --> -1:59:59,000
I would do it all over, just the same.

851
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

852
00:52:32,544 --> 00:52:37,550
The expiring flame leaped in the
lantern, and fell blue.

853
00:52:37,550 --> 00:52:42,613
He broke off in his words as if to
arrange the light, but did not,

854
00:52:42,613 --> 00:52:47,366
sitting silent instead,
just visible, and seeming to watch the

855
00:52:47,366 --> 00:52:49,300
death struggle of the flame.

856
00:52:49,300 --> 00:52:53,526
I could find nothing to say to him,
and I believed he was now winning his

857
00:52:53,526 --> 00:52:56,101
way back to serenity by himself.

858
00:52:56,101 --> 00:53:01,069
He kept his outward man so nearly natural
that I forgot about that cold touch of

859
00:53:01,069 --> 00:53:02,349
his hand, and never guessed

860
00:53:02,349 --> 00:53:02,549
how

861
00:53:02,549 --> 00:53:02,949
far

862
00:53:02,949 --> 00:53:07,893
out from reason the tide of emotion was
even now whirling him.

863
00:53:07,893 --> 00:53:12,481
“I remember at Cheyenne
onced,” he resumed.

864
00:53:12,481 --> 00:53:17,336
And he told me of a Thanksgiving visit to
town that he had made with Steve.

865
00:53:17,336 --> 00:53:22,114
“We was just colts then,” he said.

866
00:53:22,114 --> 00:53:26,704
He dwelt on their coltish doings,
their adventures sought and wrought in

867
00:53:26,704 --> 00:53:28,845
the perfect fellowship of youth.

868
00:53:28,845 --> 00:53:33,638
“For Steve and me most always hunted in
couples back in them

869
00:53:33,638 --> 00:53:36,254
gamesome years,” he explained.

870
00:53:36,254 --> 00:53:41,387
And he fell into the elemental talk of
sex, such talk as would be an elk’s or

871
00:53:41,387 --> 00:53:45,120
tiger’s; and spoken so by him,
simply and naturally,

872
00:53:45,120 --> 00:53:49,220
as we speak of the seasons,
or of death, or of any actuality,

873
00:53:49,220 --> 00:53:51,120
it was without offense.

874
00:53:51,120 --> 00:53:53,574
It would be offense should I repeat it.

875
00:53:53,574 --> 00:53:57,832
Then, abruptly ending these memories of
himself and Steve, he went out of the

876
00:53:57,832 --> 00:54:00,845
tent, and I heard him dragging a
log to the fire.

877
00:54:00,845 --> 00:54:05,647
When it had blazed up,
there on the tent wall was his shadow

878
00:54:05,647 --> 00:54:08,887
and that of the log where he sat with
his half-broken heart.

879
00:54:08,887 --> 00:54:13,086
And all the while I supposed he was
master of himself, and self-justified

880
00:54:13,086 --> 00:54:16,388
against Steve’s omission
to bid him goodbye.

881
00:54:16,388 --> 00:54:20,860
I must have fallen asleep before he
returned, for I remember nothing except

882
00:54:20,860 --> 00:54:23,860
waking and finding him in
his blankets beside me.

883
00:54:23,860 --> 00:54:27,140
The fire shadow was gone,
and gray, cold light was

884
00:54:27,140 --> 00:54:28,493
dimly on the tent.

885
00:54:28,493 --> 00:54:34,553
He slept restlessly, and his forehead was
ploughed by lines of pain.

886
00:54:34,553 --> 00:54:40,087
While I looked at him he began to mutter,
and suddenly started up with violence.

887
00:54:40,087 --> 00:54:40,740
“No!”

888
00:54:40,740 --> 00:54:42,788
he cried out; “no!

889
00:54:42,788 --> 00:54:44,028
Just the same!”

890
00:54:44,028 --> 00:54:46,801
and thus wakened himself, staring.

891
00:54:46,801 --> 00:54:48,045
“What’s the matter?”

892
00:54:48,045 --> 00:54:48,820
he demanded.

893
00:54:48,820 --> 00:54:54,814
He was slow in getting back to where we
were; and full consciousness found him

894
00:54:54,814 --> 00:54:57,515
sitting up with his eyes fixed on mine.

895
00:54:57,515 --> 00:55:01,405
They were more haunted than they had been
at all, and his next speech came

896
00:55:01,405 --> 00:55:02,811
straight from his dream.

897
00:55:02,811 --> 00:55:04,711
“Maybe you’d better quit me.

898
00:55:04,711 --> 00:55:06,085
This ain’t your trouble.”

899
00:55:06,085 --> 00:55:06,940
I laughed.

900
00:55:06,940 --> 00:55:08,782
“Why, what is the trouble?”

901
00:55:08,782 --> 00:55:12,591
His eyes still intently fixed on mine.

902
00:55:12,591 --> 00:55:16,508
“Do you think if we changed our trail we
could lose them from us?”

903
00:55:16,508 --> 00:55:20,484
I was framing a jocose reply about Ounces
being a good walker,

904
00:55:20,484 --> 00:55:23,719
when the sound of hoofs rushing in the
distance stopped me,

905
00:55:23,719 --> 00:55:26,084
and he ran out of the
tent with his rifle.

906
00:55:26,084 --> 00:55:29,997
When I followed with mine he was up the
bank, and all his powers alert.

907
00:55:29,997 --> 00:55:34,847
But nothing came out of the dimness save
our three stampeded horses.

908
00:55:34,847 --> 00:55:39,481
They crashed over fallen timber and
across the open to where their picketed

909
00:55:39,481 --> 00:55:41,674
comrade grazed at the end of his rope.

910
00:55:41,674 --> 00:55:46,204
By him they came to a stand,
and told him, I suppose,

911
00:55:46,204 --> 00:55:51,000
what they had seen; for all four now
faced in the same direction,

912
00:55:51,000 --> 00:55:53,995
looking away into the mysterious dawn.

913
00:55:53,995 --> 00:55:57,912
We likewise stood peering,
and my rifle barrel felt cold in my

914
00:55:57,912 --> 00:55:58,730
hand.

915
00:55:58,730 --> 00:56:02,779
The dawn was all we saw,
the inscrutable dawn,

916
00:56:02,779 --> 00:56:08,191
coming and coming through the black
pines and the gray open of the basin.

917
00:56:08,191 --> 00:56:13,053
There above lifted the peaks,
no sun yet on them, and behind us our

918
00:56:13,053 --> 00:56:16,087
stream made a little tinkling.

919
00:56:16,087 --> 00:56:19,213
“A bear, I suppose,” said I, at length.

920
00:56:19,213 --> 00:56:23,860
His strange look fixed me again,
and then his eyes went to the horses.

921
00:56:23,860 --> 00:56:28,020
“They smell things we can’t smell,”
said he, very slowly.

922
00:56:28,020 --> 00:56:31,499
“Will you prove to me they don’t see
things we can’t see?”

923
00:56:31,499 --> 00:56:35,548
A chill shot through me,
and I could not help a frightened glance

924
00:56:35,548 --> 00:56:36,668
where we had been watching.

925
00:56:36,668 --> 00:56:41,074
But one of the horses began to graze and
I had a wholesome thought.

926
00:56:41,074 --> 00:56:44,740
“He’s tired of whatever he sees,
then,” said I, pointing.

927
00:56:44,740 --> 00:56:48,354
A smile came for a moment
in the Virginian’s face.

928
00:56:48,354 --> 00:56:51,061
“Must be a poor show,” he observed.

929
00:56:51,061 --> 00:56:54,101
All the horses were grazing now,
and he added, “It ain’t

930
00:56:54,101 --> 00:56:56,315
hurt their appetites any.”

931
00:56:56,315 --> 00:56:57,954
We made our own breakfast then.

932
00:56:57,954 --> 00:57:02,914
And what uncanny dread I may have been
touched with up to this time henceforth

933
00:57:02,914 --> 00:57:05,560
left me in the face of a real alarm.

934
00:57:05,560 --> 00:57:08,832
The shock of Steve was
working upon the Virginian.

935
00:57:08,832 --> 00:57:12,594
He was aware of it himself;
he was fighting it with all his might;

936
00:57:12,594 --> 00:57:14,135
and he was being overcome.

937
00:57:14,135 --> 00:57:17,554
He was indeed like a gallant swimmer
against whom both wind

938
00:57:17,554 --> 00:57:19,446
and tide have conspired.

939
00:57:19,446 --> 00:57:24,552
And in this now foreboding solitude there
was only myself to throw him ropes.

940
00:57:24,552 --> 00:57:28,024
His strokes for safety were as bold as
was the undertow that

941
00:57:28,024 --> 00:57:29,584
ceaselessly annulled them.

942
00:57:29,584 --> 00:57:32,114
“I reckon I made a fuss in the tent?”

943
00:57:32,114 --> 00:57:34,857
said he, feeling his way with me.

944
00:57:34,857 --> 00:57:35,942
I threw him a rope.

945
00:57:35,942 --> 00:57:36,772
“Yes.

946
00:57:36,772 --> -1:59:59,000
Nightmare⁠—indigestion⁠—too
much newspaper before retiring.

947
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

948
00:57:41,277 --> 00:57:42,667
He caught the rope.

949
00:57:42,667 --> 00:57:44,189
“That’s correct!

950
00:57:44,189 --> 00:57:46,948
I had a hell of a foolish dream for
a growed-up man.

951
00:57:46,948 --> 00:57:48,520
You’d not think it of me.”

952
00:57:48,520 --> 00:57:51,412
“Oh, yes, I should.

953
00:57:51,412 --> 00:57:56,223
I’ve had them after prolonged
lobster and champagne.”

954
00:57:56,223 --> 00:57:59,306
“Ah,” he murmured, “prolonged!

955
00:57:59,306 --> 00:58:01,222
Prolonged is what does it.”

956
00:58:01,222 --> 00:58:02,739
He glanced behind him.

957
00:58:02,739 --> 00:58:04,007
“Steve came back⁠—”

958
00:58:04,007 --> 00:58:06,258
“In your lobster dream,” I put in.

959
00:58:06,258 --> 00:58:08,816
But he missed this rope.

960
00:58:08,816 --> 00:58:12,721
“Yes,” he answered, with
his eyes searching me.

961
00:58:12,721 --> 00:58:14,140
“And he handed me the paper⁠—”

962
00:58:14,140 --> 00:58:16,215
“By the way, where is that?”

963
00:58:16,215 --> 00:58:16,950
I asked.

964
00:58:16,950 --> 00:58:18,708
“I built the fire with it.

965
00:58:18,708 --> 00:58:23,656
But when I took it from him it was a six-
shooter I had hold of,

966
00:58:23,656 --> 00:58:25,389
and pointing at my breast.

967
00:58:25,389 --> 00:58:27,599
And then Steve spoke.

968
00:58:27,599 --> 00:58:29,044
‘Do you think you’re fit to live?’

969
00:58:29,044 --> 00:58:32,720
Steve said; and I got hot at him,
and I reckon I must have told him what

970
00:58:32,720 --> 00:58:33,320
I thought of him.

971
00:58:33,320 --> 00:58:35,080
You heard me, I expect?”

972
00:58:35,080 --> 00:58:36,114
“Glad I didn’t.

973
00:58:36,114 --> 00:58:38,203
Your language sometimes is⁠—”

974
00:58:38,203 --> 00:58:39,093
He laughed out.

975
00:58:39,093 --> 00:58:42,690
“Oh, I account for all this that’s
happening just like you do.

976
00:58:42,690 --> 00:58:46,852
If we gave our explanations,
they’d be pretty near twins.”

977
00:58:46,852 --> 00:58:49,572
“The horses saw a bear, then?”

978
00:58:49,572 --> 00:58:50,371
“Maybe a bear.

979
00:58:50,371 --> -1:59:59,000
Maybe”⁠—but here the tide caught him
again⁠—“What’s your idea about dreams?

980
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

981
00:58:55,535 --> 00:58:57,054
My ropes were all out.

982
00:58:57,054 --> 00:59:01,937
“Liver⁠—nerves,” was the best I could do.

983
00:59:01,937 --> 00:59:05,313
But now he swam strongly by himself.

984
00:59:05,313 --> 00:59:10,239
“You may think I’m discreditable,”
he said, “but I know I am.

985
00:59:10,239 --> 00:59:15,243
It ought to take more than⁠—well,
men have lost their friendships before.

986
00:59:15,243 --> 00:59:19,265
Feuds and wars have cloven a right smart
of bonds in twain.

987
00:59:19,265 --> 00:59:22,995
And if my haid is going to get shook by a
little old piece of newspaper⁠—I’m

988
00:59:22,995 --> 00:59:24,448
ashamed I burned that.

989
00:59:24,448 --> -1:59:59,000
I’m ashamed to have been that weak.

990
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

991
00:59:26,555 --> 00:59:29,515
“Any man gets unstrung,” I told him.

992
00:59:29,515 --> 00:59:34,580
My ropes had become straws;
and I strove to frame some policy

993
00:59:34,580 --> 00:59:35,779
for the next hours.

994
00:59:35,779 --> 00:59:40,584
We now finished breakfast and set forth
to catch the horses.

995
00:59:40,584 --> 00:59:46,510
As we drove them in I found that the
Virginian was telling me a ghost story.

996
00:59:46,510 --> 00:59:51,207
“At half-past three in the morning she
saw her runaway daughter standing with a

997
00:59:51,207 --> 00:59:54,798
babe in her arms; but when she moved
it was all gone.

998
00:59:54,798 --> 01:00:01,010
Later they found it was the very same
hour the young mother died in Nogales.

999
01:00:01,010 --> 01:00:04,313
And she sent for the child
and raised it herself.

1000
01:00:04,313 --> 01:00:06,286
I knowed them both back home.

1001
01:00:06,286 --> 01:00:07,533
Do you believe that?”

1002
01:00:07,533 --> 01:00:08,530
I said nothing.

1003
01:00:08,530 --> 01:00:11,311
“No more do I believe it,” he asserted.

1004
01:00:11,311 --> 01:00:12,412
“And see here!

1005
01:00:12,412 --> 01:00:15,900
Nogales time is three
hours different from Richmond.

1006
01:00:15,900 --> 01:00:18,175
I didn’t know about that point then.”

1007
01:00:18,175 --> 01:00:21,568
Once out of these mountains,
I knew he could right himself;

1008
01:00:21,568 --> 01:00:27,280
but even I, who had no Steve to dream
about, felt this silence of the peaks

1009
01:00:27,280 --> 01:00:28,780
was preying on me.

1010
01:00:28,780 --> 01:00:31,900
“Her daughter and her might have been
thinkin’ mighty hard about each other

1011
01:00:31,900 --> 01:00:34,056
just then,” he pursued.

1012
01:00:34,056 --> 01:00:35,794
“But Steve is dead.

1013
01:00:35,794 --> 01:00:37,128
Finished.

1014
01:00:37,128 --> 01:00:39,213
You cert’nly don’t believe
there’s anything more?”

1015
01:00:39,213 --> 01:00:41,634
“I wish I could,” I told him.

1016
01:00:41,634 --> 01:00:43,440
“No, I’m satisfied.

1017
01:00:43,440 --> 01:00:45,706
Heaven didn’t never interest me much.

1018
01:00:45,706 --> 01:00:49,466
But if there was a world of dreams after
you went⁠—” He stopped himself and

1019
01:00:49,466 --> 01:00:51,597
turned his searching eyes away from
mine.

1020
01:00:51,597 --> 01:00:56,058
“There’s a heap o’ darkness wherever you
try to step,” he said,

1021
01:00:56,058 --> 01:00:59,880
“and I thought I’d left off wasting
thoughts on the subject.

1022
01:00:59,880 --> 01:01:05,664
You see”⁠—he dexterously roped a horse,
and once more his splendid sanity was

1023
01:01:05,664 --> 01:01:10,741
turned to gold by his imagination⁠—“I
expect in many growed-up men you’d call

1024
01:01:10,741 --> 01:01:16,381
sensible there’s a little boy sleepin’
⁠—the little kid they onced was⁠—that

1025
01:01:16,381 --> 01:01:18,021
still keeps his fear of the dark.

1026
01:01:18,021 --> 01:01:21,166
You mentioned the dark yourself yesterday.

1027
01:01:21,166 --> 01:01:26,031
Well, this experience has woke up that
kid in me, and blamed if I can coax the

1028
01:01:26,031 --> 01:01:28,815
little cuss to go to sleep again!

1029
01:01:28,815 --> 01:01:33,175
I keep a-telling him daylight will sure
come, but he keeps a-crying and

1030
01:01:33,175 --> -1:59:59,000
holding on to me.

1031
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

1032
01:01:34,376 --> 01:01:39,690
Somewhere far in the basin there was a
faint sound, and we stood still.

1033
01:01:39,690 --> 01:01:40,757
“Hush!”

1034
01:01:40,757 --> 01:01:42,170
he said.

1035
01:01:42,170 --> 01:01:46,958
But it was like our watching the
dawn; nothing more followed.

1036
01:01:46,958 --> 01:01:50,350
“They have shot that bear,” I remarked.

1037
01:01:50,350 --> 01:01:53,921
He did not answer, and we put the
saddles on without talk.

1038
01:01:53,921 --> 01:01:58,026
We made no haste, but we were not over
half an hour, I suppose,

1039
01:01:58,026 --> 01:01:59,966
in getting off with the packs.

1040
01:01:59,966 --> 01:02:03,791
It was not a new thing to hear a shot
where wild game was in plenty;

1041
01:02:03,791 --> 01:02:09,400
yet as we rode that shot sounded already
in my mind different from others.

1042
01:02:09,400 --> 01:02:13,315
Perhaps I should not believe this today
but for what I look back to.

1043
01:02:13,315 --> 01:02:18,271
To make camp last night we had turned off
the trail, and now followed the stream

1044
01:02:18,271 --> 01:02:23,531
down for a while, taking next a
cut through the wood.

1045
01:02:23,531 --> 01:02:28,223
In this way we came upon the tracks of
our horses where they had been galloping

1046
01:02:28,223 --> 01:02:32,662
back to the camp after their fright.

1047
01:02:32,662 --> 01:02:39,827
They had kicked up the damp and matted
pine needles very plainly all along.

1048
01:02:39,827 --> 01:02:44,047
“Nothing has been here but
themselves, though,” said I.

1049
01:02:44,047 --> 01:02:47,320
“And they ain’t showing signs of
remembering any scare,”

1050
01:02:47,320 --> 01:02:48,420
said the Virginian.

1051
01:02:48,420 --> 01:02:51,297
In a little while we emerged upon an open.

1052
01:02:51,297 --> 01:02:56,693
“Here’s where they was grazing,”
said the Virginian; and the

1053
01:02:56,693 --> 01:02:58,624
signs were clear enough.

1054
01:02:58,624 --> 01:03:01,973
“Here’s where they must have got
their scare,” he pursued.

1055
01:03:01,973 --> 01:03:05,651
“You stay with them while
I circle a little.”

1056
01:03:05,651 --> 01:03:11,244
So I stayed; and certainly our animals
were very calm at visiting this scene.

1057
01:03:11,244 --> 01:03:15,858
When you bring a horse back to where he
has recently encountered a wild animal

1058
01:03:15,858 --> 01:03:19,140
his ears and his nostrils are apt
to be wide awake.

1059
01:03:19,140 --> 01:03:22,396
The Virginian had stopped and
was beckoning to me.

1060
01:03:22,396 --> 01:03:26,324
“Here’s your bear,” said he, as I arrived.

1061
01:03:26,324 --> 01:03:28,150
“Two-legged, you see.

1062
01:03:28,150 --> 01:03:29,963
And he had a hawss of his own.”

1063
01:03:29,963 --> 01:03:34,863
There was a stake driven down where an
animal had been picketed for the night.

1064
01:03:34,863 --> 01:03:40,253
“Looks like Ounces,” I
said, considering the footprints.

1065
01:03:40,253 --> 01:03:41,819
“It’s Ounces.

1066
01:03:41,819 --> 01:03:45,972
And Ounces wanted another hawss very bad,
so him and Pounds could

1067
01:03:45,972 --> -1:59:59,000
travel like gentlemen should.

1068
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

1069
01:03:47,771 --> 01:03:51,273
“But Pounds doesn’t seem to
have been with him.”

1070
01:03:51,273 --> 01:03:57,552
“Oh, Pounds, he was making coffee,
somewheres in yonder, when this

1071
01:03:57,552 --> 01:03:58,112
happened.

1072
01:03:58,112 --> 01:04:02,383
Neither of them guessed there’d be other
hawsses wandering here in the night,

1073
01:04:02,383 --> 01:04:03,861
or they both would have come.”

1074
01:04:03,861 --> 01:04:06,069
He turned back to our pack animals.

1075
01:04:06,069 --> 01:04:08,757
“Then you’ll not hunt for this
camp to make sure?”

1076
01:04:08,757 --> 01:04:10,478
“I prefer making sure first.

1077
01:04:10,478 --> 01:04:12,809
We might be expected at that camp.”

1078
01:04:12,809 --> 01:04:16,226
He took out his rifle from beneath his
leg and set it across his

1079
01:04:16,226 --> 01:04:17,506
saddle at half-cock.

1080
01:04:17,506 --> 01:04:21,466
I did the same; and thus cautiously we
resumed our journey in

1081
01:04:21,466 --> 01:04:23,480
a slightly different direction.

1082
01:04:23,480 --> 01:04:26,359
“This ain’t all we’re going to find
out,” said the Virginian.

1083
01:04:26,359 --> 01:04:30,187
“Ounces had a good idea;
but I reckon he made a bad mistake

1084
01:04:30,187 --> -1:59:59,000
later.

1085
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

1086
01:04:31,296 --> 01:04:34,679
We had found out a good deal without
any more, I thought.

1087
01:04:34,679 --> 01:04:38,949
Ounces had gone to bring in their single
horse, and coming upon three more in the

1088
01:04:38,949 --> 01:04:43,709
pasture had undertaken to catch one and
failed, merely driving them where

1089
01:04:43,709 --> 01:04:44,698
he feared to follow.

1090
01:04:44,698 --> 01:04:49,020
“Shorty never could rope a
horse alone,” I remarked.

1091
01:04:49,020 --> 01:04:50,665
The Virginian grinned.

1092
01:04:50,665 --> 01:04:51,385
“Shorty?

1093
01:04:51,385 --> 01:04:54,795
Well, Shorty sounds as well as Ounces.

1094
01:04:54,795 --> -1:59:59,000
But that ain’t the mistake
I’m thinking he made.

1095
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

1096
01:04:57,342 --> 01:05:00,430
I knew that he would not tell me,
but that was just like him.

1097
01:05:00,430 --> 01:05:03,589
For the last twenty minutes,
having something to do,

1098
01:05:03,589 --> 01:05:07,449
he had become himself again,
had come to earth from that unsafe

1099
01:05:07,449 --> 01:05:11,711
country of the brain where
beckoned a spectral Steve.

1100
01:05:11,711 --> 01:05:16,392
Nothing was left but in his eyes that
question which pain had set there;

1101
01:05:16,392 --> 01:05:21,191
and I wondered if his friend of old,
who seemed so brave and amiable,

1102
01:05:21,191 --> 01:05:25,071
would have dealt him that hurt at the
solemn end had he known what a poisoned

1103
01:05:25,071 --> 01:05:26,292
wound it would be.

1104
01:05:26,292 --> 01:05:29,226
We came out on a ridge from which
we could look down.

1105
01:05:29,226 --> 01:05:32,802
“You always want to ride on high places
when there’s folks around whose

1106
01:05:32,802 --> 01:05:35,882
intentions ain’t been
declared,” said the Virginian.

1107
01:05:35,882 --> 01:05:39,004
And we went along our
ridge for some distance.

1108
01:05:39,004 --> 01:05:45,110
Then, suddenly he turned down and guided
us almost at once to the trail.

1109
01:05:45,110 --> 01:05:46,465
“That’s it,” he said.

1110
01:05:46,465 --> 01:05:47,092
“See.”

1111
01:05:47,092 --> 01:05:50,750
The track of a horse was very
fresh on the trail.

1112
01:05:50,750 --> 01:05:54,910
But it was a galloping horse now,
and no bootprints were keeping up

1113
01:05:54,910 --> 01:05:55,917
with it any more.

1114
01:05:55,917 --> 01:05:58,600
No boots could have kept up with it.

1115
01:05:58,600 --> 01:06:01,200
The rider was making time today.

1116
01:06:01,200 --> 01:06:06,769
Yesterday that horse had been ridden up
into the mountains at leisure.

1117
01:06:06,769 --> 01:06:07,851
Who was on him?

1118
01:06:07,851 --> 01:06:10,210
There was never to be any
certain answer to that.

1119
01:06:10,210 --> 01:06:12,506
But who was not on him?

1120
01:06:12,506 --> 01:06:16,789
We turned back in our journey,
back into the heart of that basin with

1121
01:06:16,789 --> 01:06:22,012
the tall peaks all rising like teeth in
the cloudless sun, and

1122
01:06:22,012 --> 01:06:24,636
the snowfields shining white.

1123
01:06:24,636 --> 01:06:27,602
“He was afraid of us,” said the Virginian.

1124
01:06:27,602 --> 01:06:30,609
“He did not know how many of us
had come up here.

1125
01:06:30,609 --> -1:59:59,000
Three hawsses might mean
a dozen more around.

1126
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

1127
01:06:35,243 --> 01:06:39,288
We followed the backward trail in among
the pines, and came after a

1128
01:06:39,288 --> 01:06:40,965
time upon their camp.

1129
01:06:40,965 --> 01:06:44,265
And then I understood the mistake
that Shorty had made.

1130
01:06:44,265 --> 01:06:48,578
He had returned after his failure,
and had told that other man of the

1131
01:06:48,578 --> 01:06:50,276
presence of new horses.

1132
01:06:50,276 --> 01:06:54,674
He should have kept this a secret;
for haste had to be made at once,

1133
01:06:54,674 --> 01:06:57,879
and two cannot get away
quickly upon one horse.

1134
01:06:57,879 --> 01:07:00,313
But it was poor Shorty’s last blunder.

1135
01:07:00,313 --> 01:07:06,222
He lay there by their extinct fire,
with his wistful, lost-dog face upward,

1136
01:07:06,222 --> 01:07:10,202
and his thick yellow hair unparted as
it had always been.

1137
01:07:10,202 --> 01:07:12,833
The murder had been done from behind.

1138
01:07:12,833 --> 01:07:14,575
We closed the eyes.

1139
01:07:14,575 --> 01:07:17,608
“There was no natural harm in
him,” said the Virginian.

1140
01:07:17,608 --> 01:07:20,252
“But you must do a thing
well in this country.”

1141
01:07:20,252 --> 01:07:24,186
There was not a trace,
not a clue, of the other man;

1142
01:07:24,186 --> 01:07:27,883
and we found a place where we could soon
cover Shorty with earth.

1143
01:07:27,883 --> 01:07:32,245
As we lifted him we saw the newspaper
that he had been reading.

1144
01:07:32,245 --> 01:07:37,298
He had brought it from the clump of
cottonwoods where he and the other man

1145
01:07:37,298 --> 01:07:43,257
had made a later visit than ours to be
sure of the fate of their friends⁠—or

1146
01:07:43,257 --> 01:07:46,249
possibly in hopes of another horse.

1147
01:07:46,249 --> 01:07:50,633
Evidently, when the party were surprised,
they had been able to

1148
01:07:50,633 --> 01:07:52,395
escape with only one.

1149
01:07:52,395 --> 01:08:01,992
All of the newspaper was there save the
leaf I had picked up⁠—all and more,

1150
01:08:01,992 --> 01:08:07,684
for this had pencil writing on it that
was not mine, nor did I at

1151
01:08:07,684 --> 01:08:08,796
first take it in.

1152
01:08:08,796 --> 01:08:12,414
I thought it might be a clue,
and I read it aloud.

1153
01:08:12,414 --> 01:08:14,655
“Goodbye, Jeff,” it said.

1154
01:08:14,655 --> 01:08:17,839
“I could not have spoke to you
without playing the baby.”

1155
01:08:17,839 --> 01:08:18,935
“Who’s Jeff?”

1156
01:08:18,935 --> 01:08:20,078
I asked.

1157
01:08:20,078 --> 01:08:23,444
But it came over me when I
looked at the Virginian.

1158
01:08:23,444 --> 01:08:27,759
He was standing beside me quite
motionless; and then he put out his hand

1159
01:08:27,759 --> 01:08:31,673
and took the paper, and stood still,
looking at the words.

1160
01:08:31,673 --> 01:08:36,436
“Steve used to call me Jeff,”
he said, “because I was Southern.

1161
01:08:36,436 --> 01:08:38,289
I reckon nobody else ever did.”

1162
01:08:38,289 --> 01:08:42,846
He slowly folded the message from the
dead, brought by the dead,

1163
01:08:42,846 --> 01:08:45,212
and rolled it in the
coat behind his saddle.

1164
01:08:45,212 --> 01:08:49,778
For a half-minute he stood leaning his
forehead down against the saddle.

1165
01:08:49,778 --> 01:08:53,822
After this he came back and
contemplated Shorty’s face awhile.

1166
01:08:53,822 --> 01:08:56,329
“I wish I could thank him,” he said.

1167
01:08:56,329 --> 01:08:57,570
“I wish I could.”

1168
01:08:57,570 --> 01:09:03,415
We carried Shorty over and covered him
with earth, and on that laid a few pine

1169
01:09:03,415 --> 01:09:08,175
branches; then we took up our journey,
and by the end of the forenoon we had

1170
01:09:08,175 --> 01:09:11,841
gone some distance upon our trail
through the Teton Mountains.

1171
01:09:11,841 --> 01:09:17,775
But in front of us the hoofprints ever
held their stride of haste,

1172
01:09:17,775 --> 01:09:22,059
drawing farther from us through the
hours, until by the next afternoon

1173
01:09:22,059 --> 01:09:26,769
somewhere we noticed they were no longer
to be seen; and after that they never

1174
01:09:26,769 --> 01:09:28,180
came upon the trail again.

1175
01:09:28,180 --> 01:09:29,568
CHAPTER XXXIII

1176
01:09:29,568 --> 01:09:32,088
The Spinster Loses Some Sleep

1177
01:09:32,088 --> 01:09:36,833
Somewhere at the eastern base of the
Tetons did those hoofprints disappear

1178
01:09:36,833 --> 01:09:41,406
into a mountain sanctuary where many
crooked paths have led.

1179
01:09:41,406 --> 01:09:45,994
He that took another man’s possessions,
or he that took another man’s life,

1180
01:09:45,994 --> 01:09:51,232
could always run here if the law or
popular justice were too

1181
01:09:51,232 --> 01:09:52,423
hot at his heels.

1182
01:09:52,423 --> 01:09:57,381
Steep ranges and forests walled him in
from the world on all four sides,

1183
01:09:57,381 --> 01:10:00,559
almost without a break;
and every entrance lay

1184
01:10:00,559 --> 01:10:02,475
through intricate solitudes.

1185
01:10:02,475 --> 01:10:06,973
Snake River came into the place through
canyons and mournful pines and marshes,

1186
01:10:06,973 --> 01:10:10,988
to the north, and went out at the
south between formidable chasms.

1187
01:10:10,988 --> 01:10:14,983
Every tributary to this stream rose among
high peaks and ridges,

1188
01:10:14,983 --> 01:10:18,749
and descended into the valley by well-
nigh impenetrable courses:

1189
01:10:18,749 --> 01:10:24,598
Pacific Creek from Two Ocean Pass,
Buffalo Fork from no pass at all,

1190
01:10:24,598 --> 01:10:30,357
Black Rock from the To-wo-ge-tee Pass⁠—
all these, and many more,

1191
01:10:30,357 --> 01:10:35,580
were the waters of loneliness,
among whose thousand hiding-places it

1192
01:10:35,580 --> 01:10:37,380
was easy to be lost.

1193
01:10:37,380 --> 01:10:41,260
Down in the bottom was a spread of level
land, broad and beautiful,

1194
01:10:41,260 --> 01:10:46,618
with the blue and silver Tetons rising
from its chain of lakes to the west,

1195
01:10:46,618 --> 01:10:50,423
and other heights presiding
over its other sides.

1196
01:10:50,423 --> 01:10:54,186
And up and down and in and out of this
hollow square of mountains,

1197
01:10:54,186 --> 01:10:59,326
where waters plentifully flowed,
and game and natural pasture abounded,

1198
01:10:59,326 --> 01:11:02,801
there skulked a nomadic
and distrustful population.

1199
01:11:02,801 --> 01:11:07,021
This in due time built cabins,
took wives, begot children,

1200
01:11:07,021 --> 01:11:11,259
and came to speak of itself as “The
honest settlers of Jackson’s Hole.”

1201
01:11:11,259 --> 01:11:15,780
It is a commodious title,
and doubtless today more accurate

1202
01:11:15,780 --> 01:11:17,174
than it was once.

1203
01:11:17,174 --> 01:11:20,390
Into this place the hoofprints
disappeared.

1204
01:11:20,390 --> 01:11:26,247
Not many cabins were yet built there;
but the unknown rider of the horse knew

1205
01:11:26,247 --> 01:11:32,061
well that he would find shelter and
welcome among the felons of his stripe.

1206
01:11:32,061 --> 01:11:36,786
Law and order might guess his name
correctly, but there was no next step,

1207
01:11:36,786 --> 01:11:40,351
for lack of evidence;
and he would wait, whoever he was,

1208
01:11:40,351 --> 01:11:44,832
until the rage of popular justice,
which had been pursuing him and his

1209
01:11:44,832 --> 01:11:46,642
brother thieves, should subside.

1210
01:11:46,642 --> 01:11:51,338
Then, feeling his way gradually with
prudence, he would let

1211
01:11:51,338 --> 01:11:52,786
himself be seen again.

1212
01:11:52,786 --> 01:11:58,612
And now, as mysteriously as he had melted
away, rumor passed over the country.

1213
01:11:58,612 --> 01:12:03,750
No tongue seemed to be heard telling the
first news; the news was there,

1214
01:12:03,750 --> 01:12:07,685
one day, a matter of whispered
knowledge.

1215
01:12:07,685 --> 01:12:13,386
On Sunk Creek and on Bear Creek,
and elsewhere far and wide,

1216
01:12:13,386 --> 01:12:18,338
before men talked men seemed secretly to
know that Steve, and Ed,

1217
01:12:18,338 --> 01:12:20,699
and Shorty, would never again be seen.

1218
01:12:20,699 --> 01:12:24,517
Riders met each other in the road and
drew rein to discuss the event,

1219
01:12:24,517 --> 01:12:27,149
and its bearing upon
the cattle interests.

1220
01:12:27,149 --> 01:12:34,205
In town saloons men took each other
aside, and muttered over it in corners.

1221
01:12:34,205 --> 01:12:38,946
Thus it reached the ears of Molly Wood,
beginning in a veiled and harmless

1222
01:12:38,946 --> 01:12:39,497
shape.

1223
01:12:39,497 --> 01:12:42,816
A neighbor joined her when she was
out riding by herself.

1224
01:12:42,816 --> 01:12:44,334
“Good morning,” said he.

1225
01:12:44,334 --> 01:12:45,911
“Don’t you find it lonesome?”

1226
01:12:45,911 --> 01:12:49,384
And when she answered lightly,
he continued, meaning well:

1227
01:12:49,384 --> 01:12:52,209
“You’ll be having company again soon
now.

1228
01:12:52,209 --> 01:12:56,781
He has finished his job.

1229
01:12:56,781 --> 01:12:58,614
Wish he’d finished it more!

1230
01:12:58,614 --> 01:12:59,908
Well, good day.”

1231
01:12:59,908 --> 01:13:02,414
Molly thought these words over.

1232
01:13:02,414 --> 01:13:06,111
She could not tell why they gave
her a strange feeling.

1233
01:13:06,111 --> 01:13:11,131
To her Vermont mind no suspicion of the
truth would come naturally.

1234
01:13:11,131 --> 01:13:15,390
But suspicion began to come when she
returned from her ride.

1235
01:13:15,390 --> 01:13:20,346
For, entering the cabin of the Taylors’,
she came upon several people who all

1236
01:13:20,346 --> 01:13:24,480
dropped their talk short,
and were not skilful at resuming it.

1237
01:13:24,480 --> 01:13:28,226
She sat there awhile,
uneasily aware that all of them knew

1238
01:13:28,226 --> 01:13:32,354
something which she did not know,
and was not intended to know.

1239
01:13:32,354 --> 01:13:36,334
A thought pierced her⁠—had anything
happened to her lover?

1240
01:13:36,334 --> 01:13:40,386
No; that was not it.

1241
01:13:40,386 --> 01:13:52,429
The man she had met on horseback spoke of
her having company soon again.

1242
01:13:52,429 --> 01:13:53,703
How soon?

1243
01:13:53,703 --> 01:13:54,569
she wondered.

1244
01:13:54,569 --> 01:13:59,172
He had been unable to say when he should
return, and now she suddenly felt that a

1245
01:13:59,172 --> 01:14:04,360
great silence had enveloped him lately:
not the mere silence of absence,

1246
01:14:04,360 --> 01:14:10,305
of receiving no messages or letters,
but another sort of silence which now,

1247
01:14:10,305 --> 01:14:15,808
at this moment, was weighing
strangely upon her.

1248
01:14:15,808 --> 01:14:21,219
And then the next day it came
out at the schoolhouse.

1249
01:14:21,219 --> 01:14:25,780
During that interval known as recess,
she became aware through the open window

1250
01:14:25,780 --> 01:14:28,020
that they were playing
a new game outside.

1251
01:14:28,020 --> 01:14:31,070
Lusty screeches of delight
reached her ears.

1252
01:14:31,070 --> 01:14:31,754
“Jump!”

1253
01:14:31,754 --> 01:14:33,000
a voice ordered.

1254
01:14:33,000 --> 01:14:33,695
“Jump!”

1255
01:14:33,695 --> 01:14:37,432
“I don’t want to,” returned
another voice, uneasily.

1256
01:14:37,432 --> 01:14:39,758
“You said you would,” said several.

1257
01:14:39,758 --> 01:14:41,472
“Didn’t he say he would?

1258
01:14:41,472 --> 01:14:45,961
Ah, he said he would.

1259
01:14:45,961 --> 01:14:48,319
Jump now, quick!”

1260
01:14:48,319 --> 01:14:52,959
“But I don’t want to,”
quavered the voice in a tone so dismal

1261
01:14:52,959 --> 01:14:54,766
that Molly went out to see.

1262
01:14:54,766 --> 01:14:59,610
They had got Bob Carmody on the top of
the gate by a tree, with a rope round

1263
01:14:59,610 --> 01:15:05,130
his neck, the other end of which four
little boys were joyously holding.

1264
01:15:05,130 --> 01:15:09,552
The rest looked on eagerly,
three little girls clasping their hands,

1265
01:15:09,552 --> 01:15:11,836
and springing up and
down with excitement.

1266
01:15:11,836 --> 01:15:13,775
“Why, children!”

1267
01:15:13,775 --> 01:15:14,963
exclaimed Molly.

1268
01:15:14,963 --> 01:15:19,819
“He’s said his prayers and everything,”
they all screamed out.

1269
01:15:19,819 --> 01:15:22,986
“He’s a rustler, and we’re lynchin’ him.

1270
01:15:22,986 --> 01:15:24,111
Jump, Bob!”

1271
01:15:24,111 --> 01:15:25,506
“I don’t want⁠—”

1272
01:15:25,506 --> 01:15:28,687
“Ah, coward, won’t take his medicine!”

1273
01:15:28,687 --> 01:15:31,719
“Let him go, boys,” said Molly.

1274
01:15:31,719 --> 01:15:32,819
“You might really hurt him.”

1275
01:15:32,819 --> 01:15:36,342
And so she broke up this game,
but not without general protest

1276
01:15:36,342 --> 01:15:38,263
from Wyoming’s young voice.

1277
01:15:38,263 --> 01:15:41,623
“He said he would,” Henry Dow assured her.

1278
01:15:41,623 --> 01:15:45,607
And George Taylor further explained:
“He said he’d be Steve.

1279
01:15:45,607 --> 01:15:47,823
But Steve didn’t scare.”

1280
01:15:47,823 --> 01:15:51,864
Then George proceeded to tell the
schoolmarm, eagerly,

1281
01:15:51,864 --> 01:15:56,098
all about Steve and Ed,
while the schoolmarm looked at him

1282
01:15:56,098 --> 01:15:57,338
with a rigid face.

1283
01:15:57,338 --> 01:16:01,019
“You promised your mother you’d not
tell,” said Henry Dow,

1284
01:16:01,019 --> 01:16:02,619
after all had been told.

1285
01:16:02,619 --> 01:16:04,779
“You’ve gone and done it,”
and Henry wagged his head

1286
01:16:04,779 --> 01:16:06,135
in a superior manner.

1287
01:16:06,135 --> 01:16:10,594
Thus did the New England girl learn what
her cowboy lover had done.

1288
01:16:10,594 --> 01:16:14,165
She spoke of it to nobody;
she kept her misery to herself.

1289
01:16:14,165 --> 01:16:17,168
He was not there to defend his act.

1290
01:16:17,168 --> 01:16:19,972
Perhaps in a way that was better.

1291
01:16:19,972 --> 01:16:24,438
But these were hours of darkness
indeed to Molly Wood.

1292
01:16:24,438 --> 01:16:28,558
On that visit to Dunbarton,
when at the first sight of her lover’s

1293
01:16:28,558 --> 01:16:35,492
photograph in frontier dress her aunt
had exclaimed, “I suppose there are days

1294
01:16:35,492 --> 01:16:40,251
when he does not kill people,”
she had cried in all good faith and

1295
01:16:40,251 --> 01:16:43,090
mirth, “He never killed anybody!”

1296
01:16:43,090 --> 01:16:47,524
Later, when he was lying in her cabin
weak from his bullet wound,

1297
01:16:47,524 --> 01:16:51,741
but each day stronger beneath her
nursing, at a certain word of his there

1298
01:16:51,741 --> 01:16:54,727
had gone through her a shudder of doubt.

1299
01:16:54,727 --> 01:16:59,674
Perhaps in his many wanderings he had
done such a thing in self-defence,

1300
01:16:59,674 --> 01:17:01,627
or in the cause of popular justice.

1301
01:17:01,627 --> 01:17:06,114
But she had pushed the idea away from her
hastily, back into the days before she

1302
01:17:06,114 --> 01:17:07,314
had ever seen him.

1303
01:17:07,314 --> 01:17:11,205
If this had ever happened,
let her not know of it.

1304
01:17:11,205 --> 01:17:15,418
Then, as a cruel reward for his candor
and his laying himself bare to her

1305
01:17:15,418 --> 01:17:20,011
mother, the letters from Bennington had
used that very letter of his as

1306
01:17:20,011 --> 01:17:21,281
a weapon against him.

1307
01:17:21,281 --> 01:17:23,923
Her sister Sarah had quoted from it.

1308
01:17:23,923 --> 01:17:29,059
“He says with apparent pride,”
wrote Sarah, “that he has never killed

1309
01:17:29,059 --> 01:17:31,782
for pleasure or profit.’

1310
01:17:31,782 --> 01:17:34,843
Those are his exact words,
and you may guess their

1311
01:17:34,843 --> 01:17:36,549
dreadful effect upon mother.

1312
01:17:36,549 --> 01:17:39,963
I congratulate you, my dear,
on having chosen a protector

1313
01:17:39,963 --> -1:59:59,000
so scrupulous.

1314
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

1315
01:17:41,126 --> 01:17:45,274
Thus her elder sister had seen fit to
write; and letters from less near

1316
01:17:45,274 --> 01:17:47,901
relatives made hints at the same
subject.

1317
01:17:47,901 --> 01:17:52,354
So she was compelled to accept this piece
of knowledge thrust upon her.

1318
01:17:52,354 --> 01:17:57,300
Yet still, still, those events had been
before she knew him.

1319
01:17:57,300 --> 01:18:00,556
They were remote, without
detail or context.

1320
01:18:00,556 --> 01:18:02,687
He had been little more than a boy.

1321
01:18:02,687 --> 01:18:05,127
No doubt it was to save his own life.

1322
01:18:05,127 --> 01:18:10,087
And so she bore the hurt of her discovery
all the more easily because her sister’s

1323
01:18:10,087 --> 01:18:13,350
tone roused her to defend her cowboy.

1324
01:18:13,350 --> 01:18:14,418
But now!

1325
01:18:14,418 --> 01:18:21,186
In her cabin, alone, after midnight,
she arose from her sleepless bed,

1326
01:18:21,186 --> 01:18:26,095
and lighting the candle,
stood before his photograph.

1327
01:18:26,095 --> 01:18:31,286
“It is a good face,” her great-aunt had
said, after some study of it.

1328
01:18:31,286 --> 01:18:34,054
And these words were in her mind now.

1329
01:18:34,054 --> 01:18:40,388
There his likeness stood at full length,
confronting her: the spurs on the boots,

1330
01:18:40,388 --> 01:18:44,881
the fringed leathern chaparreros,
the coiled rope in hand,

1331
01:18:44,881 --> 01:18:50,076
the pistol at hip, the rough flannel
shirt, and the scarf knotted at the

1332
01:18:50,076 --> 01:18:54,114
throat⁠—and then the grave
eyes, looking at her.

1333
01:18:54,114 --> 01:18:57,604
It thrilled her to meet them, even so.

1334
01:18:57,604 --> 01:18:59,391
She could read life into them.

1335
01:18:59,391 --> 01:19:03,208
She seemed to feel passion come from
them, and then something like reproach.

1336
01:19:03,208 --> 01:19:07,868
She stood for a long while looking at
him, and then, beating her hands

1337
01:19:07,868 --> 01:19:13,548
together suddenly, she blew out her
light and went back into bed,

1338
01:19:13,548 --> 01:19:16,394
but not to sleep.

1339
01:19:16,394 --> 01:19:20,502
“You’re looking pale,
deary,” said Mrs. Taylor to her,

1340
01:19:20,502 --> 01:19:21,782
a few days later.

1341
01:19:21,782 --> 01:19:22,742
“Am I?”

1342
01:19:22,742 --> 01:19:24,854
“And you don’t eat anything.”

1343
01:19:24,854 --> 01:19:26,247
“Oh, yes, I do.”

1344
01:19:26,247 --> 01:19:27,942
And Molly retired to her cabin.

1345
01:19:27,942 --> -1:59:59,000
“George,” said Mrs. Taylor,
“you come here.

1346
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

1347
01:19:31,064 --> 01:19:34,627
It may seem severe⁠—I think
that it was severe.

1348
01:19:34,627 --> 01:19:38,384
That evening when Mr. Taylor came home to
his family, George received

1349
01:19:38,384 --> 01:19:40,675
a thrashing for disobedience.

1350
01:19:40,675 --> 01:19:44,875
“And I suppose,” said Mrs. Taylor to her
husband, “that she came out just in time

1351
01:19:44,875 --> 01:19:47,866
to stop ’em breaking Bob
Carmody’s neck for him.”

1352
01:19:47,866 --> 01:19:51,617
Upon the day following Mrs.
Taylor essayed the impossible.

1353
01:19:51,617 --> 01:19:54,534
She took herself over
to Molly Wood’s cabin.

1354
01:19:54,534 --> 01:19:58,435
The girl gave her a listless greeting,
and the dame sat slowly down,

1355
01:19:58,435 --> 01:20:00,115
and surveyed the comfortable room.

1356
01:20:00,115 --> 01:20:04,770
“A very nice home, deary,”
said she, “if it was a home.

1357
01:20:04,770 --> 01:20:08,470
But you’ll fix something like this in
your real home, I have no doubt.”

1358
01:20:08,470 --> 01:20:10,043
Molly made no answer.

1359
01:20:10,043 --> 01:20:14,114
“What we’re going to do without you I
can’t see,” said Mrs. Taylor.

1360
01:20:14,114 --> 01:20:16,918
“But I’d not have it different for worlds.

1361
01:20:16,918 --> 01:20:19,466
He’ll be coming back soon, I expect.”

1362
01:20:19,466 --> 01:20:20,118
“Mrs.

1363
01:20:20,118 --> 01:20:24,973
Taylor,” said Molly, all at once,
“please don’t say anything now.

1364
01:20:24,973 --> 01:20:26,553
I can’t stand it.”

1365
01:20:26,553 --> 01:20:28,951
And she broke into wretched tears.

1366
01:20:28,951 --> 01:20:31,173
“Why, deary, he⁠—”

1367
01:20:31,173 --> 01:20:32,658
“No; not a word.

1368
01:20:32,658 --> 01:20:35,775
Please, please⁠—I’ll go out if you do.”

1369
01:20:35,775 --> 01:20:39,566
The older woman went to the younger one,
and then put her arms round her.

1370
01:20:39,566 --> 01:20:42,981
But when the tears were over,
they had not done any good;

1371
01:20:42,981 --> 01:20:48,824
it was not the storm that clears the
sky⁠—all storms do not clear the sky.

1372
01:20:48,824 --> 01:20:52,995
And Mrs. Taylor looked at the pale girl
and saw that she could do nothing to

1373
01:20:52,995 --> 01:20:55,577
help her toward peace of mind.

1374
01:20:55,577 --> 01:21:00,368
“Of course,” she said to her husband,
after returning from her profitless

1375
01:21:00,368 --> 01:21:02,852
errand, “you might know
she’d feel dreadful.

1376
01:21:02,852 --> 01:21:03,689
“What about?”

1377
01:21:03,689 --> 01:21:04,645
said Taylor.

1378
01:21:04,645 --> 01:21:11,716
“Why, you know just as well as I do.

1379
01:21:11,716 --> 01:21:15,196
And I’ll say for myself,
I hope you’ll never have

1380
01:21:15,196 --> 01:21:17,561
to help hang folks.”

1381
01:21:17,561 --> 01:21:23,251
“Well,” said Taylor, mildly,
“if I had to, I’d have to, I guess.”

1382
01:21:23,251 --> 01:21:26,385
“Well, I don’t want it to come.

1383
01:21:26,385 --> 01:21:30,841
But that poor girl is eating her heart
right out over it.”

1384
01:21:30,841 --> 01:21:31,861
“What does she say?”

1385
01:21:31,861 --> 01:21:33,411
“It’s what she don’t say.

1386
01:21:33,411 --> 01:21:37,952
She’ll not talk, and she’ll not let me
talk, and she sits and sits.”

1387
01:21:37,952 --> 01:21:40,707
“I’ll go talk some to her,” said the man.

1388
01:21:40,707 --> 01:21:43,452
“Well, Taylor, I thought
you had more sense.

1389
01:21:43,452 --> 01:21:45,303
You’d not get a word in.

1390
01:21:45,303 --> 01:21:48,505
She’ll be sick soon if her worry
ain’t stopped someway, though.”

1391
01:21:48,505 --> 01:21:51,049
“What does she want this country to do?”

1392
01:21:51,049 --> 01:21:52,085
inquired Taylor.

1393
01:21:52,085 --> 01:21:55,167
“Does she expect it to be
like Vermont when it⁠—”

1394
01:21:55,167 --> 01:21:59,091
“We can’t help what she
expects,” his wife interrupted.

1395
01:21:59,091 --> 01:22:00,673
“But I wish we could help her.”

1396
01:22:00,673 --> 01:22:04,118
They could not, however;
and help came from another source.

1397
01:22:04,118 --> 01:22:07,738
Judge Henry rode by the next day.

1398
01:22:07,738 --> 01:22:12,691
To him good Mrs. Taylor at
once confided her anxiety.

1399
01:22:12,691 --> 01:22:14,524
The Judge looked grave.

1400
01:22:14,524 --> 01:22:16,383
“Must I meddle?”

1401
01:22:16,383 --> 01:22:16,967
he said.

1402
01:22:16,967 --> 01:22:20,334
“Yes, Judge, you must,” said Mrs. Taylor.

1403
01:22:20,334 --> 01:22:23,730
“But why can’t I send him over here
when he gets back?

1404
01:22:23,730 --> -1:59:59,000
Then they’ll just settle
it between themselves.

1405
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

1406
01:22:27,392 --> 01:22:27,785
Mrs.

1407
01:22:27,785 --> 01:22:29,145
Taylor shook her head.

1408
01:22:29,145 --> 01:22:32,645
“That would unsettle it worse than it
is,” she assured him.

1409
01:22:32,645 --> 01:22:34,325
“They mustn’t meet just now.”

1410
01:22:34,325 --> 01:22:35,767
The Judge sighed.

1411
01:22:35,767 --> 01:22:38,774
“Well,” he said, “very well.

1412
01:22:38,774 --> 01:22:43,699
I’ll sacrifice my character,
since you insist.”

1413
01:22:43,699 --> 01:22:49,200
Judge Henry sat thinking,
waiting until school should be out.

1414
01:22:49,200 --> 01:22:52,675
He did not at all relish
what lay before him.

1415
01:22:52,675 --> 01:22:54,032
He would like to have got out of it.

1416
01:22:54,032 --> 01:22:57,475
He had been a federal judge;
he had been an upright judge;

1417
01:22:57,475 --> 01:23:02,178
he had met the responsibilities of his
difficult office not only with learning,

1418
01:23:02,178 --> 01:23:06,986
which is desirable, but also with
courage and common sense besides,

1419
01:23:06,986 --> 01:23:09,544
and these are essential.

1420
01:23:09,544 --> 01:23:12,420
He had been a stanch servant of the law.

1421
01:23:12,420 --> 01:23:16,712
And now he was invited to defend that
which, at first sight,

1422
01:23:16,712 --> 01:23:21,627
nay, even at second and third sight,
must always seem a defiance of the law

1423
01:23:21,627 --> 01:23:24,460
more injurious than crime itself.

1424
01:23:24,460 --> 01:23:30,298
Every good man in this world has
convictions about right and wrong.

1425
01:23:30,298 --> 01:23:34,083
They are his soul’s riches,
his spiritual gold.

1426
01:23:34,083 --> 01:23:39,506
When his conduct is at variance with
these, he knows that it is a departure,

1427
01:23:39,506 --> 01:23:44,289
a falling; and this is a
simple and clear matter.

1428
01:23:44,289 --> 01:23:48,889
If falling were all that ever happened to
a good man, all his days would be a

1429
01:23:48,889 --> 01:23:53,323
simple matter of striving and
repentance.

1430
01:23:53,323 --> 01:23:54,548
But it is not all.

1431
01:23:54,548 --> 01:24:01,038
There come to him certain junctures,
crises, when life, like a highwayman,

1432
01:24:01,038 --> 01:24:06,957
springs upon him, demanding that he
stand and deliver his convictions in the

1433
01:24:06,957 --> 01:24:12,285
name of some righteous cause,
bidding him do evil that good may come.

1434
01:24:12,285 --> 01:24:15,989
I cannot say that I believe in doing evil
that good may come.

1435
01:24:15,989 --> 01:24:17,391
I do not.

1436
01:24:17,391 --> 01:24:22,515
I think that any man who honestly
justifies such course deceives himself.

1437
01:24:22,515 --> 01:24:28,541
But this I can say: to call any act evil,
instantly begs the question.

1438
01:24:28,541 --> 01:24:34,718
Many an act that man does is right or
wrong according to the time and place

1439
01:24:34,718 --> 01:24:39,371
which form, so to speak,
its context; strip it of its surrounding

1440
01:24:39,371 --> 01:24:42,674
circumstances, and you
tear away its meaning.

1441
01:24:42,674 --> 01:24:46,964
Gentlemen reformers, beware of this
common practice of yours!

1442
01:24:46,964 --> 01:24:53,187
beware of calling an act evil on Tuesday
because that same act was evil on

1443
01:24:53,187 --> 01:24:53,936
Monday!

1444
01:24:53,936 --> 01:24:56,183
Do you fail to follow my meaning?

1445
01:24:56,183 --> 01:24:59,178
Then here is an illustration.

1446
01:24:59,178 --> 01:25:02,468
On Monday I walk over my neighbor’s
field; there is no wrong in such

1447
01:25:02,468 --> 01:25:03,039
walking.

1448
01:25:03,039 --> 01:25:08,276
By Tuesday he has put up a sign that
trespassers will be prosecuted

1449
01:25:08,276 --> 01:25:09,294
according to law.

1450
01:25:09,294 --> 01:25:12,444
I walk again on Tuesday,
and am a lawbreaker.

1451
01:25:12,444 --> 01:25:14,244
Do you begin to see my point?

1452
01:25:14,244 --> 01:25:18,202
or are you inclined to object to the
illustration because the walking on

1453
01:25:18,202 --> 01:25:21,887
Tuesday was not wrong,
but merely illegal?

1454
01:25:21,887 --> 01:25:25,446
Then here is another illustration which
you will find it a trifle

1455
01:25:25,446 --> 01:25:27,089
more embarrassing to answer.

1456
01:25:27,089 --> 01:25:31,517
Consider carefully, let me beg you,
the case of a young man and a young

1457
01:25:31,517 --> 01:25:36,877
woman who walk out of a door on Tuesday,
pronounced man and wife by a third

1458
01:25:36,877 --> 01:25:38,647
party inside the door.

1459
01:25:38,647 --> 01:25:43,883
It matters not that on Monday they were,
in their own hearts,

1460
01:25:43,883 --> 01:25:45,717
sacredly vowed to each other.

1461
01:25:45,717 --> 01:25:50,009
If they had omitted stepping inside that
door, if they had dispensed with that

1462
01:25:50,009 --> 01:25:54,643
third party, and gone away on Monday
sacredly vowed to each other in their

1463
01:25:54,643 --> 01:25:58,445
own hearts, you would have scarcely
found their conduct moral.

1464
01:25:58,445 --> 01:26:04,157
Consider these things carefully⁠—the
signpost and the third party⁠—and

1465
01:26:04,157 --> 01:26:05,557
the difference they make.

1466
01:26:05,557 --> 01:26:09,496
And now, for a finish,
we will return to the signpost.

1467
01:26:09,496 --> 01:26:16,143
Suppose that I went over my neighbor’s
field on Tuesday, after the signpost was

1468
01:26:16,143 --> 01:26:20,686
put up, because I saw a murder about to
be committed in the field,

1469
01:26:20,686 --> 01:26:24,235
and therefore ran in and stopped it.

1470
01:26:24,235 --> 01:26:28,392
Was I doing evil that good might come?

1471
01:26:28,392 --> 01:26:32,022
Do you not think that to stay out and let
the murder be done would have been the

1472
01:26:32,022 --> 01:26:34,394
evil act in this case?

1473
01:26:34,394 --> 01:26:38,713
To disobey the signpost was right;
and I trust that you now perceive the

1474
01:26:38,713 --> 01:26:43,835
same act may wear as many different hues
of right or wrong as the rainbow,

1475
01:26:43,835 --> 01:26:46,558
according to the atmosphere in
which it is done.

1476
01:26:46,558 --> 01:26:50,827
It is not safe to say of any man,
“He did evil that good might come.”

1477
01:26:50,827 --> 01:26:53,711
Was the thing that he did,
in the first place, evil?

1478
01:26:53,711 --> 01:26:55,404
That is the question.

1479
01:26:55,404 --> 01:26:59,119
Forgive my asking you to use your mind.

1480
01:26:59,119 --> 01:27:02,723
It is a thing which no novelist should
expect of his reader,

1481
01:27:02,723 --> 01:27:07,439
and we will go back at once to Judge
Henry and his meditations about

1482
01:27:07,439 --> 01:27:08,227
lynching.

1483
01:27:08,227 --> 01:27:11,875
He was well aware that if he was to touch
at all upon this subject with the New

1484
01:27:11,875 --> 01:27:15,955
England girl, he could not put her off
with mere platitudes and humdrum

1485
01:27:15,955 --> 01:27:19,874
formulas; not, at least,
if he expected to do any good.

1486
01:27:19,874 --> 01:27:23,505
She was far too intelligent,
and he was really anxious to do good.

1487
01:27:23,505 --> 01:27:28,686
For her sake he wanted the course of the
girl’s true love to run more smoothly,

1488
01:27:28,686 --> 01:27:32,566
and still more did he desire this for
the sake of his Virginian.

1489
01:27:32,566 --> 01:27:37,170
“I sent him myself on that business,”
the Judge reflected uncomfortably.

1490
01:27:37,170 --> 01:27:40,587
“I am partly responsible for the lynching.

1491
01:27:40,587 --> 01:27:48,543
It has brought him one great unhappiness
already through the death of Steve.

1492
01:27:48,543 --> 01:27:52,943
If it gets running in this girl’s mind,
she may⁠—dear me!”

1493
01:27:52,943 --> 01:27:56,437
the Judge broke off, “what a nuisance!”

1494
01:27:56,437 --> 01:27:57,437
And he sighed.

1495
01:27:57,437 --> 01:28:02,466
For as all men know, he also knew that
many things should be done in this world

1496
01:28:02,466 --> 01:28:06,369
in silence, and that talking about
them is a mistake.

1497
01:28:06,369 --> 01:28:10,812
But when school was out,
and the girl gone to her cabin,

1498
01:28:10,812 --> 01:28:16,223
his mind had set the subject in order
thoroughly, and he knocked at her door,

1499
01:28:16,223 --> 01:28:20,598
ready, as he had put it,
to sacrifice his character in the

1500
01:28:20,598 --> 01:28:22,146
cause of true love.

1501
01:28:22,146 --> 01:28:26,989
“Well,” he said, coming straight to the
point, “some dark things have happened.”

1502
01:28:26,989 --> 01:28:30,349
And when she made no answer to this,
he continued: “But you

1503
01:28:30,349 --> 01:28:32,495
must not misunderstand us.

1504
01:28:32,495 --> 01:28:34,920
We’re too fond of you for that.”

1505
01:28:34,920 --> 01:28:38,507
“Judge Henry,” said Molly Wood,
also coming straight to the point,

1506
01:28:38,507 --> 01:28:41,190
“have you come to tell me that you
think well of lynching?”

1507
01:28:41,190 --> 01:28:42,727
He met her.

1508
01:28:42,727 --> 01:28:47,854
“Of burning Southern negroes
in public, no.

1509
01:28:47,854 --> 01:28:53,728
Of hanging Wyoming cattle
thieves in private, yes.

1510
01:28:53,728 --> 01:28:55,819
You perceive there’s a
difference, don’t you?”

1511
01:28:55,819 --> 01:28:58,968
“Not in principle,” said the
girl, dry and short.

1512
01:28:58,968 --> 01:29:02,010
“Oh⁠—dear⁠—me!”

1513
01:29:02,010 --> 01:29:04,531
slowly exclaimed the Judge.

1514
01:29:04,531 --> 01:29:08,737
“I am sorry that you cannot see that,
because I think that I can.

1515
01:29:08,737 --> 01:29:11,623
And I think that you have just as much
sense as I have.”

1516
01:29:11,623 --> 01:29:16,114
The Judge made himself very grave and
very good-humored at the same time.

1517
01:29:16,114 --> 01:29:20,540
The poor girl was strung to a high pitch,
and spoke harshly in spite of herself.

1518
01:29:20,540 --> 01:29:22,505
“What is the difference in principle?”

1519
01:29:22,505 --> 01:29:23,844
she demanded.

1520
01:29:23,844 --> 01:29:27,291
“Well,” said the Judge,
easy and thoughtful,

1521
01:29:27,291 --> 01:29:28,837
“what do you mean by principle?”

1522
01:29:28,837 --> 01:29:32,347
“I didn’t think you’d
quibble,” flashed Molly.

1523
01:29:32,347 --> 01:29:33,844
“I’m not a lawyer myself.”

1524
01:29:33,844 --> 01:29:37,641
A man less wise than Judge Henry would
have smiled at this,

1525
01:29:37,641 --> 01:29:40,972
and then war would have exploded
hopelessly between them,

1526
01:29:40,972 --> 01:29:44,662
and harm been added to what
was going wrong already.

1527
01:29:44,662 --> 01:29:49,354
But the Judge knew that he must give to
every word that the girl said

1528
01:29:49,354 --> 01:29:52,075
now his perfect consideration.

1529
01:29:52,075 --> 01:29:55,641
“I don’t mean to quibble,” he assured her.

1530
01:29:55,641 --> 01:30:00,473
“I know the trick of escaping from one
question by asking another.

1531
01:30:00,473 --> 01:30:04,380
But I don’t want to escape from anything
you hold me to answer.

1532
01:30:04,380 --> 01:30:08,148
If you can show me that I am wrong,
I want you to do so.

1533
01:30:08,148 --> 01:30:13,111
But,” and here the Judge smiled,
“I want you to play fair, too.”

1534
01:30:13,111 --> 01:30:15,372
“And how am I not?”

1535
01:30:15,372 --> 01:30:24,423
“I want you to be just as willing to be
put right by me as I am to be

1536
01:30:24,423 --> 01:30:26,182
put right by you.

1537
01:30:26,182 --> 01:30:30,574
And so when you use such a word as
principle, you must help me to answer by

1538
01:30:30,574 --> 01:30:32,709
saying what principle you mean.

1539
01:30:32,709 --> 01:30:37,494
For in all sincerity I see no likeness in
principle whatever between burning

1540
01:30:37,494 --> 01:30:44,804
Southern negroes in public and hanging
Wyoming horse-thieves in private.

1541
01:30:44,804 --> 01:30:51,297
I consider the burning a proof that the
South is semi-barbarous,

1542
01:30:51,297 --> 01:30:57,985
and the hanging a proof that Wyoming is
determined to become civilized.

1543
01:30:57,985 --> 01:31:00,732
We do not torture our criminals
when we lynch them.

1544
01:31:00,732 --> 01:31:06,091
We do not invite spectators to
enjoy their death agony.

1545
01:31:06,091 --> 01:31:10,405
We put no such hideous disgrace
upon the United States.

1546
01:31:10,405 --> 01:31:15,725
We execute our criminals by the swiftest
means, and in the quietest way.

1547
01:31:15,725 --> 01:31:17,885
Do you think the principle is the same?”

1548
01:31:17,885 --> 01:31:20,757
Molly had listened to him with attention.

1549
01:31:20,757 --> 01:31:23,407
“The way is different,” she admitted.

1550
01:31:23,407 --> 01:31:24,628
“Only the way?”

1551
01:31:24,628 --> 01:31:26,029
“So it seems to me.

1552
01:31:26,029 --> 01:31:30,362
Both defy law and order.”

1553
01:31:30,362 --> 01:31:31,922
“Ah, but do they both?

1554
01:31:31,922 --> 01:31:33,407
Now we’re getting near the principle.”

1555
01:31:33,407 --> 01:31:34,500
“Why, yes.

1556
01:31:34,500 --> 01:31:37,695
Ordinary citizens take the law
in their own hands.”

1557
01:31:37,695 --> 01:31:39,604
“The principle at last!”

1558
01:31:39,604 --> 01:31:41,216
exclaimed the Judge.

1559
01:31:41,216 --> 01:31:43,951
“Now tell me some more things.

1560
01:31:43,951 --> 01:31:46,287
Out of whose hands do they take the law?”

1561
01:31:46,287 --> 01:31:47,168
“The court’s.”

1562
01:31:47,168 --> 01:31:50,109
“What made the courts?”

1563
01:31:50,109 --> 01:31:52,559
“I don’t understand.”

1564
01:31:52,559 --> 01:31:55,937
“How did there come to be any courts?”

1565
01:31:55,937 --> 01:31:55,937
“The Constitution.”

1566
01:31:55,937 --> 01:31:57,550
“How did there come to
be any Constitution?

1567
01:31:57,550 --> 01:31:58,310
Who made it?”

1568
01:31:58,310 --> 01:32:00,012
“The delegates, I suppose.”

1569
01:32:00,012 --> 01:32:01,329
“Who made the delegates?”

1570
01:32:01,329 --> 01:32:06,609
“I suppose they were elected,
or appointed, or something.”

1571
01:32:06,609 --> 01:32:08,050
“And who elected them?”

1572
01:32:08,050 --> 01:32:09,788
“Of course the people elected them.”

1573
01:32:09,788 --> 01:32:13,010
“Call them the ordinary
citizens,” said the Judge.

1574
01:32:13,010 --> 01:32:14,333
“I like your term.

1575
01:32:14,333 --> 01:32:17,541
They are where the law
comes from, you see.

1576
01:32:17,541 --> 01:32:20,730
For they chose the delegates who made the
Constitution that provided

1577
01:32:20,730 --> 01:32:23,171
for the courts.

1578
01:32:23,171 --> 01:32:24,651
There’s your machinery.

1579
01:32:24,651 --> 01:32:31,482
These are the hands into which ordinary
citizens have put the law.

1580
01:32:31,482 --> 01:32:35,082
So you see, at best, when they lynch they
only take back what they once gave.

1581
01:32:35,082 --> 01:32:38,830
Now we’ll take your two cases that you
say are the same in principle.

1582
01:32:38,830 --> 01:32:40,668
I think that they are not.

1583
01:32:40,668 --> 01:32:44,723
For in the South they take a negro from
jail where he was waiting

1584
01:32:44,723 --> 01:32:46,662
to be duly hung.

1585
01:32:46,662 --> 01:32:50,304
The South has never claimed that the law
would let him go.

1586
01:32:50,304 --> 01:32:55,569
But in Wyoming the law has been letting
our cattle-thieves go for two years.

1587
01:32:55,569 --> 01:32:59,595
We are in a very bad way,
and we are trying to make that way a

1588
01:32:59,595 --> 01:33:04,050
little better until civilization
can reach us.

1589
01:33:04,050 --> 01:33:06,932
At present we lie beyond its pale.

1590
01:33:06,932 --> 01:33:11,773
The courts, or rather the juries,
into whose hands we have put the law,

1591
01:33:11,773 --> 01:33:13,425
are not dealing the law.

1592
01:33:13,425 --> 01:33:17,015
They are withered hands,
or rather they are imitation hands made

1593
01:33:17,015 --> 01:33:19,925
for show, with no life in them, no grip.

1594
01:33:19,925 --> 01:33:21,845
They cannot hold a cattle-thief.

1595
01:33:21,845 --> 01:33:26,688
And so when your ordinary citizen sees
this, and sees that he has placed

1596
01:33:26,688 --> 01:33:35,389
justice in a dead hand,
he must take justice back into his own

1597
01:33:35,389 --> 01:33:38,719
hands where it was once at the
beginning of all things.

1598
01:33:38,719 --> 01:33:40,817
Call this primitive, if you will.

1599
01:33:40,817 --> 01:33:46,233
But so far from being a defiance of the
law, it is an assertion of it⁠—the

1600
01:33:46,233 --> 01:33:51,273
fundamental assertion of self governing
men, upon whom our whole

1601
01:33:51,273 --> 01:33:53,653
social fabric is based.

1602
01:33:53,653 --> 01:33:57,423
There is your principle,
Miss Wood, as I see it.

1603
01:33:57,423 --> 01:34:00,355
Now can you help me to
see anything different?”

1604
01:34:00,355 --> 01:34:01,355
She could not.

1605
01:34:01,355 --> 01:34:04,240
“But perhaps you are of
the same opinion still?”

1606
01:34:04,240 --> 01:34:05,555
the Judge inquired.

1607
01:34:05,555 --> 01:34:08,905
“It is all terrible to me,” she said.

1608
01:34:08,905 --> 01:34:12,133
“Yes; and so is capital
punishment terrible.

1609
01:34:12,133 --> 01:34:14,809
And so is war.

1610
01:34:14,809 --> 01:34:19,100
And perhaps some day we
shall do without them.

1611
01:34:19,100 --> 01:34:23,012
But they are none of them so terrible as
unchecked theft and murder would be.”

1612
01:34:23,012 --> 01:34:27,475
After the Judge had departed on his way
to Sunk Creek, no one spoke to

1613
01:34:27,475 --> 01:34:29,100
Molly upon this subject.

1614
01:34:29,100 --> 01:34:32,059
But her face did not grow
cheerful at once.

1615
01:34:32,059 --> 01:34:36,469
It was plain from her fits of silence
that her thoughts were not at rest.

1616
01:34:36,469 --> 01:34:41,026
And sometimes at night she would stand in
front of her lover’s likeness,

1617
01:34:41,026 --> 01:34:44,012
gazing upon it with both
love and shrinking.

1618
