From three canyons flowed three clear
forks which began the river.

1843
01:48:10,038 --> 01:48:14,979
Their confluence was above the town a
good two miles; it looked but a few

1844
01:48:14,979 --> 01:48:20,838
paces from up here, while each side the
river straggled the margin cottonwoods,

1845
01:48:20,838 --> 01:48:23,806
like thin borders along a garden walk.

1846
01:48:23,806 --> 01:48:30,574
Over all this map hung silence like a
harmony, tremendous yet serene.

1847
01:48:30,574 --> 01:48:31,614
“How beautiful!

1848
01:48:31,614 --> 01:48:33,368
how I love it!”

1849
01:48:33,368 --> 01:48:34,448
whispered the girl.

1850
01:48:34,448 --> 01:48:36,559
“But, oh, how big it is!”

1851
01:48:36,559 --> 01:48:38,752
And she leaned against her
lover for an instant.

1852
01:48:38,752 --> 01:48:41,139
It was her spirit seeking shelter.

1853
01:48:41,139 --> 01:48:45,450
Today, this vast beauty,
this primal calm, had in it for her

1854
01:48:45,450 --> 01:48:47,450
something almost of dread.

1855
01:48:47,450 --> 01:48:51,606
The small, comfortable,
green hills of home rose before her.

1856
01:48:51,606 --> 01:48:56,462
She closed her eyes and saw Vermont:
a village street, and the post-office,

1857
01:48:56,462 --> 01:49:00,022
and ivy covering an old front door,
and her mother picking some yellow

1858
01:49:00,022 --> 01:49:01,462
roses from a bush.

1859
01:49:01,462 --> 01:49:06,735
At a sound, her eyes quickly opened;
and here was her lover turned in his

1860
01:49:06,735 --> 01:49:09,485
saddle, watching another
horseman approach.

1861
01:49:09,485 --> 01:49:13,589
She saw the Virginian’s hand in a certain
position, and knew that

1862
01:49:13,589 --> 01:49:15,109
his pistol was ready.

1863
01:49:15,109 --> 01:49:20,178
But the other merely overtook and passed
them, as they stood at the

1864
01:49:20,178 --> 01:49:21,584
brow of the hill.

1865
01:49:21,584 --> 01:49:25,758
The man had given one nod to the
Virginian, and the Virginian one to him;

1866
01:49:25,758 --> 01:49:28,721
and now he was already below them
on the descending road.

1867
01:49:28,721 --> 01:49:33,589
To Molly Wood he was a stranger;
but she had seen his eyes when he nodded

1868
01:49:33,589 --> 01:49:37,756
to her lover, and she knew,
even without the pistol,

1869
01:49:37,756 --> 01:49:41,977
that this was not enmity at first sight.

1870
01:49:41,977 --> 01:49:45,587
It was not indeed.

1871
01:49:45,587 --> 01:49:49,531
Five years of gathered hate had looked
out of the man’s eyes.

1872
01:49:49,531 --> 01:49:52,532
And she asked her lover who this was.

1873
01:49:52,532 --> 01:49:56,123
“Oh,” said he, easily,
“just a man I see now and then.”

1874
01:49:56,123 --> 01:49:58,914
“Is his name Trampas?”

1875
01:49:58,914 --> 01:50:00,008
said Molly Wood.

1876
01:50:00,008 --> 01:50:02,937
The Virginian looked at her in surprise.

1877
01:50:02,937 --> 01:50:05,810
“Why, where have you seen him?”

1878
01:50:05,810 --> 01:50:07,004
he asked.

1879
01:50:07,004 --> 01:50:08,705
“Never till now.

1880
01:50:08,705 --> 01:50:09,804
But I knew.”

1881
01:50:09,804 --> 01:50:11,186
“My gracious!

1882
01:50:11,186 --> 01:50:14,670
Yu’ never told me yu’
had mind-reading powers.”

1883
01:50:14,670 --> 01:50:16,677
And he smiled serenely at her.

1884
01:50:16,677 --> 01:50:19,319
“I knew it was Trampas as soon as
I saw his eyes.”

1885
01:50:19,319 --> 01:50:20,343
“My gracious!”

1886
01:50:20,343 --> 01:50:23,106
her lover repeated with indulgent irony.

1887
01:50:23,106 --> 01:50:26,299
“I must be mighty careful of my eyes when
you’re lookin’ at ’em.”

1888
01:50:26,299 --> 01:50:28,981
“I believe he did that
murder,” said the girl.

1889
01:50:28,981 --> 01:50:30,564
“Whose mind are yu’ readin’ now?”

1890
01:50:30,564 --> 01:50:32,044
he drawled affectionately.

1891
01:50:32,044 --> 01:50:35,274
But he could not joke her off the subject.

1892
01:50:35,274 --> 01:50:39,312
She took his strong hand in hers,
tremulously, so much of it as her

1893
01:50:39,312 --> 01:50:40,872
little hand could hold.

1894
01:50:40,872 --> 01:50:45,686
“I know something about that⁠—that⁠—last
autumn,” she said, shrinking

1895
01:50:45,686 --> 01:50:47,406
from words more definite.

1896
01:50:47,406 --> 01:50:50,338
“And I know that you only did⁠—”

1897
01:50:50,338 --> 01:50:56,945
“What I had to,” he finished,
very sadly, but sternly, too.

1898
01:50:56,945 --> 01:51:01,366
“Yes,” she asserted, keeping
hold of his hand.

1899
01:51:01,366 --> 01:51:06,574
“I suppose that⁠—lynching⁠—” (she almost
whispered the word) “is the only way.

1900
01:51:06,574 --> 01:51:10,425
But when they had to die just for
stealing horses, it seems so

1901
01:51:10,425 --> 01:51:12,033
wicked that this murderer⁠—”

1902
01:51:12,033 --> 01:51:13,070
“Who can prove it?”

1903
01:51:13,070 --> 01:51:14,188
asked the Virginian.

1904
01:51:14,188 --> 01:51:15,381
“But don’t you know it?”

1905
01:51:15,381 --> 01:51:18,045
“I know a heap o’ things inside my heart.

1906
01:51:18,045 --> 01:51:19,977
But that’s not proving.

1907
01:51:19,977 --> 01:51:22,514
There was only the body,
and the hoofprints⁠—

1908
01:51:22,514 --> 01:51:24,467
and what folks guessed.”

1909
01:51:24,467 --> 01:51:26,889
“He was never even arrested!”

1910
01:51:26,889 --> 01:51:28,568
the girl said.

1911
01:51:28,568 --> 01:51:29,761
“No.

1912
01:51:29,761 --> -1:59:59,000
He helped elect the sheriff in that county

1913
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
.”

1914
01:51:32,828 --> 01:51:39,804
Then Molly ventured a step inside the
border of her lover’s reticence.

1915
01:51:39,804 --> 01:51:44,703
“I saw⁠—” she hesitated,
“just now, I saw what you did.”

1916
01:51:44,703 --> 01:51:47,113
He returned to his caressing irony.

1917
01:51:47,113 --> 01:51:50,222
“You’ll have me plumb scared if you
keep on seein’ things.”

1918
01:51:50,222 --> 01:51:52,025
“You had your pistol ready for him.”

1919
01:51:52,025 --> 01:51:54,431
“Why, I believe I did.

1920
01:51:54,431 --> 01:51:56,125
It was mighty unnecessary.”

1921
01:51:56,125 --> 01:52:00,545
And the Virginian took out the pistol
again, and shook his head over it,

1922
01:52:00,545 --> 01:52:03,040
like one who has been
caught in a blunder.

1923
01:52:03,040 --> 01:52:07,791
She looked at him, and knew that she must
step outside his reticence again.

1924
01:52:07,791 --> 01:52:12,780
By love and her surrender to him their
positions had been exchanged.

1925
01:52:12,780 --> 01:52:16,230
He was not now, as through his long
courting he had been,

1926
01:52:16,230 --> 01:52:19,155
her half-obeying, half-
refractory worshipper.

1927
01:52:19,155 --> 01:52:23,991
She was no longer his half-
indulgent, half-scornful superior.

1928
01:52:23,991 --> 01:52:28,173
Her better birth and schooling that had
once been weapons to keep him at his

1929
01:52:28,173 --> 01:52:33,105
distance, or bring her off victorious in
their encounters, had given way before

1930
01:52:33,105 --> 01:52:35,597
the onset of the natural man himself.

1931
01:52:35,597 --> 01:52:38,762
She knew her cowboy lover,
with all that he lacked,

1932
01:52:38,762 --> 01:52:43,315
to be more than ever she could be,
with all that she had.

1933
01:52:43,315 --> 01:52:46,576
He was her worshipper still,
but her master, too.

1934
01:52:46,576 --> 01:52:51,441
Therefore now, against the baffling smile
he gave her, she felt powerless.

1935
01:52:51,441 --> 01:52:55,664
And once again a pang of yearning for her
mother to be near her today

1936
01:52:55,664 --> 01:52:56,744
shot through the girl.

1937
01:52:56,744 --> 01:53:02,456
She looked from her untamed man to the
untamed desert of Wyoming,

1938
01:53:02,456 --> 01:53:06,273
and the town where she was to take him
as her wedded husband.

1939
01:53:06,273 --> 01:53:10,211
But for his sake she would not let
him guess her loneliness.

1940
01:53:10,211 --> 01:53:14,755
He sat on his horse Monte,
considering the pistol.

1941
01:53:14,755 --> 01:53:20,070
Then he showed her a rattlesnake coiled
by the roots of some sagebrush.

1942
01:53:20,070 --> 01:53:21,513
“Can I hit it?”

1943
01:53:21,513 --> 01:53:22,862
he inquired.

1944
01:53:22,862 --> 01:53:27,187
“You don’t often miss them,”
said she, striving to be cheerful.

1945
01:53:27,187 --> 01:53:29,923
“Well, I’m told getting
married unstrings some men.”

1946
01:53:29,923 --> 01:53:32,876
He aimed, and the snake was shattered.

1947
01:53:32,876 --> 01:53:37,770
“Maybe it’s too early yet for
the unstringing to begin!”

1948
01:53:37,770 --> 01:53:41,973
And with some deliberation he sent three
more bullets into the snake.

1949
01:53:41,973 --> 01:53:43,937
“I reckon that’s enough,” said he.

1950
01:53:43,937 --> 01:53:45,262
“Was not the first one?”

1951
01:53:45,262 --> 01:53:47,450
“Oh, yes, for the snake.”

1952
01:53:47,450 --> 01:53:51,170
And then, with one leg crooked cowboy
fashion across in front of his saddle-

1953
01:53:51,170 --> 01:53:55,501
horn, he cleaned his pistol,
and replaced the empty cartridges.

1954
01:53:55,501 --> 01:53:59,647
Once more she ventured near the
line of his reticence.

1955
01:53:59,647 --> 01:54:03,125
“Has⁠—has Trampas seen you much lately?”

1956
01:54:03,125 --> 01:54:06,104
“Why, no; not for a right smart while.

1957
01:54:06,104 --> 01:54:08,008
But I reckon he has not missed me.”

1958
01:54:08,008 --> 01:54:11,174
The Virginian spoke this
in his gentlest voice.

1959
01:54:11,174 --> 01:54:14,963
But his rebuffed sweetheart turned her
face away, and from her eyes

1960
01:54:14,963 --> 01:54:16,484
she brushed a tear.

1961
01:54:16,484 --> 01:54:22,084
He reined his horse Monte beside her,
and upon her cheek she felt his kiss.

1962
01:54:22,084 --> 01:54:27,371
“You are not the only mind-reader,”
said he, very tenderly.

1963
01:54:27,371 --> 01:54:31,458
And at this she clung to him,
and laid her head upon his breast.

1964
01:54:31,458 --> 01:54:35,321
“I had been thinking,”
he went on, “that the way our marriage

1965
01:54:35,321 --> 01:54:37,881
is to be was the most beautiful way.”

1966
01:54:37,881 --> 01:54:40,753
“It is the most beautiful,” she murmured.

1967
01:54:40,753 --> 01:54:44,681
He slowly spoke out his thought,
as if she had not said this.

1968
01:54:44,681 --> 01:54:51,192
“No folks to stare, no fuss,
no jokes and ribbons and best bonnets,

1969
01:54:51,192 --> 01:54:55,756
no public eye nor talkin’ of tongues
when most yu’ want to hear

1970
01:54:55,756 --> 01:54:59,140
nothing and say nothing.”

1971
01:54:59,140 --> 01:55:01,668
She answered by holding him closer.

1972
01:55:01,668 --> 01:55:06,831
“Just the bishop of Wyoming to join us,
and not even him after we’re once

1973
01:55:06,831 --> 01:55:07,390
joined.

1974
01:55:07,390 --> 01:55:10,910
I did think that would be ahead of all
ways to get married I have seen.”

1975
01:55:10,910 --> 01:55:13,790
He paused again, and she
made no rejoinder.

1976
01:55:13,790 --> 01:55:15,550
“But we have left out your mother.”

1977
01:55:15,550 --> 01:55:18,307
She looked in his face
with quick astonishment.

1978
01:55:18,307 --> 01:55:22,631
It was as if his spirit had heard the
cry of her spirit.

1979
01:55:22,631 --> 01:55:27,488
“That is nowhere near right,” he said.

1980
01:55:27,488 --> 01:55:30,159
“That is wrong.”

1981
01:55:30,159 --> 01:55:35,145
“She could never have come
here,” said the girl.

1982
01:55:35,145 --> 01:55:37,544
“We should have gone there.

1983
01:55:37,544 --> 01:55:40,363
I don’t know how I can ask
her to forgive me.”

1984
01:55:40,363 --> 01:55:42,724
“But it was not you!”

1985
01:55:42,724 --> 01:55:43,535
cried Molly.

1986
01:55:43,535 --> 01:55:44,437
“Yes.

1987
01:55:44,437 --> 01:55:46,357
Because I did not object.

1988
01:55:46,357 --> 01:55:49,468
I did not tell you we must go to her.

1989
01:55:49,468 --> 01:55:53,092
I missed the point, thinking so much
about my own feelings.

1990
01:55:53,092 --> 01:55:58,245
For you see⁠—and I’ve never said this to
you until now⁠—your mother did hurt me.

1991
01:55:58,245 --> 01:56:02,250
When you said you would have me after my
years of waiting, and I wrote her that

1992
01:56:02,250 --> 01:56:07,995
letter telling her all about myself,
and how my family was not like yours,

1993
01:56:07,995 --> 01:56:12,728
and⁠—and⁠—all the rest I told her,
why you see it hurt me never to get a

1994
01:56:12,728 --> 01:56:18,291
word back from her except
just messages through you.

1995
01:56:18,291 --> 01:56:22,057
For I had talked to her about my
hopes and my failings.

1996
01:56:22,057 --> 01:56:25,827
I had said more than ever I’ve said to
you, because she was your mother.

1997
01:56:25,827 --> 01:56:29,767
I wanted her to forgive me,
if she could, and feel that maybe I

1998
01:56:29,767 --> 01:56:31,806
could take good care of you after all.

1999
01:56:31,806 --> 01:56:34,807
For it was bad enough to have her
daughter quit her home to teach school

2000
01:56:34,807 --> 01:56:36,683
out hyeh on Bear Creek.

2001
01:56:36,683 --> 01:56:39,895
Bad enough without havin’ me to come
along and make it worse.

2002
01:56:39,895 --> 01:56:43,738
I have missed the point in thinking
of my own feelings.”

2003
01:56:43,738 --> 01:56:45,630
“But it’s not your doing!”

2004
01:56:45,630 --> 01:56:46,781
repeated Molly.

2005
01:56:46,781 --> 01:56:51,845
With his deep delicacy he had put the
whole matter as a hardship

2006
01:56:51,845 --> 01:56:54,137
to her mother alone.

2007
01:56:54,137 --> 01:56:57,998
He had saved her any pain
of confession or denial.

2008
01:56:57,998 --> 01:57:00,600
“Yes, it is my doing,” he now said.

2009
01:57:00,600 --> 01:57:01,738
“Shall we give it up?”

2010
01:57:01,738 --> 01:57:02,509
“Give what⁠—?”

2011
01:57:02,509 --> 01:57:03,980
She did not understand.

2012
01:57:03,980 --> 01:57:05,630
“Why, the order we’ve got it fixed in.

2013
01:57:05,630 --> 01:57:09,218
Plans are⁠—well, they’re
no more than plans.

2014
01:57:09,218 --> 01:57:13,020
I hate the notion of changing,
but I hate hurting your mother more.

2015
01:57:13,020 --> 01:57:15,493
Or, anyway, I ought to hate it more.

2016
01:57:15,493 --> 01:57:18,135
So we can shift, if yu’ say so.

2017
01:57:18,135 --> 01:57:19,991
It’s not too late.”

2018
01:57:19,991 --> 01:57:20,631
“Shift?”

2019
01:57:20,631 --> 01:57:21,591
she faltered.

2020
01:57:21,591 --> 01:57:24,896
“I mean, we can go to your home now.

2021
01:57:24,896 --> 01:57:27,323
We can start by the stage tonight.

2022
01:57:27,323 --> 01:57:29,722
Your mother can see us married.

2023
01:57:29,722 --> 01:57:33,707
We can come back and finish in the
mountains instead of beginning in them.

2024
01:57:33,707 --> -1:59:59,000
It’ll be just merely shifting, yu’ see.

2025
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

2026
01:57:36,905 --> 01:57:41,525
He could scarcely bring himself to say
this at all; yet he said it almost as if

2027
01:57:41,525 --> 01:57:42,605
he were urging it.

2028
01:57:42,605 --> 01:57:47,223
It implied a renunciation that he could
hardly bear to think of.

2029
01:57:47,223 --> 01:57:51,646
To put off his wedding day,
the bliss upon whose threshold he stood

2030
01:57:51,646 --> 01:57:56,206
after his three years of faithful battle
for it, and that wedding journey he had

2031
01:57:56,206 --> 01:58:01,383
arranged: for there were the mountains
in sight, the woods and canyons where he

2032
01:58:01,383 --> 01:58:04,816
had planned to go with her after the
bishop had joined them;

2033
01:58:04,816 --> 01:58:11,000
the solitudes where only the wild
animals would be, besides themselves.

2034
01:58:11,000 --> 01:58:16,453
His horses, his tent,
his rifle, his rod, all were waiting

2035
01:58:16,453 --> 01:58:18,583
ready in the town for
their start tomorrow.

2036
01:58:18,583 --> 01:58:22,604
He had provided many dainty things
to make her comfortable.

2037
01:58:22,604 --> 01:58:27,487
Well, he could wait a little more,
having waited three years.

2038
01:58:27,487 --> 01:58:32,767
It would not be what his heart most
desired: there would be the “public eye

2039
01:58:32,767 --> 01:58:36,433
and the talking of tongues”
⁠—but he could wait.

2040
01:58:36,433 --> 01:58:39,860
The hour would come when he could be
alone with his bride at last.

2041
01:58:39,860 --> 01:58:43,064
And so he spoke as if he urged it.

2042
01:58:43,064 --> 01:58:43,891
“Never!”

2043
01:58:43,891 --> 01:58:44,872
she cried.

2044
01:58:44,872 --> 01:58:46,610
“Never, never!”

2045
01:58:46,610 --> 01:58:47,962
She pushed it from her.

2046
01:58:47,962 --> 01:58:51,092
She would not brook such
sacrifice on his part.

2047
01:58:51,092 --> 01:58:54,254
Were they not going to her
mother in four weeks?

2048
01:58:54,254 --> 01:58:58,984
If her family had warmly accepted him⁠—
but they had not; and in any case,

2049
01:58:58,984 --> 01:59:01,407
it had gone too far, it was too late.

2050
01:59:01,407 --> 01:59:05,327
She told her lover that she would not
hear him, that if he said any more she

2051
01:59:05,327 --> 01:59:08,485
would gallop into town
separately from him.

2052
01:59:08,485 --> 01:59:13,966
And for his sake she would hide deep from
him this loneliness of hers,

2053
01:59:13,966 --> 01:59:18,632
and the hurt that he had given her in
refusing to share with her his trouble

2054
01:59:18,632 --> 01:59:21,711
with Trampas, when others
must know of it.

2055
01:59:21,711 --> 01:59:26,757
Accordingly, they descended the hill
slowly together, lingering to spin out

2056
01:59:26,757 --> 01:59:28,357
these last miles long.

2057
01:59:28,357 --> 01:59:32,994
Many rides had taught their horses to go
side by side, and so they went now:

2058
01:59:32,994 --> 01:59:38,250
the girl sweet and thoughtful in her
sedate gray habit; and the man in his

2059
01:59:38,250 --> 01:59:43,784
leathern chaps and cartridge belt and
flannel shirt, looking gravely into the

2060
01:59:43,784 --> 01:59:48,159
distance with the level
gaze of the frontier.

2061
01:59:48,159 --> 01:59:51,528
Having read his sweetheart’s mind very
plainly, the lover now

2062
01:59:51,528 --> 01:59:53,252
broke his dearest custom.

2063
01:59:53,252 --> 01:59:58,179
It was his code never to speak ill of any
man to any woman.

2064
01:59:58,179 --> 02:00:01,322
Men’s quarrels were not for women’s ears.

2065
02:00:01,322 --> 02:00:05,663
In his scheme, good women were to know
only a fragment of men’s lives.

2066
02:00:05,663 --> 02:00:10,664
He had lived many outlaw years,
and his wide knowledge of evil made

2067
02:00:10,664 --> 02:00:12,777
innocence doubly precious to him.

2068
02:00:12,777 --> 02:00:17,201
But today he must depart from his code,
having read her mind well.

2069
02:00:17,201 --> 02:00:22,024
He would speak evil of one man to one
woman, because his reticence had hurt

2070
02:00:22,024 --> 02:00:26,572
her⁠—and was she not far from her
mother, and very lonely,

2071
02:00:26,572 --> 02:00:27,479
do what he could?

2072
02:00:27,479 --> 02:00:33,255
She should know the story of his quarrel
in language as light and casual as he

2073
02:00:33,255 --> 02:00:34,458
could veil it with.

2074
02:00:34,458 --> 02:00:36,812
He made an oblique start.

2075
02:00:36,812 --> 02:00:39,698
He did not say to her:
“I’ll tell you about this.

2076
02:00:39,698 --> 02:00:43,002
You saw me get ready for Trampas because
I have been ready for him any

2077
02:00:43,002 --> 02:00:44,409
time these five years.”

2078
02:00:44,409 --> 02:00:49,127
He began far off from the point with that
rooted caution of his⁠—that caution

2079
02:00:49,127 --> 02:00:52,249
which is shared by the primal savage
and the perfected diplomat.

2080
02:00:52,249 --> 02:00:55,727
“There’s cert’nly a right smart o’
difference between men

2081
02:00:55,727 --> 02:00:57,171
and women,” he observed.

2082
02:00:57,171 --> 02:00:58,607
“You’re quite sure?”

2083
02:00:58,607 --> 02:00:59,540
she retorted.

2084
02:00:59,540 --> 02:01:02,277
“Ain’t it fortunate?⁠—that
there’s both, I mean.”

2085
02:01:02,277 --> 02:01:04,037
“I don’t know about fortunate.

2086
02:01:04,037 --> 02:01:08,077
Machinery could probably do all the heavy
work for us without your help.”

2087
02:01:08,077 --> 02:01:10,949
“And who’d invent the machinery?”

2088
02:01:10,949 --> 02:01:11,589
She laughed.

2089
02:01:11,589 --> 02:01:15,069
“We shouldn’t need the huge,
noisy things you do.

2090
02:01:15,069 --> 02:01:17,301
Our world would be a gentle one.”

2091
02:01:17,301 --> 02:01:19,097
“Oh, my gracious!”

2092
02:01:19,097 --> 02:01:20,753
“What do you mean by that?”

2093
02:01:20,753 --> 02:01:21,997
“Oh, my gracious!

2094
02:01:21,997 --> 02:01:23,356
Get along, Monte!

2095
02:01:23,356 --> 02:01:26,101
A gentle world all full of ladies!”

2096
02:01:26,101 --> 02:01:27,661
“Do you call men gentle?”

2097
02:01:27,661 --> 02:01:28,887
inquired Molly.

2098
02:01:28,887 --> 02:01:30,539
“Now it’s a funny thing about that.

2099
02:01:30,539 --> 02:01:33,962
Have yu’ ever noticed a joke
about fathers-in-law?

2100
02:01:33,962 --> 02:01:40,350
There’s just as many fathers⁠—as mothers-
in-law; but which side are your jokes?”

2101
02:01:40,350 --> 02:01:42,149
Molly was not vanquished.

2102
02:01:42,149 --> 02:01:45,481
“That’s because the men write the
comic papers,” said she.

2103
02:01:45,481 --> 02:01:46,867
“Hear that, Monte?

2104
02:01:46,867 --> 02:01:48,147
The men write ’em.

2105
02:01:48,147 --> 02:01:52,458
Well, if the ladies wrote a comic paper,
I expect that might be gentle.”

2106
02:01:52,458 --> -1:59:59,000
She gave up this battle in
mirth; and he resumed:⁠

2107
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
—

2108
02:01:55,435 --> 02:01:58,635
“But don’t you really reckon it’s
uncommon to meet a father-in-law

2109
02:01:58,635 --> 02:02:00,195
flouncin’ around the house?

2110
02:02:00,195 --> 02:02:06,451
As for gentle⁠—Once I had to sleep in a
room next a ladies’ temperance meetin’.

2111
02:02:06,451 --> 02:02:07,943
Oh, heavens!

2112
02:02:07,943 --> 02:02:12,791
Well, I couldn’t change my room,
and the hotel man, he apologized

2113
02:02:12,791 --> 02:02:14,438
to me next mawnin’.

2114
02:02:14,438 --> 02:02:17,483
Said it didn’t surprise him
the husbands drank some.”

2115
02:02:17,483 --> 02:02:21,904
Here the Virginian broke down over his
own fantastic inventions,

2116
02:02:21,904 --> 02:02:24,870
and gave a joyous chuckle in
company with his sweetheart.

2117
02:02:24,870 --> 02:02:31,022
“Yes, there’s a big heap o’ difference
between men and women,” he said.

2118
02:02:31,022 --> 02:02:33,448
“Take that fello’ and myself, now.”

2119
02:02:33,448 --> 02:02:34,417
“Trampas?”

2120
02:02:34,417 --> 02:02:37,261
said Molly, quickly serious.

2121
02:02:37,261 --> 02:02:41,773
She looked along the road ahead,
and discerned the figure of Trampas

2122
02:02:41,773 --> 02:02:44,548
still visible on its way to town.

2123
02:02:44,548 --> 02:02:48,757
The Virginian did not wish her to be
serious⁠—more than could be helped.

2124
02:02:48,757 --> 02:02:53,296
“Why, yes,” he replied,
with a waving gesture at Trampas.

2125
02:02:53,296 --> 02:02:54,809
“Take him and me.

2126
02:02:54,809 --> 02:02:56,697
He don’t think much o’ me!

2127
02:02:56,697 --> 02:02:58,314
How could he?

2128
02:02:58,314 --> 02:03:00,123
And I expect he’ll never.

2129
02:03:00,123 --> 02:03:03,294
But yu’ saw just now how
it was between us.

2130
02:03:03,294 --> 02:03:05,576
We were not a bit like
a temperance meetin’.”

2131
02:03:05,576 --> 02:03:08,992
She could not help laughing at the twist
he gave to his voice.

2132
02:03:08,992 --> 02:03:12,703
And she felt happiness warming her;
for in the Virginian’s tone about

2133
02:03:12,703 --> 02:03:16,809
Trampas was something now that
no longer excluded her.

2134
02:03:16,809 --> 02:03:21,936
Thus he began his gradual recital,
in a cadence always easy,

2135
02:03:21,936 --> 02:03:25,219
and more and more musical with the
native accent of the South.

2136
02:03:25,219 --> 02:03:30,448
With the light turn he gave it,
its pure ugliness melted into charm.

2137
02:03:30,448 --> 02:03:33,128
“No, he don’t think anything of me.

2138
02:03:33,128 --> 02:03:37,448
Once a man in the John Day Valley didn’t
think much, and by Cañada de

2139
02:03:37,448 --> 02:03:39,823
Oro I met another.

2140
02:03:39,823 --> 02:03:43,923
It will always be so here and there,
but Trampas beats ’em all.

2141
02:03:43,923 --> 02:03:47,901
For the others have always expressed
themselves⁠—got shut of their poor

2142
02:03:47,901 --> 02:03:49,233
opinion in the open air.”

2143
02:03:49,233 --> 02:03:54,775
“Yu’ see, I had to explain myself to
Trampas a right smart while ago,

2144
02:03:54,775 --> 02:03:57,535
long before ever I laid my eyes on yu’.

2145
02:03:57,535 --> 02:04:00,027
It was just nothing at all.

2146
02:04:00,027 --> 02:04:04,147
A little matter of cyards in the days
when I was apt to spend my money and

2147
02:04:04,147 --> 02:04:06,608
my holidays pretty headlong.

2148
02:04:06,608 --> 02:04:11,943
My gracious, what nonsensical
times I have had!

2149
02:04:11,943 --> 02:04:19,042
But I was apt to win at
cyards, ’specially poker.

2150
02:04:19,042 --> 02:04:23,477
And Trampas, he met me one night,
and I expect he must have thought I

2151
02:04:23,477 --> 02:04:24,978
looked kind o’ young.

2152
02:04:24,978 --> 02:04:30,079
So he hated losin’ his money to such a
young-lookin’ man, and he took his way

2153
02:04:30,079 --> 02:04:31,621
of sayin’ as much.

2154
02:04:31,621 --> 02:04:36,254
I had to explain myself to him plainly,
so that he learned right away my age

2155
02:04:36,254 --> 02:04:37,344
had got its growth.

2156
02:04:37,344 --> 02:04:42,013
“Well, I expect he hated that worse,
having to receive my explanation with

2157
02:04:42,013 --> 02:04:47,366
folks lookin’ on at us publicly that-a-
way, and him without further ideas

2158
02:04:47,366 --> 02:04:49,133
occurrin’ to him at the moment.

2159
02:04:49,133 --> 02:04:54,538
That’s what started his poor opinion of
me, not havin’ ideas at the moment.

2160
02:04:54,538 --> 02:04:58,660
And so the boys resumed their cyards.

2161
02:04:58,660 --> 02:05:00,177
“I’d most forgot about it.

2162
02:05:00,177 --> 02:05:03,872
But Trampas’s mem’ry is one
of his strong points.

2163
02:05:03,872 --> 02:05:09,074
Next thing⁠—oh, it’s a good while later⁠—
he gets to losin’ flesh because Judge

2164
02:05:09,074 --> 02:05:12,867
Henry gave me charge of him and some
other punchers taking cattle⁠—”

2165
02:05:12,867 --> 02:05:16,019
“That’s not next,” interrupted the girl.

2166
02:05:16,019 --> 02:05:17,125
“Not?

2167
02:05:17,125 --> 02:05:17,991
Why⁠—”

2168
02:05:17,991 --> 02:05:19,238
“Don’t you remember?”

2169
02:05:19,238 --> 02:05:22,705
she said, timid, yet eager.

2170
02:05:22,705 --> 02:05:23,495
“Don’t you?”

2171
02:05:23,495 --> 02:05:24,868
“Blamed if I do!”

2172
02:05:24,868 --> 02:05:26,086
“The first time we met?”

2173
02:05:26,086 --> 02:05:29,835
“Yes; my mem’ry keeps that⁠—
like I keep this.”

2174
02:05:29,835 --> 02:05:33,675
And he brought from his pocket her own
handkerchief, the token he had picked up

2175
02:05:33,675 --> 02:05:40,035
at a river’s brink when he had carried
her from an overturned stage.

2176
02:05:40,035 --> 02:05:45,226
“We did not exactly meet, then,” she said.

2177
02:05:45,226 --> 02:05:48,067
“It was at that dance.

2178
02:05:48,067 --> 02:05:51,778
I hadn’t seen you yet;
but Trampas was saying something horrid

2179
02:05:51,778 --> 02:05:58,253
about me, and you said⁠—you said,
‘Rise on your legs, you pole cat,

2180
02:05:58,253 --> 02:05:59,561
and tell them you’re a liar.’

2181
02:05:59,561 --> 02:06:03,468
When I heard that, I think⁠—I
think it finished me.”

2182
02:06:03,468 --> 02:06:09,555
And crimson suffused Molly’s countenance.

2183
02:06:10,015 --> 02:06:13,200
“I’d forgot,” the Virginian murmured.

2184
02:06:13,200 --> -1:59:59,000
Then sharply, “How did you hear it?

2185
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

2186
02:06:15,571 --> 02:06:16,316
“Mrs.

2187
02:06:16,316 --> 02:06:17,209
Taylor⁠—”

2188
02:06:17,209 --> 02:06:17,752
“Oh!

2189
02:06:17,752 --> 02:06:20,946
Well, a man would never have
told a woman that.”

2190
02:06:20,946 --> 02:06:22,956
Molly laughed triumphantly.

2191
02:06:22,956 --> 02:06:25,516
“Then who told Mrs. Taylor?”

2192
02:06:25,516 --> 02:06:27,556
Being caught, he grinned at her.

2193
02:06:27,556 --> 02:06:32,385
“I reckon husbands are a special kind of
man,” was all that he found to say.

2194
02:06:32,385 --> 02:06:36,890
“Well, since you do know about that,
it was the next move in the game.

2195
02:06:36,890 --> 02:06:40,999
Trampas thought I had no call to stop him
sayin’ what he pleased about a woman who

2196
02:06:40,999 --> 02:06:42,970
was nothin’ to me⁠—then.

2197
02:06:42,970 --> 02:06:46,214
But all women ought to be
somethin’ to a man.

2198
02:06:46,214 --> 02:06:49,917
So I had to give Trampas another
explanation in the presence of folks

2199
02:06:49,917 --> 02:06:54,221
lookin’ on, and it was
just like the cyards.

2200
02:06:54,221 --> 02:06:56,182
No ideas occurred to him again.

2201
02:06:56,182 --> 02:06:59,476
And down goes his opinion of me some more!

2202
02:06:59,476 --> 02:07:01,801
“Well, I have not been able to raise it.

2203
02:07:01,801 --> 02:07:06,774
There has been this and that and the
other⁠—yu’ know most of the later doings

2204
02:07:06,774 --> 02:07:10,894
yourself⁠—and today is the first time
I’ve happened to see the man since

2205
02:07:10,894 --> 02:07:12,534
the doings last autumn.

2206
02:07:12,534 --> 02:07:14,883
Yu’ seem to know about them, too.

2207
02:07:14,883 --> 02:07:19,397
He knows I can’t prove he was with that
gang of horse thieves.

2208
02:07:19,397 --> 02:07:22,270
And I can’t prove he killed poor Shorty.

2209
02:07:22,270 --> 02:07:26,951
But he knows I missed him awful close,
and spoiled his thieving for a while.

2210
02:07:26,951 --> 02:07:29,808
So d’ yu’ wonder he don’t
think much of me?

2211
02:07:29,808 --> 02:07:33,201
But if I had lived to be twenty-nine
years old like I am,

2212
02:07:33,201 --> 02:07:37,640
and with all my chances made no enemy,
I’d feel myself a failure.”

2213
02:07:37,640 --> 02:07:39,587
His story was finished.

2214
02:07:39,587 --> 02:07:44,384
He had made her his confidant in matters
he had never spoken of before,

2215
02:07:44,384 --> 02:07:46,899
and she was happy to be thus
much nearer to him.

2216
02:07:46,899 --> 02:07:50,819
It diminished a certain fear that was
mingled with her love of him.

2217
02:07:50,819 --> 02:07:54,319
During the next several miles he was
silent, and his silence

2218
02:07:54,319 --> 02:07:55,479
was enough for her.

2219
02:07:55,479 --> 02:08:01,013
Vermont sank away from her thoughts,
and Wyoming held less of loneliness.

2220
02:08:01,013 --> 02:08:05,430
They descended altogether into the map
which had stretched below them,

2221
02:08:05,430 --> 02:08:09,507
so that it was a map no longer,
but earth with growing things,

2222
02:08:09,507 --> 02:08:14,917
and prairie-dogs sitting upon it,
and now and then a bird flying over it.

2223
02:08:14,917 --> 02:08:17,947
And after a while she said to him,
“What are you thinking about?”

2224
02:08:17,947 --> 02:08:20,010
“I have been doing sums.

2225
02:08:20,010 --> 02:08:23,574
Figured in hours it sounds right short.

2226
02:08:23,574 --> 02:08:28,182
Figured in minutes it boils up
into quite a mess.

2227
02:08:28,182 --> 02:08:31,735
Twenty by sixty is twelve hundred.

2228
02:08:31,735 --> 02:08:35,924
Put that into seconds,
and yu’ get seventy-two thousand

2229
02:08:35,924 --> 02:08:36,935
seconds.

2230
02:08:36,935 --> 02:08:39,044
Seventy-two thousand.

2231
02:08:39,044 --> 02:08:42,995
Seventy-two thousand seconds yet
before we get married.”

2232
02:08:42,995 --> 02:08:44,296
“Seconds!

2233
02:08:44,296 --> 02:08:47,258
To think of its having come to seconds!”

2234
02:08:47,258 --> 02:08:49,228
“I am thinkin’ about it.

2235
02:08:49,228 --> 02:08:52,471
I’m choppin’ sixty of
’em off every minute.”

2236
02:08:52,471 --> 02:08:54,701
With such chopping time wears away.

2237
02:08:54,701 --> 02:08:59,141
More miles of the road lay behind them,
and in the virgin wilderness the scars

2238
02:08:59,141 --> 02:09:04,301
of new-scraped water ditches began to
appear, and the first wire fences.

2239
02:09:04,301 --> 02:09:07,641
Next, they were passing cabins and
occasional fields, the

2240
02:09:07,641 --> 02:09:09,373
outposts of habitation.

2241
02:09:09,373 --> 02:09:13,163
The free road became wholly imprisoned,
running between unbroken

2242
02:09:13,163 --> 02:09:14,925
stretches of barbed wire.

2243
02:09:14,925 --> 02:09:21,108
Far off to the eastward a flowing column
of dust marked the approaching stage,

2244
02:09:21,108 --> 02:09:25,664
bringing the bishop,
probably, for whose visit here they

2245
02:09:25,664 --> 02:09:26,997
had timed their wedding.

2246
02:09:26,997 --> 02:09:32,095
The day still brimmed with heat and
sunshine; but the great daily shadow was

2247
02:09:32,095 --> 02:09:36,000
beginning to move from the feet of the
Bow Leg Mountains outward

2248
02:09:36,000 --> 02:09:36,900
toward the town.

2249
02:09:36,900 --> 02:09:39,439
Presently they began to meet citizens.

2250
02:09:39,439 --> 02:09:44,892
Some of these knew them and nodded,
while some did not, and stared.

2251
02:09:44,892 --> 02:09:50,854
Turning a corner into the town’s chief
street, where stood the hotel,

2252
02:09:50,854 --> 02:09:55,211
the bank, the drug store,
the general store, and the seven

2253
02:09:55,211 --> 02:09:56,749
saloons, they were hailed heartily.

2254
02:09:56,749 --> 02:10:01,754
Here were three friends⁠—Honey Wiggin,
Scipio Le Moyne, and Lin McLean⁠—all

2255
02:10:01,754 --> 02:10:06,441
desirous of drinking the Virginian’s
health, if his lady⁠—would she mind?

2256
02:10:06,441 --> 02:10:08,556
The three stood grinning,
with their hats off;

2257
02:10:08,556 --> 02:10:12,863
but behind their gaiety the Virginian
read some other purpose.

2258
02:10:12,863 --> 02:10:15,759
“We’ll all be very good,”
said Honey Wiggin.

2259
02:10:15,759 --> 02:10:17,601
“Pretty good,” said Lin.

2260
02:10:17,601 --> 02:10:19,344
“Good,” said Scipio.

2261
02:10:19,344 --> 02:10:20,926
“Which is the honest man?”

2262
02:10:20,926 --> 02:10:23,520
inquired Molly, glad to see them.

2263
02:10:23,520 --> 02:10:24,540
“Not one!”

2264
02:10:24,540 --> 02:10:26,231
said the Virginian.

2265
02:10:26,231 --> 02:10:29,271
“My old friends scare me when I
think of their ways.”

2266
02:10:29,271 --> 02:10:33,144
“It’s bein’ engaged scares
yu’,” retorted Mr. McLean.

2267
02:10:33,144 --> 02:10:37,409
“Marriage restores your courage, I find.”

2268
02:10:37,409 --> 02:10:40,341
“Well, I’ll trust all of you,” said Molly.

2269
02:10:40,341 --> 02:10:44,460
“He’s going to take me to the hotel,
and then you can drink his health as

2270
02:10:44,460 --> 02:10:45,860
much as you please.”

2271
02:10:45,860 --> 02:10:50,221
With a smile to them she turned to
proceed, and he let his horse move with

2272
02:10:50,221 --> 02:10:51,989
hers; but he looked at his friends.

2273
02:10:51,989 --> 02:10:58,208
Then Scipio’s bleached blue eyes narrowed
to a slit, and he said what they had all

2274
02:10:58,208 --> 02:10:59,922
come out on the street to say:⁠—

2275
02:10:59,922 --> 02:11:02,484
“Don’t change your clothes.”

2276
02:11:02,484 --> 02:11:03,462
“Oh!”

2277
02:11:03,462 --> 02:11:11,075
protested Molly, “isn’t he
rather dusty and countrified?”

2278
02:11:11,075 --> 02:11:15,296
But the Virginian had
taken Scipio’s meaning.

2279
02:11:15,296 --> 02:11:18,063
“Don’t change your clothes.”

2280
02:11:18,063 --> 02:11:23,708
Innocent Molly appreciated these words no
more than the average reader who reads a

2281
02:11:23,708 --> 02:11:28,430
masterpiece, complacently unaware that
its style differs from that

2282
02:11:28,430 --> 02:11:29,377
of the morning paper.

2283
02:11:29,377 --> 02:11:34,372
Such was Scipio’s intention,
wishing to spare her from alarm.

2284
02:11:34,372 --> 02:11:39,860
So at the hotel she let her lover go with
a kiss, and without a thought of

2285
02:11:39,860 --> 02:11:40,720
Trampas.

2286
02:11:40,720 --> 02:11:46,271
She in her room unlocked the possessions
which were there waiting for her,

2287
02:11:46,271 --> 02:11:47,710
and changed her dress.

2288
02:11:47,710 --> 02:11:52,641
Wedding garments, and other civilized
apparel proper for a genuine

2289
02:11:52,641 --> 02:11:56,803
frontiersman when he comes to town,
were also in the hotel,

2290
02:11:56,803 --> 02:11:58,586
ready for the Virginian to wear.

2291
02:11:58,586 --> 02:12:03,162
It is only the somewhat green and
unseasoned cowpuncher who struts before

2292
02:12:03,162 --> 02:12:06,048
the public in spurs and deadly weapons.

2293
02:12:06,048 --> 02:12:11,558
For many a year the Virginian had put
away these childish things.

2294
02:12:11,558 --> 02:12:14,439
He made a sober toilet for the streets.

2295
02:12:14,439 --> 02:12:18,628
Nothing but his face and bearing remained
out of the common when he was in a town.

2296
02:12:18,628 --> 02:12:24,798
But Scipio had told him not to change his
clothes; therefore he went out with his

2297
02:12:24,798 --> 02:12:25,911
pistol at his hip.

2298
02:12:25,911 --> 02:12:29,956
Soon he had joined his three friends.

2299
02:12:29,956 --> 02:12:32,396
“I’m obliged to yu’,” he said.

2300
02:12:32,396 --> 02:12:34,535
“He passed me this mawnin’.”

2301
02:12:34,535 --> 02:12:37,459
“We don’t know his intentions,”
said Wiggin.

2302
02:12:37,459 --> 02:12:40,469
“Except that he’s hangin’
around,” said McLean.

2303
02:12:40,469 --> 02:12:43,458
“And fillin’ up,” said
Scipio, “which reminds me⁠—”

2304
02:12:43,458 --> 02:12:47,911
They strolled into the saloon of a
friend, where, unfortunately,

2305
02:12:47,911 --> 02:12:49,276
sat some foolish people.

2306
02:12:49,276 --> 02:12:54,222
But one cannot always tell how much of a
fool a man is, at sight.

2307
02:12:54,222 --> 02:12:57,136
It was a temperate health-
drinking that they made.

2308
02:12:57,136 --> 02:13:02,466
“Here’s how,” they muttered softly to the
Virginian; and “How,”

2309
02:13:02,466 --> 02:13:05,256
he returned softly, looking
away from them.

2310
02:13:05,256 --> 02:13:10,157
But they had a brief meeting of eyes,
standing and lounging near each other,

2311
02:13:10,157 --> 02:13:13,271
shyly; and Scipio shook
hands with the bridegroom.

2312
02:13:13,271 --> 02:13:17,384
“Some day,” he stated,
tapping himself; for in his vagrant

2313
02:13:17,384 --> 02:13:22,734
heart he began to envy the man who could
bring himself to marry.

2314
02:13:22,734 --> 02:13:26,080
And he nodded again, repeating,
“Here’s how.”

2315
02:13:26,080 --> 02:13:30,307
They stood at the bar,
full of sentiment, empty of words,

2316
02:13:30,307 --> 02:13:33,305
memory and affection
busy in their hearts.

2317
02:13:33,305 --> 02:13:38,625
All of them had seen rough days together,
and they felt guilty with emotion.

2318
02:13:38,625 --> 02:13:40,848
“It’s hot weather,” said Wiggin.

2319
02:13:40,848 --> 02:13:44,162
“Hotter on Box Elder,” said McLean.

2320
02:13:44,162 --> 02:13:46,258
“My kid has started teething.”

2321
02:13:46,258 --> 02:13:48,217
Words ran dry again.

2322
02:13:48,217 --> 02:13:51,941
They shifted their positions,
looked in their glasses,

2323
02:13:51,941 --> 02:13:53,618
read the labels on the bottles.

2324
02:13:53,618 --> 02:13:57,157
They dropped a word now and then to the
proprietor about his

2325
02:13:57,157 --> 02:13:59,257
trade, and his ornaments.

2326
02:13:59,257 --> 02:14:00,903
“Good head

2327
02:14:00,903 --> 02:14:03,251
,” commented McLean.

2328
02:14:03,251 --> 02:14:06,351
“Big old ram,” assented the proprietor.

2329
02:14:06,351 --> 02:14:10,082
“Shot him myself on Gray Bull last fall.”

2330
02:14:10,082 --> 02:14:14,301
“Sheep was thick in the Tetons last
fall,” said the Virginian.

2331
02:14:14,301 --> 02:14:20,794
On the bar stood a machine into which the
idle customer might drop his nickel.

2332
02:14:20,794 --> 02:14:24,642
The coin then bounced among an
arrangement of pegs,

2333
02:14:24,642 --> 02:14:29,175
descending at length into one or
another of various holes.

2334
02:14:29,175 --> 02:14:33,732
You might win as much as ten times your
stake, but this was not the most usual

2335
02:14:33,732 --> 02:14:38,753
result; and with nickels the three
friends and the bridegroom now mildly

2336
02:14:38,753 --> 02:14:41,494
sported for a while,
buying them with silver when

2337
02:14:41,494 --> 02:14:42,594
their store ran out.

2338
02:14:42,594 --> 02:14:45,787
“Was it sheep you went
after in the Tetons?”

2339
02:14:45,787 --> 02:14:50,410
inquired the proprietor,
knowing it was horse thieves.

2340
02:14:50,410 --> 02:14:53,444
“Yes,” said the Virginian.

2341
02:14:53,444 --> 02:14:55,040
“I’ll have ten more nickels.”

2342
02:14:55,040 --> 02:14:56,722
“Did you get all the sheep you wanted?”

2343
02:14:56,722 --> 02:14:58,052
the proprietor continued.

2344
02:14:58,052 --> 02:15:00,828
“Poor luck,” said the Virginian.

2345
02:15:00,828 --> 02:15:05,075
“Think there’s a friend of yours in town
this afternoon,” said the proprietor.

2346
02:15:05,075 --> 02:15:06,889
“Did he mention he was my friend?”

2347
02:15:06,889 --> 02:15:08,270
The proprietor laughed.

2348
02:15:08,270 --> 02:15:12,735
The Virginian watched another nickel
click down among the pegs.

2349
02:15:12,735 --> 02:15:16,341
Honey Wiggin now made the
bridegroom a straight offer.

2350
02:15:16,341 --> 02:15:19,852
“We’ll take this thing off
your hands,” said he.

2351
02:15:19,852 --> 02:15:23,629
“Any or all of us,” said Lin.

2352
02:15:23,629 --> 02:15:27,020
But Scipio held his peace.

2353
02:15:27,020 --> 02:15:31,262
His loyalty went every inch as far as
theirs, but his understanding of

2354
02:15:31,262 --> 02:15:33,351
his friend went deeper.

2355
02:15:33,351 --> 02:15:38,476
“Don’t change your clothes,”
was the first and the last help he would

2356
02:15:38,476 --> 02:15:40,326
be likely to give in this matter.

2357
02:15:40,326 --> 02:15:46,716
The rest must be as such matters must
always be, between man and man.

2358
02:15:46,716 --> 02:15:49,903
To the other two friends,
however, this seemed a very special

2359
02:15:49,903 --> 02:15:53,036
case, falling outside
established precedent.

2360
02:15:53,036 --> 02:15:57,122
Therefore they ventured
offers of interference.

2361
02:15:57,122 --> 02:16:01,322
“A man don’t get married
every day,” apologized McLean.

2362
02:16:01,322 --> 02:16:03,380
“We’ll just run him out of town for yu’.”

2363
02:16:03,380 --> 02:16:06,315
“Save yu’ the trouble,” urged Wiggin.

2364
02:16:06,315 --> 02:16:07,840
“Say the word.”

2365
02:16:07,840 --> 02:16:10,334
The proprietor now added his voice.

2366
02:16:10,334 --> 02:16:13,784
“It’ll sober him up to spend his night
out in the brush.

2367
02:16:13,784 --> -1:59:59,000
He’ll quit his talk then.

2368
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

2369
02:16:15,014 --> 02:16:18,696
But the Virginian did not say the
word, or any word.

2370
02:16:18,696 --> 02:16:20,547
He stood playing with the nickels.

2371
02:16:20,547 --> 02:16:23,823
“Think of her,” muttered McLean.

2372
02:16:23,823 --> 02:16:26,156
“Who else would I be thinking of?”

2373
02:16:26,156 --> 02:16:27,245
returned the Southerner.

2374
02:16:27,245 --> 02:16:29,861
His face had become very sombre.

2375
02:16:29,861 --> 02:16:32,419
“She has been raised so different!”

2376
02:16:32,419 --> 02:16:33,577
he murmured.

2377
02:16:33,577 --> 02:16:38,286
He pondered a little,
while the others waited, solicitous.

2378
02:16:38,286 --> 02:16:40,845
A new idea came to the proprietor.

2379
02:16:40,845 --> 02:16:43,621
“I am acting mayor of this town,” said he.

2380
02:16:43,621 --> 02:16:46,590
“I’ll put him in the calaboose and keep
him till you get married and away.”

2381
02:16:46,590 --> 02:16:48,866
“Say the word,” repeated Honey Wiggin.

2382
02:16:48,866 --> 02:16:52,621
Scipio’s eye met the proprietor’s,
and he shook his head about a

2383
02:16:52,621 --> 02:16:53,785
quarter of an inch.

2384
02:16:53,785 --> 02:16:57,043
The proprietor shook his
to the same amount.

2385
02:16:57,043 --> 02:16:58,643
They understood each other.

2386
02:16:58,643 --> 02:17:03,213
It had come to that point where there was
no way out, save only the ancient,

2387
02:17:03,213 --> 02:17:06,614
eternal way between man and man.

2388
02:17:06,614 --> 02:17:13,169
It is only the great mediocrity that goes
to law in these personal matters.

2389
02:17:13,169 --> 02:17:15,969
“So he has talked about me some?”

2390
02:17:15,969 --> 02:17:16,800
said the Virginian.

2391
02:17:16,800 --> 02:17:19,662
“It’s the whiskey,” Scipio explained.

2392
02:17:19,662 --> 02:17:24,051
“I expect,” said McLean,
“he’d run a mile if he was in a state

2393
02:17:24,051 --> 02:17:26,958
to appreciate his insinuations.”

2394
02:17:26,958 --> 02:17:30,752
“Which we are careful not to mention to
yu’,” said Wiggin, “unless

2395
02:17:30,752 --> 02:17:32,162
yu’ inquire for ’em.”

2396
02:17:32,162 --> 02:17:35,680
Some of the fools present had drawn
closer to hear this interesting

2397
02:17:35,680 --> 02:17:37,251
conversation.

2398
02:17:37,251 --> 02:17:42,193
In gatherings of more than six there will
generally be at least one fool;

2399
02:17:42,193 --> 02:17:44,808
and this company must
have numbered twenty men.

2400
02:17:44,808 --> 02:17:48,998
“This country knows well enough,”
said one fool, who hungered to be

2401
02:17:48,998 --> 02:17:52,614
important, “that you don’t brand no
calves that ain’t your own.”

2402
02:17:52,614 --> 02:17:54,644
The saturnine Virginian looked at him.

2403
02:17:54,644 --> 02:17:57,789
“Thank yu’,” said he,
gravely, “for your endorsement

2404
02:17:57,789 --> 02:17:59,529
of my character.”

2405
02:17:59,529 --> 02:18:01,529
The fool felt flattered.

2406
02:18:01,529 --> 02:18:04,085
The Virginian turned to his friends.

2407
02:18:04,085 --> 02:18:09,281
His hand slowly pushed his hat back,
and he rubbed his black head in thought.

2408
02:18:09,281 --> 02:18:13,786
“Glad to see yu’ve got your gun with
you,” continued the happy fool.

2409
02:18:13,786 --> 02:18:18,742
“You know what Trampas claims about that
affair of yours in the Tetons?

2410
02:18:18,742 --> 02:18:22,357
He claims that if everything was known
about the killing of Shorty⁠—”

2411
02:18:22,357 --> 02:18:26,749
“Take one on the house,”
suggested the proprietor to him,

2412
02:18:26,749 --> 02:18:27,583
amiably.

2413
02:18:27,583 --> 02:18:29,773
“Your news will be fresher.”

2414
02:18:29,773 --> 02:18:31,252
And he pushed him the bottle.

2415
02:18:31,252 --> 02:18:35,243
The fool felt less important.

2416
02:18:35,243 --> 02:18:38,993
“This talk had went the rounds before it
got to us,” said Scipio,

2417
02:18:38,993 --> 02:18:40,708
“or we’d have headed it off.

2418
02:18:40,708 --> 02:18:43,068
He has got friends in town.”

2419
02:18:43,068 --> 02:18:47,036
Perplexity knotted the Virginian’s brows.

2420
02:18:47,036 --> 02:18:51,651
This community knew that a man had
implied he was a thief and a murderer;

2421
02:18:51,651 --> 02:18:53,488
it also knew that he knew it.

2422
02:18:53,488 --> 02:18:58,514
But the case was one of
peculiar circumstances, assuredly.

2423
02:18:58,514 --> 02:19:00,504
Could he avoid meeting the man?

2424
02:19:00,504 --> 02:19:04,600
Soon the stage would be starting
south for the railroad.

2425
02:19:04,600 --> 02:19:08,681
He had already today proposed to his
sweetheart that they should take it.

2426
02:19:08,681 --> 02:19:13,309
Could he for her sake leave unanswered a
talking enemy upon the field?

2427
02:19:13,309 --> 02:19:15,374
His own ears had not heard the enemy.

2428
02:19:15,374 --> 02:19:18,888
Into these reflections the
fool stepped once more.

2429
02:19:18,888 --> 02:19:24,748
“Of course this country don’t
believe Trampas,” said he.

2430
02:19:24,748 --> 02:19:25,788
“This country⁠—”

2431
02:19:25,788 --> 02:19:28,619
But he contributed no further thoughts.

2432
02:19:28,619 --> 02:19:32,135
From somewhere in the rear of the
building, where it opened upon the tin

2433
02:19:32,135 --> 02:19:36,097
cans and the hinder purlieus of the
town, came a movement,

2434
02:19:36,097 --> 02:19:39,338
and Trampas was among
them, courageous with whiskey.

2435
02:19:39,338 --> 02:19:43,528
All the fools now made
themselves conspicuous.

2436
02:19:43,528 --> 02:19:47,493
One lay on the floor,
knocked there by the Virginian,

2437
02:19:47,493 --> 02:19:49,937
whose arm he had attempted to hold.

2438
02:19:49,937 --> 02:19:53,696
Others struggled with Trampas,
and his bullet smashed the ceiling

2439
02:19:53,696 --> 02:19:55,589
before they could drag
the pistol from him.

2440
02:19:55,589 --> 02:19:56,547
“There now!

2441
02:19:56,547 --> 02:19:58,195
there now!”

2442
02:19:58,195 --> 02:20:02,940
they interposed; “you don’t want to talk
like that,” for he was pouring out a

2443
02:20:02,940 --> 02:20:05,682
tide of hate and vilification.

2444
02:20:05,682 --> 02:20:09,963
Yet the Virginian stood quiet by the bar,
and many an eye of astonishment

2445
02:20:09,963 --> 02:20:11,293
was turned upon him.

2446
02:20:11,293 --> 02:20:15,303
“I’d not stand half that language,”
some muttered to each other.

2447
02:20:15,303 --> 02:20:21,184
Still the Virginian waited quietly,
while the fools reasoned with Trampas.

2448
02:20:21,184 --> 02:20:25,304
But no earthly foot can step between a
man and his destiny.

2449
02:20:25,304 --> 02:20:27,989
Trampas broke suddenly free.

2450
02:20:27,989 --> 02:20:33,754
“Your friends have saved your life,”
he rang out, with obscene epithets.

2451
02:20:33,754 --> 02:20:36,102
“I’ll give you till sundown
to leave town.”

2452
02:20:36,102 --> 02:20:38,206
There was total silence instantly.

2453
02:20:38,206 --> 02:20:42,922
“Trampas,” spoke the Virginian,
“I don’t want trouble with you.”

2454
02:20:42,922 --> 02:20:46,774
“He never has wanted it,”
Trampas sneered to the bystanders.

2455
02:20:46,774 --> 02:20:48,979
“He has been dodging it five years.

2456
02:20:48,979 --> 02:20:50,635
But I’ve got him coralled.”

2457
02:20:50,635 --> 02:20:53,243
Some of the Trampas faction smiled.

2458
02:20:53,243 --> 02:20:59,457
“Trampas,” said the Virginian again,
“are yu’ sure yu’ really mean that?”

2459
02:20:59,457 --> 02:21:05,853
The whiskey bottle flew through the air,
hurled by Trampas, and crashed through

2460
02:21:05,853 --> 02:21:08,684
the saloon window behind the Virginian.

2461
02:21:08,684 --> 02:21:12,969
“That was surplusage,
Trampas,” said he, “if

2462
02:21:12,969 --> 02:21:14,249
yu’ mean the other.”

2463
02:21:14,249 --> 02:21:17,570
“Get out by sundown, that’s
all,” said Trampas.

2464
02:21:17,570 --> 02:21:21,650
And wheeling, he went out of the saloon
by the rear, as he had entered.

2465
02:21:21,650 --> 02:21:25,594
“Gentlemen,” said the Virginian,
“I know you will all oblige me.”

2466
02:21:25,594 --> 02:21:26,514
“Sure!”

2467
02:21:26,514 --> 02:21:30,707
exclaimed the proprietor,
heartily, “We’ll see that everybody

2468
02:21:30,707 --> 02:21:32,315
lets this thing alone.”

2469
02:21:32,315 --> 02:21:37,592
The Virginian gave a general nod to the
company, and walked out into the street.

2470
02:21:37,592 --> 02:21:40,908
“It’s a turruble shame,”
sighed Scipio, “that he

2471
02:21:40,908 --> 02:21:42,864
couldn’t have postponed it.”

2472
02:21:42,864 --> 02:21:46,038
The Virginian walked in the open
air with thoughts disturbed.

2473
02:21:46,038 --> 02:21:49,853
“I am of two minds about one thing,”
he said to himself uneasily.

2474
02:21:49,853 --> 02:21:54,079
Gossip ran in advance of him;
but as he came by, the talk fell away

2475
02:21:54,079 --> 02:21:55,498
until he had passed.

2476
02:21:55,498 --> 02:22:00,029
Then they looked after him,
and their words again rose audibly.

2477
02:22:00,029 --> 02:22:04,402
Thus everywhere a little eddy of
silence accompanied his steps.

2478
02:22:04,402 --> 02:22:08,516
“It don’t trouble him much,”
one said, having read nothing

2479
02:22:08,516 --> 02:22:10,116
in the Virginian’s face.

2480
02:22:10,116 --> 02:22:13,088
“It may trouble his girl
some,” said another.

2481
02:22:13,088 --> 02:22:17,736
“She’ll not know,” said a
third, “until it’s over.”

2482
02:22:17,736 --> 02:22:19,576
“He’ll not tell her?”

2483
02:22:19,576 --> 02:22:21,166
“I wouldn’t.

2484
02:22:21,166 --> 02:22:22,729
It’s no woman’s business.”

2485
02:22:22,729 --> 02:22:23,868
“Maybe that’s so.

2486
02:22:23,868 --> 02:22:27,646
Well, it would have suited me to
have Trampas die sooner.”

2487
02:22:27,646 --> 02:22:30,167
“How would it suit you to
have him live longer?”

2488
02:22:30,167 --> 02:22:33,439
inquired a member of the opposite
faction, suspected of being

2489
02:22:33,439 --> 02:22:34,846
himself a cattle thief.

2490
02:22:34,846 --> 02:22:38,838
“I could answer your question,
if I had other folks’ calves

2491
02:22:38,838 --> 02:22:40,521
I wanted to brand.”

2492
02:22:40,521 --> 02:22:43,942
This raised both a laugh and a silence.

2493
02:22:43,942 --> 02:22:47,519
Thus the town talked,
filling in the time before sunset.

2494
02:22:47,519 --> 02:22:52,404
The Virginian, still walking aloof in the
open air, paused at the edge of the

2495
02:22:52,404 --> 02:22:52,942
town.

2496
02:22:52,942 --> 02:22:56,392
“I’d sooner have a sickness than be
undecided this way,”

2497
02:22:56,392 --> 02:22:58,780
he said, and he looked up and down.

2498
02:22:58,780 --> 02:23:01,938
Then a grim smile came at his own expense.

2499
02:23:01,938 --> 02:23:04,976
“I reckon it would make me sick⁠—
but there’s not time.”

2500
02:23:04,976 --> 02:23:09,509
Over there in the hotel sat his
sweetheart alone, away from her mother,

2501
02:23:09,509 --> 02:23:14,220
her friends, her home,
waiting his return, knowing nothing.

2502
02:23:14,220 --> 02:23:15,700
He looked into the west.

2503
02:23:15,700 --> 02:23:21,668
Between the sun and the bright ridges of
the mountains was still a space of sky;

2504
02:23:21,668 --> 02:23:26,772
but the shadow from the mountains’ feet
had drawn halfway toward the town.

2505
02:23:26,772 --> 02:23:29,889
“About forty minutes more,” he said aloud.

2506
02:23:29,889 --> 02:23:32,527
“She has been raised so different.”

2507
02:23:32,527 --> 02:23:34,450
And he sighed as he turned back.

2508
02:23:34,450 --> 02:23:39,191
As he went slowly, he did not know how
great was his own unhappiness.

2509
02:23:39,191 --> 02:23:43,567
“She has been raised so
different,” he said again.

2510
02:23:43,567 --> 02:23:48,752
Opposite the post-office the bishop of
Wyoming met him and greeted him.

2511
02:23:48,752 --> 02:23:55,190
His lonely heart throbbed at the warm,
firm grasp of this friend’s hand.

2512
02:23:55,190 --> 02:23:59,900
The bishop saw his eyes glow suddenly,
as if tears were close.

2513
02:23:59,900 --> -1:59:59,000
But none came, and no word more open
than, “I’m glad to see you.

2514
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

2515
02:24:04,070 --> 02:24:08,939
But gossip had reached the bishop,
and he was sorely troubled also.

2516
02:24:08,939 --> 02:24:11,870
“What is all this?”

2517
02:24:11,870 --> 02:24:14,704
said he, coming straight to it.

2518
02:24:14,704 --> 02:24:18,572
The Virginian looked at
the clergyman frankly.

2519
02:24:18,572 --> 02:24:22,222
“Yu’ know just as much about it as
I do,” he said.

2520
02:24:22,222 --> 02:24:25,524
“And I’ll tell yu’ anything yu’ ask.”

2521
02:24:25,524 --> 02:24:27,650
“Have you told Miss Wood?”

2522
02:24:27,650 --> 02:24:28,788
inquired the bishop.

2523
02:24:28,788 --> 02:24:33,265
The eyes of the bridegroom fell,
and the bishop’s face grew at once more

2524
02:24:33,265 --> 02:24:34,953
keen and more troubled.

2525
02:24:34,953 --> 02:24:39,276
Then the bridegroom raised his eyes
again, and the bishop almost loved him.

2526
02:24:39,276 --> 02:24:41,471
He touched his arm, like a brother.

2527
02:24:41,471 --> 02:24:43,320
“This is hard luck,” he said.

2528
02:24:43,320 --> 02:24:46,584
The bridegroom could scarce
keep his voice steady.

2529
02:24:46,584 --> 02:24:52,722
“I want to do right today more than any
day I have ever lived,” said he.

2530
02:24:52,722 --> 02:24:54,674
“Then go and tell her at once.”

2531
02:24:54,674 --> 02:24:57,414
“It will just do nothing but scare her.”

2532
02:24:57,414 --> -1:59:59,000
“Go and tell her at once.

2533
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

2534
02:24:59,279 --> 02:25:03,090
“I expected you was going to tell me to
run away from Trampas.

2535
02:25:03,090 --> 02:25:04,515
I can’t do that, yu’ know.”

2536
02:25:04,515 --> 02:25:06,013
The bishop did know.

2537
02:25:06,013 --> 02:25:10,077
Never before in all his wilderness work
had he faced such a thing.

2538
02:25:10,077 --> 02:25:13,065
He knew that Trampas was an evil in the
country, and that the

2539
02:25:13,065 --> 02:25:15,666
Virginian was a good.

2540
02:25:15,666 --> 02:25:20,194
He knew that the cattle thieves⁠—the
rustlers⁠—were gaining,

2541
02:25:20,194 --> 02:25:24,725
in numbers and audacity;
that they led many weak young fellows to

2542
02:25:24,725 --> 02:25:29,968
ruin; that they elected their men to
office, and controlled juries;

2543
02:25:29,968 --> 02:25:32,604
that they were a staring
menace to Wyoming.

2544
02:25:32,604 --> 02:25:35,359
His heart was with the Virginian.

2545
02:25:35,359 --> 02:25:40,302
But there was his Gospel,
that he preached, and believed,

2546
02:25:40,302 --> 02:25:41,691
and tried to live.

2547
02:25:41,691 --> 02:25:45,831
He stood looking at the ground and
drawing a finger along his eyebrow.

2548
02:25:45,831 --> 02:25:49,356
He wished that he might have heard
nothing about all this.

2549
02:25:49,356 --> 02:25:52,673
But he was not one to blink his
responsibility as a Christian server

2550
02:25:52,673 --> 02:25:54,283
of the church militant.

2551
02:25:54,283 --> 02:25:59,076
“Am I right,” he now slowly asked,
“in believing that you think I

2552
02:25:59,076 --> 02:26:00,396
am a sincere man?”

2553
02:26:00,396 --> 02:26:02,276
“I don’t believe anything about it.

2554
02:26:02,276 --> 02:26:03,276
I know it.”

2555
02:26:03,276 --> 02:26:06,743
“I should run away from
Trampas,” said the bishop.

2556
02:26:06,743 --> 02:26:08,676
“That ain’t quite fair, seh.

2557
02:26:08,676 --> 02:26:13,287
We all understand you have got to do the
things you tell other folks to do.

2558
02:26:13,287 --> 02:26:15,673
And you do them, seh.

2559
02:26:15,673 --> 02:26:20,208
You never talk like anything but a man,
and you never set yourself above others.

2560
02:26:20,208 --> 02:26:22,765
You can saddle your own horses.

2561
02:26:22,765 --> 02:26:26,790
And I saw yu’ walk unarmed into that
White River excitement when those two

2562
02:26:26,790 --> 02:26:31,811
other parsons was a-foggin’ and a-
fannin’ for their own safety.

2563
02:26:31,811 --> 02:26:33,353
Damn scoundrels!”

2564
02:26:33,353 --> 02:26:37,713
The bishop instantly rebuked such
language about brothers of his cloth,

2565
02:26:37,713 --> 02:26:40,971
even though he disapproved both of
them and their doctrines.

2566
02:26:40,971 --> 02:26:44,484
“Everyone may be an instrument
of Providence,” he concluded.

2567
02:26:44,484 --> 02:26:49,594
“Well,” said the Virginian,
“if that is so, then Providence makes

2568
02:26:49,594 --> 02:26:53,549
use of instruments I’d not touch with
a ten-foot pole.

2569
02:26:53,549 --> 02:26:57,379
Now if you was me, seh,
and not a bishop, would you

2570
02:26:57,379 --> -1:59:59,000
run away from Trampas?

2571
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

2572
02:26:59,492 --> 02:27:01,982
“That’s not quite fair, either!”

2573
02:27:01,982 --> 02:27:03,710
exclaimed the bishop, with a smile.

2574
02:27:03,710 --> 02:27:06,403
“Because you are asking me to take
another man’s convictions,

2575
02:27:06,403 --> 02:27:07,803
and yet remain myself.”

2576
02:27:07,803 --> 02:27:08,843
“Yes, seh.

2577
02:27:08,843 --> 02:27:10,145
I am.

2578
02:27:10,145 --> 02:27:12,123
That’s so.

2579
02:27:12,123 --> 02:27:13,934
That don’t get at it.

2580
02:27:13,934 --> 02:27:16,436
I reckon you and I can’t get at it.”

2581
02:27:16,436 --> 02:27:20,514
“If the Bible,” said the bishop,
“which I believe to be God’s word,

2582
02:27:20,514 --> 02:27:21,954
was anything to you⁠—”

2583
02:27:21,954 --> 02:27:23,554
“It is something to me, seh.

2584
02:27:23,554 --> 02:27:26,136
I have found fine truths in it.”

2585
02:27:26,136 --> 02:27:28,830
“ ‘Thou shalt not kill,’
” quoted the bishop.

2586
02:27:28,830 --> 02:27:29,813
“That is plain.”

2587
02:27:29,813 --> 02:27:32,240
The Virginian took his turn at smiling.

2588
02:27:32,240 --> 02:27:34,235
“Mighty plain to me, seh.

2589
02:27:34,235 --> 02:27:37,499
Make it plain to Trampas,
and there’ll be no killin’.

2590
02:27:37,499 --> 02:27:39,318
We can’t get at it that way.”

2591
02:27:39,318 --> 02:27:41,716
Once more the bishop quoted earnestly.

2592
02:27:41,716 --> -1:59:59,000
“ ‘Vengeance is mine,
I will repay, saith the Lord.’

2593
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

2594
02:27:45,614 --> 02:27:48,319
“How about instruments of Providence, seh?

2595
02:27:48,319 --> 02:27:50,263
Why, we can’t get at it that way.

2596
02:27:50,263 --> 02:27:54,998
If you start usin’ the Bible that way,
it will mix you up mighty quick, seh.”

2597
02:27:54,998 --> 02:28:00,605
“My friend,” the bishop urged,
and all his good, warm heart was in it,

2598
02:28:00,605 --> 02:28:04,086
“my dear fellow⁠—go away
for the one night.

2599
02:28:04,086 --> 02:28:05,528
He’ll change his mind.”

2600
02:28:05,528 --> 02:28:07,288
The Virginian shook his head.

2601
02:28:07,288 --> 02:28:10,016
“He cannot change his word, seh.

2602
02:28:10,016 --> 02:28:12,576
Or at least I must stay
around till he does.

2603
02:28:12,576 --> 02:28:15,418
Why, I have given him the say-so.

2604
02:28:15,418 --> 02:28:16,893
He’s got the choice.

2605
02:28:16,893 --> 02:28:22,024
Most men would not have took what I took
from him in the saloon.

2606
02:28:22,024 --> 02:28:24,358
Why don’t you ask him to leave town?”

2607
02:28:24,358 --> 02:28:26,484
The good bishop was at a standstill.

2608
02:28:26,484 --> 02:28:32,994
Of all kicking against the pricks none is
so hard as this kick of a professing

2609
02:28:32,994 --> 02:28:36,007
Christian against the whole
instinct of human man.

2610
02:28:36,007 --> 02:28:39,361
“But you have helped me
some,” said the Virginian.

2611
02:28:39,361 --> 02:28:41,894
“I will go and tell her.

2612
02:28:41,894 --> 02:28:45,971
At least, if I think it will be good for
her, I will tell her.”

2613
02:28:45,971 --> 02:28:49,195
The bishop thought that he saw one last
chance to move him.

2614
02:28:49,195 --> 02:28:53,122
“You’re twenty-nine,” he began.

2615
02:28:53,122 --> 02:28:55,735
“And a little over,” said the Virginian.

2616
02:28:55,735 --> 02:28:58,893
“And you were fourteen when you ran
away from your family.”

2617
02:28:58,893 --> 02:29:05,652
“Well, I was weary, yu’ know,
of havin’ elder brothers lay down my

2618
02:29:05,652 --> 02:29:08,206
law night and mawnin’.”

2619
02:29:08,206 --> 02:29:10,120
“Yes, I know.

2620
02:29:10,120 --> 02:29:14,049
So that your life has been your
own for fifteen years.

2621
02:29:14,049 --> 02:29:16,063
But it is not your own now.

2622
02:29:16,063 --> 02:29:17,688
You have given it to a woman.”

2623
02:29:17,688 --> 02:29:20,151
“Yes; I have given it to her.

2624
02:29:20,151 --> 02:29:23,394
But my life’s not the whole of me.

2625
02:29:23,394 --> 02:29:26,243
I’d give her twice my life⁠—fifty⁠—
a thousand of ’em.

2626
02:29:26,243 --> 02:29:32,888
But I can’t give her⁠—her nor anybody in
heaven or earth⁠—I can’t give my⁠—my⁠—

2627
02:29:32,888 --> 02:29:34,715
we’ll never get at it, seh!

2628
02:29:34,715 --> 02:29:37,071
There’s no good in words.

2629
02:29:37,071 --> 02:29:37,727
Goodbye.”

2630
02:29:37,727 --> 02:29:41,713
The Virginian wrung the bishop’s
hand and left him.

2631
02:29:41,713 --> 02:29:43,107
“God bless him!”

2632
02:29:43,107 --> 02:29:44,196
said the bishop.

2633
02:29:44,196 --> 02:29:45,640
“God bless him!”

2634
02:29:45,640 --> 02:29:50,918
The Virginian unlocked the room in the
hotel where he kept stored his tent,

2635
02:29:50,918 --> 02:29:54,427
his blankets, his packsaddles,
and his many accoutrements for the

2636
02:29:54,427 --> 02:29:56,186
bridal journey in the mountains.

2637
02:29:56,186 --> 02:30:01,549
Out of the window he saw the mountains
blue in shadow, but some cottonwoods

2638
02:30:01,549 --> 02:30:05,936
distant in the flat between were still
bright green in the sun.

2639
02:30:05,936 --> 02:30:10,108
From among his possessions he took
quickly a pistol, wiping and loading it.

2640
02:30:10,108 --> 02:30:15,488
Then from its holster he removed the
pistol which he had tried and made sure

2641
02:30:15,488 --> 02:30:16,951
of in the morning.

2642
02:30:16,951 --> 02:30:22,695
This, according to his wont when going
into a risk, he shoved between his

2643
02:30:22,695 --> 02:30:24,968
trousers and his shirt in front.

2644
02:30:24,968 --> 02:30:28,334
The untried weapon he placed in the
holster, letting it hang

2645
02:30:28,334 --> 02:30:29,834
visibly at his hip.

2646
02:30:29,834 --> 02:30:33,025
He glanced out of the window again,
and saw the mountains of

2647
02:30:33,025 --> 02:30:34,630
the same deep blue.

2648
02:30:34,630 --> 02:30:39,017
But the cottonwoods were no
longer in the sunlight.

2649
02:30:39,017 --> 02:30:43,220
The shadow had come past them,
nearer the town; for fifteen of the

2650
02:30:43,220 --> 02:30:44,726
forty minutes were gone.

2651
02:30:44,726 --> 02:30:46,437
“The bishop is wrong,” he said.

2652
02:30:46,437 --> 02:30:48,373
“There is no sense in telling her.”

2653
02:30:48,373 --> 02:30:52,019
And he turned to the door,
just as she came to it herself.

2654
02:30:52,019 --> 02:30:52,541
“Oh!”

2655
02:30:52,541 --> 02:30:54,883
she cried out at once, and rushed to him.

2656
02:30:54,883 --> 02:30:57,095
He swore as he held her close.

2657
02:30:57,095 --> 02:30:58,856
“The fools!”

2658
02:30:58,856 --> 02:30:59,550
he said.

2659
02:30:59,550 --> 02:31:00,651
“The fools!”

2660
02:31:00,651 --> 02:31:04,291
“It has been so frightful waiting for
you,” said she, leaning

2661
02:31:04,291 --> 02:31:05,378
her head against him.

2662
02:31:05,378 --> 02:31:07,349
“Who had to tell you this?”

2663
02:31:07,349 --> 02:31:08,256
he demanded.

2664
02:31:08,256 --> 02:31:09,517
“I don’t know.

2665
02:31:09,517 --> 02:31:11,285
Somebody just came and said it.”

2666
02:31:11,285 --> 02:31:13,930
“This is mean luck,” he
murmured, patting her.

2667
02:31:13,930 --> 02:31:15,205
“This is mean luck.”

2668
02:31:15,205 --> 02:31:20,486
She went on: “I wanted to run out and
find you; but I didn’t!

2669
02:31:20,486 --> 02:31:23,830
I didn’t!

2670
02:31:23,830 --> 02:31:29,082
I stayed quiet in my room till they said
you had come back.”

2671
02:31:29,082 --> 02:31:31,144
“It is mean luck.

2672
02:31:31,144 --> 02:31:33,195
Mighty mean,” he repeated.

2673
02:31:33,195 --> 02:31:34,731
“How could you be so long?”

2674
02:31:34,731 --> 02:31:35,921
she asked.

2675
02:31:35,921 --> 02:31:38,156
“Never mind, I’ve got you now.

2676
02:31:38,156 --> 02:31:39,516
It is over.”

2677
02:31:39,516 --> 02:31:42,458
Anger and sorrow filled him.

2678
02:31:42,458 --> 02:31:45,834
“I might have known some fool would
tell you,” he said.

2679
02:31:45,834 --> 02:31:47,298
“It’s all over.

2680
02:31:47,298 --> 02:31:51,591
Never mind.”

2681
02:31:51,591 --> 02:31:55,238
Her arms tightened their hold of him.

2682
02:31:55,238 --> 02:31:57,210
Then she let him go.

2683
02:31:57,210 --> 02:31:58,372
“What shall we do?”

2684
02:31:58,372 --> 02:31:59,232
she said.

2685
02:31:59,232 --> 02:32:00,728
“What now?”

2686
02:32:00,728 --> 02:32:01,580
“Now?”

2687
02:32:01,580 --> 02:32:02,546
he answered.

2688
02:32:02,546 --> 02:32:03,797
“Nothing now.”

2689
02:32:03,797 --> 02:32:06,726
She looked at him without understanding.

2690
02:32:06,726 --> 02:32:11,056
“I know it is a heap worse for you,”
he pursued, speaking slowly.

2691
02:32:11,056 --> 02:32:12,406
“I knew it would be.”

2692
02:32:12,406 --> 02:32:13,791
“But it is over!”

2693
02:32:13,791 --> 02:32:15,040
she exclaimed again.

2694
02:32:15,040 --> 02:32:17,216
He did not understand her now.

2695
02:32:17,216 --> 02:32:19,246
He kissed her.

2696
02:32:19,246 --> 02:32:22,007
“Did you think it was over?”

2697
02:32:22,007 --> 02:32:24,590
he said simply.

2698
02:32:24,590 --> 02:32:27,036
“There is some waiting still before us.

2699
02:32:27,036 --> 02:32:29,308
I wish you did not have to wait alone.

2700
02:32:29,308 --> 02:32:30,603
But it will not be long.”

2701
02:32:30,603 --> 02:32:36,316
He was looking down, and did not see the
happiness grow chilled upon her face,

2702
02:32:36,316 --> 02:32:38,563
and then fade into bewildered fear.

2703
02:32:38,563 --> 02:32:41,357
“I did my best,” he went on.

2704
02:32:41,357 --> 02:32:42,856
“I think I did.

2705
02:32:42,856 --> 02:32:44,261
I know I tried.

2706
02:32:44,261 --> 02:32:49,197
I let him say to me before them all what
no man has ever said, or ever will

2707
02:32:49,197 --> 02:32:49,800
again.

2708
02:32:49,800 --> 02:32:53,552
I kept thinking hard of you⁠—with all my
might, or I reckon I’d have

2709
02:32:53,552 --> 02:32:54,497
killed him right there.

2710
02:32:54,497 --> 02:32:58,026
And I gave him a show to change his mind.

2711
02:32:58,026 --> 02:33:00,817
I gave it to him twice.

2712
02:33:00,817 --> 02:33:03,907
I spoke as quiet as I am
speaking to you now.

2713
02:33:03,907 --> 02:33:04,922
But he stood to it.

2714
02:33:04,922 --> 02:33:09,809
And I expect he knows he went too far in
the hearing of others to go

2715
02:33:09,809 --> 02:33:10,950
back on his threat.

2716
02:33:10,950 --> -1:59:59,000
He will have to go on to the finish now.

2717
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

2718
02:33:13,649 --> 02:33:15,231
“The finish?”

2719
02:33:15,231 --> 02:33:17,763
she echoed, almost voiceless.

2720
02:33:17,763 --> 02:33:20,840
“Yes,” he answered very gently.

2721
02:33:20,840 --> 02:33:24,697
Her dilated eyes were fixed upon him.

2722
02:33:24,697 --> 02:33:28,989
“But⁠—” she could scarce
form utterance, “but you?”

2723
02:33:28,989 --> 02:33:32,515
“I have got myself ready,” he said.

2724
02:33:32,515 --> 02:33:36,771
“Did you think⁠—why, what did you think?”

2725
02:33:36,771 --> 02:33:38,074
She recoiled a step.

2726
02:33:38,074 --> 02:33:41,285
“What are you going⁠—” She put her two
hands to her head.

2727
02:33:41,285 --> 02:33:42,826
“Oh, God!”

2728
02:33:42,826 --> 02:33:45,330
she almost shrieked, “you are going⁠—”

2729
02:33:45,330 --> 02:33:49,628
He made a step, and would have put his
arm round her, but she backed against

2730
02:33:49,628 --> 02:33:52,887
the wall, staring speechless at him.

2731
02:33:52,887 --> 02:33:57,222
“I am not going to let him shoot
me,” he said quietly.

2732
02:33:57,222 --> 02:34:00,374
“You mean⁠—you mean⁠—but
you can come away!”

2733
02:34:00,374 --> 02:34:01,147
she cried.

2734
02:34:01,147 --> 02:34:02,647
“It’s not too late yet.

2735
02:34:02,647 --> 02:34:05,278
You can take yourself out of his reach.

2736
02:34:05,278 --> 02:34:07,818
Everybody knows that you are brave.

2737
02:34:07,818 --> 02:34:09,524
What is he to you?

2738
02:34:09,524 --> 02:34:11,592
You can leave him in this place.

2739
02:34:11,592 --> 02:34:13,240
I’ll go with you anywhere.

2740
02:34:13,240 --> 02:34:18,236
To any house, to the mountains,
to anywhere away.

2741
02:34:18,236 --> 02:34:22,708
We’ll leave this horrible place together
and⁠—and⁠—oh, won’t you listen to me?”

2742
02:34:22,708 --> 02:34:24,260
She stretched her hands to him.

2743
02:34:24,260 --> 02:34:25,159
“Won’t you listen?”

2744
02:34:25,159 --> 02:34:26,432
He took her hands.

2745
02:34:26,432 --> 02:34:28,005
“I must stay here.”

2746
02:34:28,005 --> 02:34:29,768
Her hands clung to his.

2747
02:34:29,768 --> 02:34:32,735
“No, no, no.

2748
02:34:32,735 --> 02:34:33,925
There’s something else.

2749
02:34:33,925 --> 02:34:37,104
There’s something better than shedding
blood in cold blood.

2750
02:34:37,104 --> 02:34:39,791
Only think what it means!

2751
02:34:39,791 --> 02:34:42,396
Only think of having to
remember such a thing!

2752
02:34:42,396 --> 02:34:45,148
Why, it’s what they hang people for!

2753
02:34:45,148 --> 02:34:46,120
It’s murder!”

2754
02:34:46,120 --> 02:34:47,533
He dropped her hands.

2755
02:34:47,533 --> 02:34:50,153
“Don’t call it that name,”
he said sternly.

2756
02:34:50,153 --> 02:34:51,629
“When there was the choice!”

2757
02:34:51,629 --> 02:34:55,923
she exclaimed, half to herself,
like a person stunned and

2758
02:34:55,923 --> 02:34:57,120
speaking to the air.

2759
02:34:57,120 --> 02:34:59,778
“To get ready for it when
you have the choice!”

2760
02:34:59,778 --> 02:35:02,595
“He did the choosing,”
answered the Virginian.

2761
02:35:02,595 --> 02:35:03,717
“Listen to me.

2762
02:35:03,717 --> 02:35:05,452
Are you listening?”

2763
02:35:05,452 --> 02:35:08,030
he asked, for her gaze was dull.

2764
02:35:08,030 --> 02:35:09,362
She nodded.

2765
02:35:09,362 --> 02:35:12,262
“I work hyeh.

2766
02:35:12,262 --> 02:35:13,992
I belong hyeh.

2767
02:35:13,992 --> 02:35:15,308
It’s my life.

2768
02:35:15,308 --> 02:35:18,351
If folks came to think I was a coward⁠—”

2769
02:35:18,351 --> 02:35:20,468
“Who would think you were a coward?”

2770
02:35:20,468 --> 02:35:21,096
“Everybody.

2771
02:35:21,096 --> 02:35:25,788
My friends would be sorry and ashamed,
and my enemies would walk around saying

2772
02:35:25,788 --> 02:35:27,374
they had always said so.

2773
02:35:27,374 --> 02:35:30,739
I could not hold up my head again
among enemies or friends.”

2774
02:35:30,739 --> 02:35:31,989
“When it was explained⁠—”

2775
02:35:31,989 --> 02:35:33,950
“There’d be nothing to explain.

2776
02:35:33,950 --> 02:35:35,893
There’d just be the fact.”

2777
02:35:35,893 --> 02:35:37,023
He was nearly angry.

2778
02:35:37,023 --> 02:35:41,678
“There is a higher courage than fear of
outside opinion,” said

2779
02:35:41,678 --> 02:35:43,274
the New England girl.

2780
02:35:43,274 --> 02:35:46,316
Her Southern lover looked at her.

2781
02:35:46,316 --> 02:35:47,527
“Cert’nly there is.

2782
02:35:47,527 --> -1:59:59,000
That’s what I’m showing
in going against yours.

2783
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

2784
02:35:49,920 --> 02:35:53,753
“But if you know that you are brave,
and if I know that you are brave,

2785
02:35:53,753 --> 02:35:56,066
oh, my dear, my dear!

2786
02:35:56,066 --> 02:35:58,319
what difference does the world make?

2787
02:35:58,319 --> 02:36:01,300
How much higher courage to
go your own course⁠—”

2788
02:36:01,300 --> 02:36:04,683
“I am goin’ my own course,” he broke in.

2789
02:36:04,683 --> 02:36:07,866
“Can’t yu’ see how it must be about a man?

2790
02:36:07,866 --> 02:36:12,981
It’s not for their benefit,
friends or enemies, that I have got

2791
02:36:12,981 --> 02:36:14,248
this thing to do.

2792
02:36:14,248 --> 02:36:17,723
If any man happened to say I was a thief
and I heard about it,

2793
02:36:17,723 --> 02:36:20,580
would I let him go on spreadin’ such
a thing of me?

2794
02:36:20,580 --> 02:36:23,723
Don’t I owe my own honesty
something better than that?

2795
02:36:23,723 --> 02:36:29,333
Would I sit down in a corner rubbin’ my
honesty and whisperin’ to it, ‘There!

2796
02:36:29,333 --> 02:36:30,244
there!

2797
02:36:30,244 --> 02:36:31,458
I know you ain’t a thief?’

2798
02:36:31,458 --> 02:36:33,484
No, seh; not a little bit!

2799
02:36:33,484 --> 02:36:37,810
What men say about my nature is not just
merely an outside thing.

2800
02:36:37,810 --> 02:36:42,617
For the fact that I let ’em keep on
sayin’ it is a proof I don’t value my

2801
02:36:42,617 --> 02:36:48,154
nature enough to shield it from their
slander and give them their punishment.

2802
02:36:48,154 --> -1:59:59,000
And that’s being a poor sort of a jay.

2803
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

2804
02:36:50,396 --> 02:36:52,026
She had grown very white.

2805
02:36:52,026 --> 02:36:54,308
“Can’t yu’ see how it must
be about a man?”

2806
02:36:54,308 --> 02:36:55,501
he repeated.

2807
02:36:55,501 --> 02:37:00,826
“I cannot,” she answered,
in a voice that scarcely seemed her own.

2808
02:37:00,826 --> 02:37:02,491
“If I ought to, I cannot.

2809
02:37:02,491 --> 02:37:06,672
To shed blood in cold blood.

2810
02:37:06,672 --> 02:37:12,092
When I heard about that last fall⁠—about
the killing of those cattle thieves⁠—I

2811
02:37:12,092 --> 02:37:15,807
kept saying to myself: ‘He had to do it.

2812
02:37:15,807 --> 02:37:18,574
It was a public duty.’

2813
02:37:18,574 --> 02:37:23,628
And lying sleepless I got used to Wyoming
being different from Vermont.

2814
02:37:23,628 --> 02:37:28,734
But this⁠—” she gave a shudder⁠—“when I
think of tomorrow, of you and me,

2815
02:37:28,734 --> -1:59:59,000
and of⁠—If you do this,
there can be no tomorrow for you and me.

2816
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
”

2817
02:37:32,895 --> 02:37:36,209
At these words he also turned white.

2818
02:37:36,209 --> 02:37:39,556
“Do you mean⁠—” he asked,
and could go no farther.

2819
02:37:39,556 --> 02:37:43,276
Nor could she answer him,
but turned her head away.

2820
02:37:43,276 --> 02:37:44,990
“This would be the end?”

2821
02:37:44,990 --> 02:37:46,097
he asked.

2822
02:37:46,097 --> 02:37:49,097
Her head faintly moved to signify yes.

2823
02:37:49,097 --> 02:37:52,353
He stood still, his hand shaking a little.

2824
02:37:52,353 --> 02:37:54,206
“Will you look at me and say that?”

2825
02:37:54,206 --> 02:37:55,275
he murmured at length.

2826
02:37:55,275 --> 02:37:56,644
She did not move.

2827
02:37:56,644 --> 02:37:57,627
“Can you do it?”

2828
02:37:57,627 --> 02:37:58,374
he said.

2829
02:37:58,374 --> 02:38:02,470
His sweetness made her turn,
but could not pierce her frozen resolve.

2830
02:38:02,470 --> 02:38:06,540
She gazed at him across the great
distance of her despair.

2831
02:38:06,540 --> 02:38:08,430
“Then it is really so?”

2832
02:38:08,430 --> 02:38:09,145
he said.

2833
02:38:09,145 --> 02:38:12,007
Her lips tried to form words, but failed.

2834
02:38:12,007 --> 02:38:15,370
He looked out of the window,
and saw nothing but shadow.

2835
02:38:15,370 --> 02:38:19,319
The blue of the mountains was now
become a deep purple.

2836
02:38:19,319 --> 02:38:21,964
Suddenly his hand closed hard.

2837
02:38:21,964 --> 02:38:23,925
“Goodbye, then,” he said.

2838
02:38:23,925 --> 02:38:26,960
At that word she was at
his feet, clutching him.

2839
02:38:26,960 --> 02:38:28,952
“For my sake,” she begged him.

2840
02:38:28,952 --> 02:38:30,175
“For my sake.”

2841
02:38:30,175 --> 02:38:32,909
A tremble passed through his frame.

2842
02:38:32,909 --> 02:38:37,137
She felt his legs shake as she held them,
and, looking up, she saw that his eyes

2843
02:38:37,137 --> 02:38:39,090
were closed with misery.

2844
02:38:39,090 --> 02:38:42,303
Then he opened them, and in their steady
look she read her answer.

2845
02:38:42,303 --> 02:38:46,744
He unclasped her hands from holding him,
and raised her to her feet.

2846
02:38:46,744 --> 02:38:52,485
“I have no right to kiss you
any more,” he said.

2847
02:38:52,485 --> 02:38:58,865
And then, before his desire could break
him down from this, he was gone,

2848
02:38:58,865 --> 02:38:59,776
and she was alone.

2849
02:38:59,776 --> 02:39:03,278
She did not fall, or totter,
but stood motionless.

2850
02:39:03,278 --> 02:39:07,478
And next⁠—it seemed a moment and it
seemed eternity⁠—she heard in the

2851
02:39:07,478 --> 02:39:10,751
distance a shot, and then two shots.

2852
02:39:10,751 --> 02:39:14,124
Out of the window she saw
people beginning to run.

2853
02:39:14,124 --> 02:39:18,111
At that she turned and fled to her room,
and flung herself face

2854
02:39:18,111 --> 02:39:19,859
downward upon the floor.

2855
02:39:19,859 --> 02:39:24,271
Trampas had departed into solitude from
the saloon, leaving behind

2856
02:39:24,271 --> 02:39:26,067
him his ultimatum.

2857
02:39:26,067 --> 02:39:32,111
His loud and public threat was town
knowledge already, would very likely

2858
02:39:32,111 --> 02:39:34,334
be county knowledge tonight.

2859
02:39:34,334 --> 02:39:39,605
Riders would take it with them to
entertain distant cabins up the river

2860
02:39:39,605 --> 02:39:44,345
and down the river; and by dark the
stage would go south with the news of

2861
02:39:44,345 --> 02:39:47,289
it⁠—and the news of its outcome.

2862
02:39:47,289 --> 02:39:50,460
For everything would be over by dark.

2863
02:39:50,460 --> -1:59:59,000
After five years, here was the end
coming⁠—coming before dark

2864
-1:59:59,000 --> 00:00:02,000
.

2865
02:39:56,208 --> 02:39:59,713
Trampas had got up this morning
with no such thought.

2866
02:39:59,713 --> 02:40:03,283
It seemed very strange to look back upon
the morning; it lay so

2867
02:40:03,283 --> 02:40:05,534
distant, so irrevocable.

2868
02:40:05,534 --> 02:40:08,637
And he thought of how he
had eaten his breakfast.

2869
02:40:08,637 --> 02:40:10,375
How would he eat his supper?

2870
02:40:10,375 --> 02:40:13,662
For supper would come afterward.

2871
02:40:13,662 --> 02:40:17,080
Some people were eating theirs now,
with nothing like this before them.

2872
02:40:17,080 --> 02:40:21,961
His heart ached and grew cold to think of
them, easy and comfortable with plates

2873
02:40:21,961 --> 02:40:23,390
and cups of coffee.

2874
02:40:23,390 --> 02:40:26,984
He looked at the mountains,
and saw the sun above their ridges,

2875
02:40:26,984 --> 02:40:29,183
and the shadow coming from their feet.

2876
02:40:29,183 --> 02:40:33,371
And there close behind him was the
morning he could never go back to.

2877
02:40:33,371 --> 02:40:36,703
He could see it clearly;
his thoughts reached out like arms to

2878
02:40:36,703 --> 02:40:40,200
touch it once more, and be in it again.

2879
02:40:40,200 --> 02:40:44,207
The night that was coming he could not
see, and his eyes and his

2880
02:40:44,207 --> 02:40:45,806
thoughts shrank from it.

2881
02:40:45,806 --> 02:40:48,686
He had given his enemy until sundown.

2882
02:40:48,686 --> 02:40:52,762
He could not trace the path which had
led him to this.

2883
02:40:52,762 --> 02:40:57,144
He remembered their first meeting⁠—five
years back, in Medicine Bow,

2884
02:40:57,144 --> 02:41:00,218
and the words which at
once began his hate.

2885
02:41:00,218 --> 02:41:05,523
No, it was before any words;
it was the encounter of their eyes.

2886
02:41:05,523 --> 02:41:11,160
For out of the eyes of every stranger
looks either a friend or an enemy,

2887
02:41:11,160 --> 02:41:12,342
waiting to be known.

2888
02:41:12,342 --> 02:41:17,434
But how had five years of hate come to
play him such a trick, suddenly, today?

2889
02:41:17,434 --> 02:41:21,160
Since last autumn he had meant sometime
to get even with this man who seemed to

2890
02:41:21,160 --> 02:41:25,737
stand at every turn of his crookedness,
and rob him of his spoils.

2891
02:41:25,737 --> 02:41:32,338
But how had he come to choose such a way
of getting even as this, face to face?

2892
02:41:32,338 --> 02:41:34,909
He knew many better ways;
and now his own rash

2893
02:41:34,909 --> 02:41:36,332
proclamation had trapped him.

2894
02:41:36,332 --> 02:41:41,861
His words were like doors shutting him in
to perform his threat to the letter,

2895
02:41:41,861 --> 02:41:45,252
with witnesses at hand to see
that he did so.

2896
02:41:45,252 --> 02:41:48,652
Trampas looked at the sun
and the shadow again.

2897
02:41:48,652 --> 02:41:50,889
He had till sundown.

2898
02:41:50,889 --> 02:41:54,821
The heart inside him was turning it round
in this opposite way:

2899
02:41:54,821 --> 02:42:00,836
it was to himself that in his rage he
had given this lessening margin of

2900
02:42:00,836 --> 02:42:02,026
grace.

2901
02:42:02,026 --> 02:42:05,426
But he dared not leave town in all the
world’s sight after all the

2902
02:42:05,426 --> 02:42:06,619
world had heard him.

2903
02:42:06,619 --> 02:42:11,441
Even his friends would fall from him
after such an act.

2904
02:42:11,441 --> 02:42:16,008
Could he⁠—the thought actually came to
him⁠—could he strike before the time

2905
02:42:16,008 --> 02:42:16,848
set?

2906
02:42:16,848 --> 02:42:18,950
But the thought was useless.

2907
02:42:18,950 --> 02:42:23,794
Even if his friends could harbor him
after such a deed, his enemies would

2908
02:42:23,794 --> 02:42:29,100
find him, and his life would be
forfeit to a certainty.

2909
02:42:29,100 --> 02:42:32,543
His own trap was closing upon him.

2910
02:42:32,543 --> 02:42:36,595
He came upon the main street,
and saw some distance off the Virginian

2911
02:42:36,595 --> 02:42:38,580
standing in talk with the bishop.

2912
02:42:38,580 --> 02:42:42,466
He slunk between two houses,
and cursed both of them.

2913
02:42:42,466 --> 02:42:46,799
The sight had been good for him,
bringing some warmth of rage back

2914
02:42:46,799 --> 02:42:48,004
to his desperate heart.

2915
02:42:48,004 --> 02:42:51,239
And he went into a place
and drank some whiskey.

2916
02:42:51,239 --> 02:42:56,654
“In your shoes,” said the barkeeper,
“I’d be afraid to take so much.”

2917
02:42:56,654 --> 02:43:02,728
But the nerves of Trampas were almost
beyond the reach of intoxication,

2918
02:43:02,728 --> 02:43:06,350
and he swallowed some more,
and went out again.

2919
02:43:06,350 --> 02:43:09,982
Presently he fell in with some of his
brothers in cattle stealing,

2920
02:43:09,982 --> 02:43:11,874
and walked along with them for a little.

2921
02:43:11,874 --> 02:43:14,972
“Well, it will not be long now,”
they said to him.

2922
02:43:14,972 --> 02:43:17,457
And he had never heard words so desolate.

2923
02:43:17,457 --> 02:43:20,373
“No,” he made out to say; “soon now.”

2924
02:43:20,373 --> 02:43:24,123
Their cheerfulness seemed unearthly to
him, and his heart almost

2925
02:43:24,123 --> 02:43:26,290
broke beneath it.

2926
02:43:26,290 --> 02:43:29,356
“We’ll have one to your
success,” they suggested.

2927
02:43:29,356 --> 02:43:33,447
So with them he repaired to another
place; and the sight of a man leaning

2928
02:43:33,447 --> 02:43:36,640
against the bar made him start so
that they noticed him.

2929
02:43:36,640 --> 02:43:41,951
Then he saw that the man was a stranger
whom he had never laid eyes on till now.

2930
02:43:41,951 --> 02:43:44,070
“It looked like Shorty,”
he said, and could have

2931
02:43:44,070 --> 02:43:45,231
bitten his tongue off.

2932
02:43:45,231 --> 02:43:48,622
“Shorty is quiet up in the
Tetons,” said a friend.

2933
02:43:48,622 --> 02:43:50,924
“You don’t want to be thinking about him.

2934
02:43:50,924 --> 02:43:51,840
Here’s how!”

2935
02:43:51,840 --> 02:43:54,018
Then they clapped him on the back
and he left them.

2936
02:43:54,018 --> 02:43:59,382
He thought of his enemy and his hate,
beating his rage like a failing horse,

2937
02:43:59,382 --> 02:44:01,564
and treading the courage of his drink.

2938
02:44:01,564 --> 02:44:06,271
Across a space he saw Wiggin,
walking with McLean and Scipio.

2939
02:44:06,271 --> 02:44:11,825
They were watching the town to see that
his friends made no foul play.

2940
02:44:11,825 --> 02:44:14,822
“We’re giving you a clear
field,” said Wiggin.

2941
02:44:14,822 --> 02:44:18,226
“This race will not be
pulled,” said McLean.

2942
02:44:18,226 --> 02:44:20,855
“Be with you at the finish,” said Scipio.

2943
02:44:20,855 --> 02:44:23,089
And they passed on.

2944
02:44:23,089 --> 02:44:27,891
They did not seem like real people to him.

2945
02:44:27,891 --> 02:44:32,548
Trampas looked at the walls and
windows of the houses.

2946
02:44:32,548 --> 02:44:33,429
Were they real?

2947
02:44:33,429 --> 02:44:35,940
Was he here, walking in this street?

2948
02:44:35,940 --> 02:44:37,401
Something had changed.

2949
02:44:37,401 --> 02:44:40,672
He looked everywhere,
and feeling it everywhere,

2950
02:44:40,672 --> 02:44:42,367
wondered what this could be.

2951
02:44:42,367 --> 02:44:47,539
Then he knew: it was the sun that had
gone entirely behind the mountains,

2952
02:44:47,539 --> 02:44:49,092
and he drew out his pistol.

2953
02:44:49,092 --> 02:44:53,834
The Virginian, for precaution,
did not walk out of the front

2954
02:44:53,834 --> 02:44:54,832
door of the hotel.

2955
02:44:54,832 --> 02:44:57,547
He went through back ways,
and paused once.

2956
02:44:57,547 --> 02:45:02,803
Against his breast he felt the wedding
ring where he had it suspended by a

2957
02:45:02,803 --> 02:45:04,392
chain from his neck.

2958
02:45:04,392 --> 02:45:07,967
His hand went up to it,
and he drew it out and looked at it.

2959
02:45:07,967 --> 02:45:11,606
He took it off the chain,
and his arm went back to hurl it from

2960
02:45:11,606 --> 02:45:13,130
him as far as he could.

2961
02:45:13,130 --> 02:45:17,253
But he stopped and kissed it with one
sob, and thrust it in his pocket.

2962
02:45:17,253 --> 02:45:20,262
Then he walked out into
the open, watching.

2963
02:45:20,262 --> 02:45:23,705
He saw men here and there,
and they let him pass

2964
02:45:23,705 --> 02:45:26,401
as before, without speaking.

2965
02:45:26,401 --> 02:45:29,975
He saw his three friends,
and they said no word to him.

2966
02:45:29,975 --> 02:45:34,245
But they turned and followed in his rear
at a little distance,

2967
02:45:34,245 --> 02:45:38,538
because it was known that Shorty had
been found shot from behind.

2968
02:45:38,538 --> 02:45:43,123
The Virginian gained a position soon
where no one could come at him except

2969
02:45:43,123 --> 02:45:46,357
from in front; and the sight of the
mountains was almost more than he could

2970
02:45:46,357 --> 02:45:49,721
endure, because it was there that he
had been going tomorrow.

2971
02:45:49,721 --> 02:45:53,966
“It is quite a while after sunset,”
he heard himself say.

2972
02:45:53,966 --> 02:45:58,360
A wind seemed to blow his sleeve off his
arm, and he replied to it,

2973
02:45:58,360 --> 02:46:01,595
and saw Trampas pitch forward.

2974
02:46:01,595 --> 02:46:05,321
He saw Trampas raise his arm from the
ground and fall again,

2975
02:46:05,321 --> 02:46:07,545
and lie there this time, still.

2976
02:46:07,545 --> 02:46:12,336
A little smoke was rising from the pistol
on the ground, and he looked at his own,

2977
02:46:12,336 --> 02:46:15,822
and saw the smoke flowing
upward out of it.

2978
02:46:15,822 --> 02:46:18,452
“I expect that’s all,” he said aloud.

2979
02:46:18,452 --> 02:46:21,855
But as he came nearer Trampas,
he covered him with his weapon.

2980
02:46:21,855 --> 02:46:24,994
He stopped a moment, seeing the hand
on the ground move.

2981
02:46:24,994 --> 02:46:31,036
Two fingers twitched,
and then ceased; for it was all.

2982
02:46:31,036 --> 02:46:34,548
The Virginian stood looking
down at Trampas.

2983
02:46:34,548 --> 02:46:37,296
“Both of mine hit,” he
said, once more aloud.

2984
02:46:37,296 --> 02:46:42,010
“His must have gone mighty
close to my arm.

2985
02:46:42,010 --> 02:46:45,383
I told her it would not be me.”

2986
02:46:45,383 --> 02:46:49,667
He had scarcely noticed that he was
being surrounded and congratulated.

2987
02:46:49,667 --> 02:46:55,803
His hand was being shaken,
and he saw it was Scipio in tears.

2988
02:46:55,803 --> 02:47:00,553
Scipio’s joy made his heart
like lead within him.

2989
02:47:00,553 --> 02:47:04,403
He was near telling his friend
everything, but he did not.

2990
02:47:04,403 --> 02:47:08,539
“If anybody wants me about this,”
he said, “I will be at the hotel.”

2991
02:47:08,539 --> 02:47:09,779
“Who’ll want you?”

2992
02:47:09,779 --> 02:47:10,603
